<FIRST>r a AM-Novello-AIDS     10-23 0307</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Novello-AIDS,0315</SECOND>
<HEAD>Doctor Recommended for Surgeon General Warns AIDS Is Family Disease</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLEY SHANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A physician recommended for the U.S. Surgeon
General's post says the nation must begin thinking about AIDS as a
disease that strikes whole families, not just adults.
   ``We have to think of the children who will be sick,'' Dr.
Antonia C. Novello said Monday. ``...we also have to think of the
children who will be orphaned when the parents die. It's a family
context. If we think of AIDS in a family context, I think we will
be much more forceful.''
   Novello, 45, has been recommended by Dr. Louis Sullivan,
secretary of Health and Human Services, to succeed Dr. C. Everett
Koop as surgeon general. She is deputy director of the National
Institute of Child Health and Human Development at the National
Institutes of Health.
   Novello, a native of Puerto Rico, has yet to be nominated by
President Bush. She spoke to about 500 people from 15 states
attending a symposium on health career opportunities for Hispanics.
   The fact that she has been recommended for the job, Novello
said, sends a message that the Bush administration is interested in
recruiting minorities for powerful positions.
   ``It's an honor for me, and for being Hispanic and for being a
woman,'' she said at a news conference.
   Novello, who chairs the Pediatric Task Force for AIDS, said
health officials must obtain the ``true number'' of children
infected with the HIV virus. The HIV virus causes acquired immune
deficiency syndrome.
   The task force estimates that by 1991, 10,000 to 20,000 children
will be infected with the virus, and 3,000 youngsters will have the
disease.
   ``However, it is feasible to believe that there are many more
children infected,'' she said, adding that not all infected
children have been tested.
</TEXT>
