<FIRST>r a AM-BackYardBody     10-23 0311</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Back Yard Body,0319</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Buries Friend's Body in Parents' Back Yard</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT MILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAYVILLE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A young man panicked and buried a friend
in his parents' back yard after the friend died in his car, then
agonized for a week before telling his mother, police said Monday.
   An autopsy was conducted on the body of Alan Istvan, 28, of New
Fairfield, Conn., said Suffolk County police Lt. John Gierasch.
   Gierasch said there would be no decision on whether to charge
Michael Montheard, a 24-year-old house painter from Danbury, Conn.,
until Montheard had been interviewed and autopsy results were in.
   ``So far everything he has told us seems to be holding up,''
Gierasch said.
   The death and burial came to light Sunday night, when Montheard
telephoned his mother, Virginia Eckstein, said the family attorney,
John Byrnes. Montheard told her he had buried Istvan in her back
yard in this Long Island city of about 15,000 people 65 miles east
of New York City.
   The police were notified and they found Istvan's body in a
3-foot-deep grave covered with leaves behind the Eckstein home.
   According to Byrnes, Istvan fell asleep in Montheard's car when
they went out with another friend after work Oct. 13. Montheard and
the other friend left Istvan alone in the car for a little while,
Byrnes said. When they returned, they found him dead.
   ``He apparently had vomited and became asphyxiated on his own
vomit,'' Byrnes said.
   Montheard and the friend, who has not been identified by Byrnes
or police, threw a blanket over Istvan's body, drove to Long Island
early the next morning, and buried it in his mother and
stepfather's yard.
   If Montheard's story holds up, the only charge he could possibly
face would be unlawful disposal of a body, a misdemeanor violation
of state health law, Gierasch said.
</TEXT>
