<FILEID>AP-NR-10-23-89 0107EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-SFQuake-Fryes 1stLd-Writethru a0412 10-23 0597</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SF Quake-Fryes, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0412,0609</SECOND>
<HEAD>Homeless in the Suburbs _ Two Days on a ``Numb High''</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 13th graf, `The contents ...' to CORRECT spelling of `cupboard'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS GATOS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leta Frye recently joined the ranks of
the nation's homeless.
   She's not a disheveled bag lady with possessions stashed in a
supermarket shopping cart. Mrs. Frye's belongings are strewn on a
slope in the Santa Cruz Mountains, mixed up with the debris of her
earthquake-ravaged $450,000 house.
   The split-level, four-bedroom home is now a splintered pile of
rubble, rocked off its foundation and tossed 15 feet by the 6.9
magnitude San Francisco Bay area earthquake. Only three huge pine
trees prevent the wreckage from sliding down the mountain.
   ``I realize I'm in a different subset of the population now.
Suddenly, I'm a homeless person,'' the 54-year-old dietitian said
Sunday, as she and her husband, William, picked through the debris.
``I slept in my car for two nights. I have a different frame of
mind now.''
   ``It's kind of like a death in the family,'' Aetna Casualty and
Life Insurance Co. spokesman Tom Greaney said of the loss.
   Aetna adjuster Toni Johnson said the Frye home was the worst she
had seen so far, adding that it would take weeks to determine how
many homes in the Bay area were destroyed in the quake.
   ``There are just too many to count,'' she said.
   The Fryes were paid $20,000 on Friday as an advance to their
earthquake insurance claim. The couple had argued a year ago over
whether to buy insurance and reluctantly paid the $440-a-year
premium.
   ``We really debated about it before we signed up. Thank God we
did,'' said Mrs. Frye.
   The couple bought the 22-year-old house five years ago. It's one
of 112 houses in the Villa del Monte Estates area about 50 miles
south of San Francisco and just southwest of San Jose.
   ``Many people have come by here and said we have the dubious
distinction of having the most destroyed house in the Villa,'' Mrs.
Frye said.
   ``We've become very popular,'' added Frye.
   The contents of dressers, cupboards, drawers and desks where
strewn about inside the demolished home, and the Fryes used a
garden rake to fish out mementos and personal items in reach.
   ``I think everybody around here for two days was on this numb
high _ sort of in shock,'' Mrs. Frye said.
   When the earthquake struck, Mrs. Frye was driving home in her
car and thought the tires had gone flat. Her husband, 57, an
executive at Lockheed Space Ordnance, was in Maryland on a business
trip.
   ``His first comment was, `Well, Leta, you wanted to remodel,' ''
Mrs. Frye said. ``We had one room we called the T.U.R. _ the
torn-up room, which I was going to remodel. Now I call it the
T.U.H. _ torn-up house.''
   The Fryes, who now are staying in a hotel, say they are
uncertain whether they will rebuild on the one-acre site.
   The 27,750 people living in Los Gatos were still coping Sunday
with effects of the quake. Traffic lights were still out, plywood
covered many storefront windows, roadblocks remained in the heart
of town, and state Highway 17 leading south through the mountains
to Santa Cruz was still closed. A steady procession of trucks
carried water into the mountains.
   The heavily wooded area features a phenomenon unusual in
California _ noticeable seasons. Fall leaves have turned orange and
have filled the four-inch cracks on the mountain roads throught the
region.
</TEXT>
