<FIRST>r a PM-BakkerSentencing     10-23 0454</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bakker Sentencing,0467</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bakker Faces Sentencing From `Maximum Bob'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Retransmits a0452 to fix cycle designator</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL NOWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jim Bakker says God has forgiven him for
his sins, but his lawyer is afraid the TV evangelist will have a
tougher time setting things straight with a no-nonsense federal
judge they call ``Maximum Bob.''
   Bakker could be sent to prison for 120 years and fined more than
$5.2 million when he goes before U.S. District Judge Robert Potter
on Tuesday for sentencing for fraud and conspiracy.
   ``Maximum Bob will probably knock a year off the maximum,''
defense attorney George Davis joked ruefully.
   The judge lived up to his moniker last month when he sentenced
former Bakker aide David Taggart to 18 years and five months in
prison for tax evasion.
   ``One can only speculate Jim will get a heavier sentence than
Taggart _ it's a foregone conclusion,'' Davis said in an interview.
Taggart also was fined $500,000.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Jerry Miller said prosecutors will ask
for a prison sentence, but he refused to elaborate.
   Miller also declined to say if the government will ask that
Bakker be taken into custody immediately after sentencing;
prosecutors unsuccessfully tried to jail him after his conviction.
   Bakker, 49, was convicted Oct. 5 on 24 counts of fraud and
conspiracy for overselling $158 million in lifetime vacations, or
``partnerships,'' at PTL's resort hotels. The jury found that
Bakker used more than $3.7 million to buy luxurious homes, fancy
cars, jewelry and expensive vacations.
   The six-week trial was briefly interrupted by Bakker's
commitment to a mental hospital after a breakdown.
   ``God has forgiven me for my sins,'' he told followers from the
pulpit last week at his New Covenant Church in Orlando, Fla. ``I'm
not guilty.''
   Taggart and his brother, James, were convicted of diverting more
than $1.1 milion in PTL money for their own use and cheating the
government out of $525,000 in taxes.
   James Taggart drew the maximum prison term _ 17 years and nine
months _ and was fined $500,000. Both Taggarts testified against
Bakker.
   Potter, a Reagan appointee on the bench for eight years, ``can
be harsh when it's called for, compassionate when it's justified,''
Charlotte lawyer George Laughrun said last month.
   If a defendant admits his guilt, Potter is likely to weigh that
in his favor, Laughrun said. If Potter thinks a defendant is lying,
he's likely to hold that against him, the lawyer said.
   Before sentencing the Taggarts, Potter said he thought they had
lied on the stand. But Potter gave former PTL executive Richard
Dortch eight years out of a possible 10 after Dortch pleaded
guilty, apologized and agreed to testify for the government.
</TEXT>
