<FIRST>r w PM-Anthony-Gingrich     10-23 0355</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Anthony-Gingrich,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Democrat Fires Business Tabloid Article at GOP Nemesis</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House ethics panel should keep looking
into Republican Whip Newt Gingrich's ties with a Georgia
businessman, even though the panel's lawyer says further
investigation is not needed, a leading House Democrat says.
   Rep. Beryl Anthony Jr. of Arkansas said the ethics panel should
send its own staff to investigate Gingrich's contacts with two
federal agencies on behalf of real estate developer Chester Roush
Jr. because it ``cannot ignore'' an article published this weekend
in the Atlanta Business Chronicle.
   Roush, a longtime political patron of Gingrich, was among the
supporters who raised $13,000 for Gingrich to tour Europe in 1977
for research on a novel. Gingrich, a history professor at West
Georgia College at the time, was elected to Congress the following
year and never wrote the book.
   The article, which was distributed to news organizations by the
Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee that Anthony chairs,
said Gingrich attempted to intervene with government agencies on
behalf of Roush projects twice in 1986 _ once with the Farmers'
Home Administration and once with the Department of Housing and
Urban Development.
   In both cases, the agencies reaffirmed their decisions denying
the relief sought by Gingrich for the Carrollton, Ga., businessman.
   Richard Galen, a spokesman for Gingrich, said he had not read
the article and could not comment on the specifics. However, he
said it sounded like the article recounted a typical
congressman-constituent relationship.
   ``That's what people in Congress do, and they're generally proud
of it, helping businessmen in their area wend their way through the
labyrinth of the federal bureaucracy,'' Galen said.
   Last week, the ethics committee's outside counsel concluded
there was no basis for opening a formal investigation into charges
by another Arkansas Democrat, Rep. Bill Alexander.
   Alexander had accused Gingrich of violating House rules and
campaign finance laws through the 1977 book partnership involving
Roush and another one in 1984.
   ``Merely reading through documents is not enough,'' Anthony said
in a statement distributed along with the article. ``The committee
now needs to send its own staff to Georgia to interview individuals
involved.''
</TEXT>
