<DOCNO> AP891023-0025 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-23-89 0205EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r p PM-Pell'sDecision     10-23 0664</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pell's Decision,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON TODAY: Sen. Claiborne Pell _ Pondering the Future</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: RETRANSMITTING to fix category code.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Claiborne Pell, the courtly chairman of
the Senate Foreign Relations Committee, is considering ending his
30-year Senate career but Democrats say they are ``pushing him
hard'' to run for re-election.
   Pell will be 71 next month and these Democrats say he has every
right to retire.
   But they also say his decision to step aside would make the 1990
Rhode Island Senate race highly competitive, perhaps leaving an
otherwise virtually safe seat vulnerable to a strong Republican
drive.
   Republicans say that if the veteran Rhode Island senator does
retire there is a better-than-even chance that Rep. Claudine
Schneider, R-R.I., the almost-certain GOP candidate, can prevail,
spurring the GOP's drive to regain the Senate majority it lost in
1986.
   ``The Democratic Party and his own colleagues are pushing him
hard to run,'' said a Senate source close to Pell, adding that one
of those doing some gentle pushing is Senate Majority Leader George
Mitchell of Maine.
   ``We are telling him, `We need you, we want you, you are an
important part of this body,''' said Anita Dunn, communications
director for the Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee.
   ``Senator Pell has said he is undecided; there is every
indication that he has not made up his mind,'' she said. ``I think
his colleagues would clearly like him to run.''
   ``I think it's a blow if he doesn't run,'' said Sen. John Kerry,
D-Mass., a former chairman of the Democratic campaign committee.
Kerry said that is because Pell is widely regarded as all but
certain to retain his seat if he does seek a fifth six-year term.
   ``But it's really his choice,'' Kerry said. ``It's a very
personal thing and it's hard for the committee to intrude; it's
hard for the Democratic Caucus to intrude.''
   Pell has done no fundraising, leaving the strong impression he
will choose to retire. He has repeatedly told associates he is
genuinely undecided but that he will announce a decision, possibly
by mid-November.
   ``I will make my views known at an appropriate time,'' Pell says
when asked the question directly.
   ``He's clearly considering stepping down and is looking for
alternative ways to pursue his foreign policy interests,'' said
Sen. Richard Lugar, R-Ind., the senator Pell succeeded as chairman.
   Pell has much to ponder. He will be 72 shortly after the 1990
elections, 78 at the end of a new six-year term.
   In Rhode Island, Pell has two conflicting precedents to follow.
   He holds the seat vacated by Sen. Theodore Francis Green,
D-R.I., who was 92 when he retired.
   But Pell has often quoted, with apparent approval, the line used
by Sen. John O. Pastore, D-R.I., when he ended his political career
in 1976 at age 69. It was good to leave, Pastore said, ``while the
music is still playing.''
   On the other hand, Pell is the chamber's fourth most senior
member. He is the author of the Pell Grant program for college
tuition aid. The chairmanship of the Foreign Relations Committee
represents an ambition realized.
   But Pell, a soft-spoken and reserved liberal, has had to face
constant, often grating guerrilla warfare from Sen. Jesse Helms,
R-N.C., the panel's arch-conservative. He has often had difficulty
persuading the panel to face up to its legislative burden,
repeatedly failing to obtain the quorums needed to do business.
   Party officials offer varying assessments of the impact if Pell
decides to retire.
   Wendy De Mocker, communications director for the National
Republican Senatorial Committee, asserted that Pell himself is
vulnerable to a strong campaign by Rep. Schneider.
   Speaking for the Democrats, Anita Dunn said Pell's retirement
``would move a fairly safe Democratic seat onto the playing field
and make it a competitive race.''
   But she said that should not develop into an opening wedge that
causes Democrats to lose their majority in the Senate which the
party now controls, 55-45.
</TEXT>
