<FIRST>r a PM-HondurasCrash-Americans     10-23 0286</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Honduras Crash-Americans,0293</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wisconsin Farmer, Washington Lawyer Killed in Honduras Crash</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Honduras-Crash</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A Wisconsin farmer returning from a volunteer mission to
Nicaragua and an attorney doing free work for a human rights group
were among the 12 Americans killed when a Boeing 727 jet crashed in
Honduras.
   Of the 146 people on board, 131 died when the Honduran jet
crashed into a hillside near Tegucigalpa. Three Americans were
among the 15 survivors.
   Daniel Yurista, 37, was returning home after spending five weeks
in Nicaragua working with the Farmer to Farmer program helping set
up a dairy cooperative, said his wife, Kathy.
   Yurista used draft horses on his farm and had been helping
Nicaraguan farmers use draft horses for field power. He had planned
to fly home one week ago, but was aboard the flight because of
travel delays, she said.
   Yurista lived near Prairie Farm, 45 miles north of Menomonie,
Wis.
   Two other Americans on the plane were private lawyers doing
volunteer work for the Internationl Human Rights Law Group, its
executive director said Sunday in Washington, D.C.
   Amy Young said the lawyers were in Nicargua to prepare for
monitoring the February 1989 elections in that country. She
identified them as D. Lea Browning and Anthony Friedrich.
   She said Ms. Browning, 32, whom the State Deparment listed as
Deborah Browning, was in stable condition in a Tegucigalpa
hosspital. Friedrich, 28, was killed, according to the U.S. Embassy
in Honduras.
   Another American passenger, Eugene Van Dyke, was in critical
condition at Brooke Army Medical Center in San Antonio, a duty
officer said Sunday. The State Department identified Van Dyke as an
employee of the U.S. Agency for International Development in
Tegucigalpa.
</TEXT>
