<DOCNO> AP891023-0035 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-23-89 0345EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Hugo-McClellanville     10-23 0562</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hugo-McClellanville,0580</SECOND>
<HEAD>One Month Later, Shrimping Village Worries About Rebuilding Economy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TRIP DuBARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>McCLELLANVILLE, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One month after Hurricane Hugo
bashed this shrimping village, 65-foot trawlers remain sprawled
along the shattered waterfront, bulldozers remove oaks on roads,
and mattresses dry on porches.
   But as the nation focuses on the earthquake in the San Francisco
Bay area 3,000 miles away, this community of 500 is entering the
most difficult part of its recovery.
   Hugo hit just as the four-month shrimping season was getting
under way.
   ``Everything is tied to the seafood in one way or another,''
said Rutledge Leland, mayor of the 150-year-old village located
about 40 miles north of Charleston. ``I think the biggest problem
is the reality of the fact that so much of our economy has been
destroyed and that there are so many people that have lost their
businesses and their boats.''
   Hugo roared ashore Sept. 21 with 135 mph winds and storm surges
of 10 to 15 feet. The storm ultimately killed 18 and caused at
least $4 billion in damage in South Carolina alone before fading
into the Northeast.
   ``Shrimping is one of those things where you make it all in
about 120, 150 days a year,'' Leland said last week. ``If you
haven't made it by Thanksgiving, that's it. And that's just about
the time most of these guys are going to get back to work.''
   Leland's seafood packing plant, which he estimates accounts for
about 70 percent of the town's $7 million in annual seafood sales,
was largely ruined. He hopes to be operating at 50 percent capacity
by the time the shrimping season ends in December.
   About 60 percent of McClellanville's 35-boat fleet was knocked
out of service for at least 30 days to 60 days when the hurricane
swept ashore, Leland said.
   Only 30 feet of the town's 2,500 feet of dock survived the storm.
   Farrell White, 50, has been a shrimper for the past 35 years.
Now his 73-foot boat, ``Daddy's Girl,'' lies aground some 30 feet
from the harbor with an estimated $50,000 in damage.
   ``Shrimping season's over for us,'' White said.
   He hopes to refloat his boat and obtain a Small Business
Administration loan, which could supply up to $500,000 for lost
equipment and wages at interest rates as low as 4 percent.
   National relief efforts have flooded the village with food,
clothing and volunteers, so much so that some has been distributed
to other nearby communities.
   But housing for the newly homeless still remains a problem.
Precise figures are unavailable, but officials say nearly 400
people have asked for federal assistance in repairing their homes
or relocating to temporary housing.
   Lincoln High School remains closed indefinitely; it was flooded
with 7 feet of water. The school's 330 students returned to classes
last week, 25 miles away in Charleston suburbs where teachers are
newly trained in stress counseling.
   For adults, as many as five mental health counselors have been
in town every day since the hurricane. Counselors plan to stay into
next year.
   Leland is concerned about the time it will take the town to
rebound.
   ``I don't know how you put a town under,'' Leland said. ``It was
a real thriving seafood town. (But) it's going to take us four or
five years to even come close to where we were before.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891023-0036 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-23-89 0347EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-SFQuake-Farmworkers Bjt   10-23 0611</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SF Quake-Farmworkers, Bjt,0630</SECOND>
<HEAD>Life Was Unstable Before the Earthquake</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COLLEEN BARRY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WATSONVILLE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Life for farmworkers was never
predictable, even before an earthquake destroyed at least 370 homes
and forced hundreds of people onto the streets of this farming
community.
   It's a situation many have faced before _ even in the best of
times.
   ``Being homeless is only a couple of dollars away and they are
trying to figure out day-to-day where they are going to live,''
said Estella Mejia, who works for Salud Para la Gente, a community
health clinic.
   ``Life's very unstable and when something like this happens, it
adds to it. They live with crises already,'' Mejia said.
   But normally, those crises are personal _ families living 10 to
a home or workers combing the region for jobs when the harvests are
over.
   This time, the people are suffering as a community.
   ``When we go on the streets and into camps to visit, it's a
little chaotic. But what gives me hope is there are a lot of people
who care,'' Mejia said.
   Watsonville, a community of 30,000, is near the epicenter of
Tuesday's quake, about 80 miles south of San Francisco. It is a
frozen food processing center for vegetables grown in the area's
fields.
   City Councilman Rex Clark said the disaster brought the
community together.
   ``I see neighbors whom I've known for a long time and only say
hello to and now suddenly you stop to talk and see what's happened
to their houses,'' Clark said.
   A half-dozen tent encampments have sprouted in vacant fields
where officials estimate 500 are living. About 1,000 others are in
three shelters. Countless others are living in cars or yards.
   Many residents were so frightened by the quake and its
aftershocks they refuse to go indoors, even though their homes had
been declared safe.
   ``It's just scary. I think another disaster is going to
happen,'' said Rosa Chavez, who has spent nights since the quake
with her 8-month-old baby and other family members in the back of
her father's truck. ``The little kids are afraid of going into any
building.''
   Raymundo Leyva is one of those who fear another tremor could
topple the weakened walls of his house. After Tuesday's quake, as
soon as he could get to a working telephone line, Leyva called his
grandparents in Mexico who had survived their own powerful
earthquake four years ago.
   ``Everyone was crying. They said they were happy to hear from me
because they thought Watsonville was gone,'' Leyva said. ``They
thought it was going to happen, the same thing that happened in
Mexico City. I did, too.''
   City spokeswoman Lorraine Washington said no attempt will be
made to ban camping until all homes are inspected and it is
determined who was left truly homeless. Workers so far have marked
330 homes unsafe to enter near the hard-hit downtown area. That
total is expected to rise dramatically as workers travel into the
outskirts of town, she said.
   Damage to the city has been estimated at $122 million with the
loss of downtown businesses making up a quarter of that total.
   Almost an entire block of businesses bordering a central plaza
where townspeople normally gather in the evenings will have to be
demolished. Several landmarks, including Ford's Department Store
and the town clock, are among those will have to be razed.
   ``That's going to dramatically change the appearance of the
downtown plaza because those buildings were the backdrop,'' said
Clark.
   ``There's a lot of Victorian architecture and no one's going to
replace it with that style,'' he said. ``Hopefully we won't become
glass and steel.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
