<FIRST>r a PM-SFQuake-Religion     10-23 0375</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SF Quake-Religion,0389</SECOND>
<HEAD>Residents Turn to Churches, Synagogues in Quake Aftermath</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-SF Quake, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDY LIPPMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The earthquake that left them spiritually
homeless hasn't shaken the faith of the parishioners at St. Francis
de Sales Cathedral.
   The century-old Roman Catholic cathedral was declared unsafe
after Tuesday's 6.9-magnitude earthquake _ its tower cracked and
leaning. Many parishioners kept away by a wire fence sought
spiritual comfort Sunday in a Baptist church down the street.
   ``Sometimes in life God shakes us and says, `Pay attention.'
There is something more important than the ordinary things in our
lives,'' the Rev. Joseph M. Powers told the congregation.
   ``It wasn't just the ground that shook Tuesday. The earthquake
shook a lot of things that we do _ ordinary things on our agenda.''
   St. Francis has served people in this community for 102 years.
It stands in an older section of town across from the bus station.
   It rarely draws a huge crowd _ senior citizens, neighborhood
families and some commuters come together to form what priests call
an ``urban community.''
   Yet it is loved and its damage has brought pain to the
congregation.
   ``I need to cry. I need to let go. It's a heavy burden on the
heart,'' said Ona Solom, who assisted at Sunday's service.
   But the Rev. James Keeley notes that a church is more than a
structure.
   ``A building is important,'' he said. ``But people, they are
more important.''
   And while the parishioners at St. Francis sang ``From Our Exile
God Bring Us Home'' people here and in surrounding communities were
joining together to make sure they were all right and to find
comfort and to offer help to others.
   Some churches encouraged congregants to share stories either at
prayer breakfasts or services.
   Churches and synagogues collected money, food and clothes. A
group of Protestant churches started a counseling service, sending
ministers to visit those who need help.
   At the Shiloh Christian Fellowship congregants were urged to
donate their skills to help those whose homes had been damaged.
   ``We don't want to offer only prayers. We want to offer
something more. We want to help people who need it,'' said the Rev.
David Kiteley, Shiloh's minister.
</TEXT>
