<SECOND>PM-BRF--SPJ,0119</SECOND>
<HEAD>AP Reporter Becomes President of Society of Journalists</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Carolyn S. Carlson, an Associated Press reporter
in Atlanta, has been inaugurated president of the Society of
Professional Journalists.
   Carlson, 38, served as treasurer, secretary and president-elect
of the 17,000-member organization before taking office at the
society's annual convention Saturday in Houston.
   She has been with AP's Atlanta bureau since 1977. Her
assignments have included covering the state Senate. A journalism
graduate of the University of Georgia, she worked as a political
reporter for The Augusta Chronicle.
   SPJ, the largest professional group in journalism, was begun in
1909. It is dedicated to promoting freedom of the press and high
standards in journalism.
