<FILEID>AP-NR-10-23-89 0518EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     10-23 0417</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0426</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rain Dampens Pacific Coast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Rain fell over the Pacific Coast early today, while much of the
nation enjoyed fair weather.
   A storm system moving out of the Gulf of Alaska spread rain
across the northern and central Pacific Coast Sunday, and
threatened to bring heavy snow to the mountains of northern
California today.
   Snowfall totals of up to 3 feet are possible over the highest
elevations of the northern mountains of California by late today.
Rain dampened Seattle early today.
   Dry weather prevailed across much of the rest of the nation,
with clear skies over the southern and central Plains and the
southern and middle Atlantic Coast.
   High temperatures were only in the 40s Sunday in northern New
England and upstate New York. Record lows for the date were set in
Fort Wayne, Ind., where the temperature dipped to 27 degrees, and
in Tallahassee, Fla., where the temperature cooled to 34 degrees.
   The high for the nation Sunday was 91 degrees in Texas at
Childress, Junction, Laredo and San Angelo.
   Other reports at 3 a.m. EDT:
   _East: Albany, N.Y., 37 fair; Atlanta 57 fair; Boston 43 fair;
Charleston, S.C., 54 fair; Chattanooga 51 fair; Cincinnati 47
cloudy; Cleveland 38 fair; Detroit 38 fair; Hatteras 59 fair;
Jacksonville 52 fair; Key West 71 fair; Knoxville 46 partly cloudy;
Macon 48 fair; Miami 65 fair; New York 46 fair; Philadelphia 42
fair; Pittsburgh 38 fair; Portland, Maine, 32 fair; Richmond 39
fair; Tampa 52 fair; Washington, D.C., 46 fair.
