<FIRST>r a PM-SFQuake-Relief 2ndLd-Writethru a0525 10-23 0582</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SF Quake-Relief, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0525,0591</SECOND>
<HEAD>Donations from Cash to Croutons Flow into Quake Area</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf, `Around the ..., to include that time is p.m.;
pick up 5th graf, `Following the ...</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-SF Earthquake, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto SNJ2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   From cash to croutons, tax tips to televisions, San Francisco
Bay area residents and businesses are pitching in to feed and
comfort their earthquake-shattered neighbors.
   And the haves are doing their part to help the have-nots. In
affluent Marin County north of San Francisco, a line of Mercedes
Benzes, Porsches and pickups brought food or volunteers to the
Marin Community Food Bank Warehouse.
   ``We're not all sitting around in our hot tubs,'' said the food
bank's executive director, Anne Rogers. ``People are taking the
lists of items we need and going around the stores with shopping
carts.''
   Around the nation today at 5:04 p.m. PDT, the minute the
earthquake hit on Oct. 17, as many as 100 radio stations will
observe 15 seconds of silence as part of an effort called ``Radio
Relief,'' according to Pollack Media Group.
   Following the silence, stations will urge listeners to donate to
the American Red Cross fund providing disaster relief. The stations
will then play either the Beatles' ``A Little Help From My
Friends'' or Dionne Warwick's ``That's What Friends Are For.''
   While much of the quake aid has come from Bay area companies,
millions of dollars and other donations continued to stream in over
the weekend from elsewhere around the country.
   In Provo, Utah, fans at a football game Saturday between Brigham
Young University and the University of Texas-El Paso poured $60,301
into collection boxes set up for earthquake relief donations to the
Red Cross.
   Coors Brewing Co. in Golden, Colo., sent bottled water last week
and joined with another company to send two trailer loads Sunday.
Three passenger ferries from Washington state are heading to the
Bay area to help transport commuters, but their departure has been
delayed by bad weather.
   Clorox Co., based in Oakland, Calif., gave $100,000 each to the
Red Cross and Salvation Army, and shipped about 1,000 cases of
liquid bleach, cleansers, mildew stain remover and salad dressing
and croutons to relief groups.
   Goodyear Tire &amp; Rubber Co., which owns numerous retail stores in
the area, offered free repairs on tires, headlamps and fan belts to
keep ambulances, fire trucks and other emergency vehicles operating.
   And Elmwood Park, N.J.-based JVC Co., also with outlets in the
Bay area, donated televisions to Red Cross shelters.
   ``We are proud to be a part of what appears to be an
extraordinary effort on the part of the local business community to
lend a helping hand,'' Peter Lillevand, of the San Francisco law
firm of Orrick, Herrington and Sutcliffe, said in a news release
announcing a donation of $50,000 to relief efforts.
   Banks with local branches, including Citibank, American Savings
Bank and the Bank of California, offered cash and, in some cases,
special terms on loans and other financial assistance. Ernst &amp;
Young, an accounting firm, set up a hot line to answer tax
questions about deducting quake losses.
   Elsewhere around the country, church groups organized ``meals on
wheels'' road trips to hard-hit areas. A Seventh Day Adventist
group from Reno, Nev., planned to supply 10,000 meals a day to
Santa Cruz and Watsonville.The Alabama Baptist State Convention
dispatched a disaster relief truck to Santa Cruz, where it is
expected to feed up to 5,000 people a day.
</TEXT>
