<FIRST>r i PM-HongKong-China     10-23 0345</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hong Kong-China,0356</SECOND>
<HEAD>China Agrees To Resume Repatriation Of Illegal Immigrants</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government said today China will again take
back illegal immigrants caught crossing into Hong Kong in a sign of
easing tension between Beijing and the British colony.
   Chinese authorities have refused to repatriate citizens who
sneaked into the British colony illegally since early this month,
when Hong Kong allowed a dissident Chinese swimmer flee to the
United States.
   The terse statement said an agreement was reached after
discussions between the Hong Kong government and the local branch
of Xinhua News Agency, the de facto Chinese Embassy in the
territory.
   About 1,100 Chinese were awaiting repatriation today. A
government spokeswoman said she did not know how many would be
returned Tuesday.
   ``It's quite good as far as we're concerned in that we're back
to normality with the Chinese,'' a Hong Kong official said on
condition of anonymity.
   He said he expected the agreement would reduce tension ``quite a
bit.''
   Relations between Beijing and Hong Kong, which reverts to China
in 1997, have been delicate in recent months.
   Many of the colony's 5.7 million people supported the spring
pro-democracy movement in Beijing. China warned the colony not to
become a base for efforts to topple the communist government.
   Beijing was angered when Hong Kong let the dissident swimmer,
Yang Yang, travel to the United States after he overstayed his
visa, instead of repatriating him. Yang had participated in the
pro-democracy movement.
   The local Xinhua office said the colonial government set a bad
precedent in handling the case.
   China then decided to stop accepting the return of illegal
immigrants and said cooperation would not resume until the British
and Hong Kong governments showed their sincerity. Beijing did not
elaborate.
   The government statement issued today said both sides reaffirmed
understandings on the return to China of illegal immigrants and
Chinese who overstay their visas in Hong Kong.
   The Hong Kong government has sent back all illegal immigrants
from China since 1980. More than 12,000 have been sent back to
China this year.
</TEXT>
