<FIRST>r a PM-X-RatedComputer     10-23 0221</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-X-Rated Computer,0227</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sex Game Could Hinder Emergency Computer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Workers have programmed an X-rated game into the
computer system used by New York City's ambulance corps, and an
expert fears it could drag out emergency response times, according
to a report published today.
   Ambulance dispatchers and other Emergency Medical Service
workers could be distracted by the sex game, or the program could
spread a virus into the computer system and cause it to break down,
the New York Post reported.
   The newspaper quoted John Petrofsky, a senior management
consultant for the ambulance system, who said he was fired last
week after he notified his superiors about the threat posed by the
game, ``Foreplay.''
   ``It's a disaster waiting to happen,'' Petrofsky said.
   Petrofsky said he warned top Emergency Medical Service officials
for eight months while he was demoted and then fired.
   Officials will search the system today for the sex game, ``to
see whether we can get a hold of this program,'' Lynn Schulman, a
spokeswoman for EMS, said Sunday.
   The time it takes to dispatch an ambulance to a medical
emergency would double from three to six minutes if dispatchers had
to work manually during a computer crash, said Alexander Kuehl, a
former medical director of EMS.
   ``It's very possible calls will get lost,'' Kuehl added.
</TEXT>
