<FIRST>r a PM-DC-10Parts     10-23 0486</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-DC-10 Parts,0498</SECOND>
<HEAD>Search Ends With No Flange, Investigators Wait on Harvest</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Konny in 11th graf is cq</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALTA, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Searchers ended their quest Sunday for engine
pieces from a jetliner that crashed in July, with no luck in
finding a part important to investigators.
   Search teams from metal detector clubs turned up some engine
fragments over the weekend when they ranged over corn and soybean
stubble, but a flange remained missing.
   Investigators hope farmers completing their harvest may come
across the flange, which connected the forward fan shaft to the
disc in the tail-mounted DC-10 engine made by General Electric
Aircraft Engines. The flange was held together with 20 bolts.
   Of the parts still missing, the flange is the most important to
investigators, said Jerry Clark, flight safety investigator for GE,
which called off the search after two straight weekends of hunting.
   ``There's one square mile yet to be harvested along the primary
path of fragments we've found,'' he said Sunday. The location of
parts in fields helps investigators determine what pieces came in
contact with others, he said.
   The No. 2 engine flew apart as United Flight 232 was flying
north of Alta, spewing metal and severing hydraulic lines for
flight controls. Pilots wrestled the jumbo jet to the Sioux Gateway
Airport in Sioux City but the plane cartwheeled down a runway in a
fiery crash that killed 112 of the 296 aboard.
   Volunteers on Sunday found a fragment of a fan blade from the
No. 2 engine and a piece of a track for engine ball bearings, Clark
said. On Saturday, searchers north of Alta found two blade
retainers that were part of the engine rotors, and a part of the
hydraulic pump.
   Along with airplane debris, searchers found artifacts from more
than a century of farming and rural living, including a sledge
hammer and old horseshoes with spikes, which provided animals with
traction while pulling old-time farm implements.
   The search by about 90 volunteers centered Sunday on the Ed
Anderson farm.
   ``I told them that the area they were searching used to have a
farmstead on it, so I'm sure they'll find all sorts of things,''
said Anderson.
   Another resident, Konny Droegmiller, will keep an old brass
sleigh bell that was found.
   ``I'll make it into something to hang on the front door for
Christmas,'' she said.
   General Electric, which called off its search Sunday, offered
more than $270,000 in rewards for engine parts. Farmer Janice
Sorenson received $119,000 earlier this month when she found most
of the rear engine fan disc as she worked in a field. The rest of
the disc was found on the nearby farm of Harold Halverson, who
received about $40,000 in reward money.
   This weekend, a $1,000 reward was paid for a set of shrouds for
a fan blade. The shrouds help dampen vibration and also serve as
spacers between fan blades.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891023-0054 </DOCNO>
