<DOCNO> AP891023-0055 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-23-89 0920EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Britain-China     10-23 0286</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-China,0293</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: Secret Subway in Beijing Would Enable Leaders to Escape</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China's leaders have built a secret subway line
under the streets of Beijing so they can escape in the event of a
counterrevoltution, according to a British TV documentary.
   The railway network runs between the Great Hall of the People
overlooking Tiananmen Square and the Xi Shan mountain military base
in west Beijing, a former Chinese civil servant told Independent
Television's ``World In Action.'' The program was scheduled to be
broadcast today.
   The unidentified man, who said he fled to Hong Kong after the
June military crackdown on pro-democracy protesters, said he twice
rode the underground trains to the military base.
   ``They can have a headquarters there if they wish,'' he said.
``They have hospitals and also army camps and ammunition dumps
there. They have all these facilities open to their use.''
   The former official said two other stations are linked to the
line _ one under the government compound at Zhongnanhai where party
leaders live and work, and the other under the Bank of China where
the country's gold is stored.
   The identities of those interviewed in ``The Terror After
Tiananmen'' were concealed to protect them from arrest. The
producers were not credited to prevent Chinese authorities from
tracing their sources, the program said.
   The civil servant worked at a junior level but was
well-connected. He worked in an office in which he could observe
senior leaders first hand, according to the program.
   The documentary was made secretly in Beijing with amateur video
cameras after the June crackdown, producers said. Hundreds, perhaps
thousands, of protesters were killed as troops rolled through
Beijing streets to recapture Tiananmen from the students.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
