<DOCNO> AP891023-0058 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-23-89 1005EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-MilwaukeeCrime 1stLd-Writethru a0498 10-23 0624</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Milwaukee Crime, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0498,0638</SECOND>
<HEAD>Once Peaceful City Reeling as Homicides Set Record</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf to UPDATE with another killing; pick up 4th graf,
`Even the ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYA L. WESLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's being called the ``year of 100 murders.''
A once-quiet city has erupted with drive-by shootings, drug-running
and nightly gunfire.
   ``We started on New Year's morning with two drug-related
homicides and it hasn't stopped since,'' says police Capt. George
W. Hegerty.
   The city broke its previous record of 95 homicides in a year,
set in 1987, early in October. Police logged the 100th homicide
early last week, and the toll went to 101 on Sunday night when a
24-year-old man was shot to death in his car on a North Side street.
   Even the onset of colder weather hasn't slowed the carnage the
way it usually does.
   ``There's only been two weeks this year when we didn't have a
homicide reported,'' Hegerty said. ``I was hoping the numbers would
drop off, but they keep going up.''
   Milwaukee residents, who treasure their ethnic neighborhoods,
clean streets and tradition of progressive government, are
mobilizing to turn back the tide of violence.
   Many neighborhoods are forming block watch groups, and in other
cases, residents are simply taking it on themselves to call the
police when they see drug deals or other illegal activity, said
Alderwoman Marlene E. Johnson, who represents an inner-city ward.
   ``There have been a lot of busts lately, and many of those have
been due to citzen alerts,'' she said. ``The key is the people in
the community saying, `Hey, this is enough of this.' ''
   The number of murders has been climbing since 1985, except for a
drop last year. There were 73 murders in 1985, 85 in 1986, 95 in
1987 and 73 in 1988.
   That is despite a decline in city population that started at
least two decades ago. The latest population estimate of about
600,000 in January 1988 was down by about 36,000 from the 1980
census total.
   As is the case in other cities, drugs get much of the blame for
the increase in killings.
   At least 12 of this year's homicides have been directly linked
to drug activity and many of the remainder are believed to have
involved alcohol or drug intoxication, Hegerty said.
   The violence has included so-called ``drive-by'' shootings where
someone fires from a car and then speeds away. Police blame gang
activity for three drive-by shootings last summer, including one
that killed a 30-year-old man standing outside a tavern less than a
block from his house.
   ``Our problem is serious,'' Hegerty said, ``but fortunately, as
bad as it is, I don't think it's as bad as it is in other major
cities.''
   Karen Hendrickson, a Milwaukee native and president of a block
watch group in her neighborhood on the city's near north side,
bemoans the change rising crime has brought to her community. Fear,
she noted, is changing the traditional Halloween.
   ``When we were kids, we went out when it was dark and our
parents let us have the run of the neighborhood,'' she said. ``We
would never let that happen today. We ought to be alarmed by that.''
   The roots of the problem go deeper than the current drug
problem, to poverty and racial discrimination that keeps minorities
unemployed, say Ms. Hendrickson and others.
   ``Give people a better environment to live in and give them
something constructive to do. Then you'll see a turnaround,'' says
the Rev. LeHavre Buck, director of Harambee, an organization
working to improve conditions for inner-city residents.
   ``Now, as usual, we're in a position of reacting,'' he said.
``We're trying to shut the gate after the horse has gone.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
