<FIRST>r a PM-RiotTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0471 10-23 0667</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Riot Trial, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0471,0682</SECOND>
<HEAD>Miami on Edge as Riot Officer's Trial Opens</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 12 grafs to UPDATE with trial beginning; pick up
10th graf pvs, `The Jan. 16 ...</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto covering</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Miami police officer went on trial today for the
shooting of a black motorcyclist whose death touched off three days
of racial violence in January.
   The trial of Officer William Lozano opened amid tight security
and pleas for calm. Lozano is charged with two counts of
manslaughter in the deaths of the motorcyclist, Clement Anthony
Lloyd, 23, and his passenger, Allan Blanchard, 24.
   Lloyd was shot to death during a police chase, and Blanchard
died when the machine wrecked.
   Lozano has said he fired in self-defense because the speeding
motorcycle headed straight for him. But other witnesses in the
Overtown neighborhood dispute that version, calling the shooting
unwarranted.
   Defense attorney Roy Black opened the trial by saying it will be
impossible to seat an objective jury in Miami. He asked that the
trial be moved to another city.
   ``We are going to show that what jurors who sit on this case
will have on their minds is that if Officer Lozano is acquitted,
there is going to be a riot,'' he said.
   Assistant State Attorney Richard Shiffrin said the government
was convinced that an objective jury can be seated, and he opposed
defense efforts to introduce television tape, newspaper articles
and witnesses to tell the story of the January riot.
   ``To replay everything that has transpired since January would
be unnecessary, and in addition tends to inflame the community,''
the prosecutor said.
   Circuit Judge Joseph Farina said he would consider starting jury
selection immediately, and then sequestering the panel during
subsequent pre-trial motions so they will not be affected by
publicity before testimony starts.
   Outside the Metro-Dade Justice Building, Lozano's friends and
family members waved Colombian flags and placards of support as
they marched up and down a sidewalk.
   A smaller group denounced the Colombian-born officer. One man,
who loudly proclaimed Lozano ``a cold-blooded murderer,'' was taken
into custody when he tried to enter the courtroom.
   Police killings of blacks _ or the subsequent trials _ have
triggered violence in Miami four times in the 1980s, and crisis
teams were in place today around the racially tense city. The fear
of renewed violence was a key to the defense's effort to move the
trial from Miami.
   The Jan. 16 slaying touched off burning and looting in
predominantly black neighborhoods. One person was killed, 11 were
wounded by gunfire and 13 structures burned down only days before
the Miami area was host to the Super Bowl.
   Tensions, especially between blacks and Hispanics, remained high
after the violence. At one point, an attorney for the Hispanic
Officers Association wrote a letter to Police Chief Perry Anderson
asking that its members be pulled from black neighborhoods because
of residents' anger. The chief, who is black, denied the request.
   Blanchard's family has filed a $10 million federal lawsuit
against the city, accusing the police department of displaying a
pattern of violence, especially toward blacks.
   Many Hispanics have taken up Lozano's cause, collecting money
for him during radio pledge drives.
   The Metro-Dade police force, which patrols part of the largely
black Liberty City area hit by riots in January, has given its
officers riot classes and new gas masks, and has two armored trucks
on standby.
   Even while urging calm, black leaders including Willie Sims of
Dade's official Community Relations Board acknowledge that blacks
are intently watching the trial. The board has been training teams
that will head into any neighborhood where violence begins.
   ``I won't sit here and tell you that nothing, absolutely zero,
will happen,'' Sims said. ``But we are optimistic that whatever
does occur, we will be able to reduce the level drastically.''
   The board has proposed an interracial pop concert on Nov. 10 and
a ``unity summit'' to help keep the peace.
</TEXT>
