<SECOND>PM-East Germany, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0551,0446</SECOND>
<HEAD>East German Workers Form First Independent Labor Union</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS lede to show it is East Germany's first independent labor
union; ADDS 4 grafs with party newspaper quoting opposition member for
the first time, background.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GIRARD C. STEICHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Several hundred East German workers at an
electronics plant outside East Berlin have formed the communist
nation's first independent labor union, a spokesman said today.
   Roelf Boerger said the union's platform includes a demand for
the right to strike, and he urged all 6,000 employees of the
Wilhelm Pieck factory in Teltow to join the new labor movement. He
said the union's name is ``Reform.''
   Boerger's statement was distributed to Western news media in
West Berlin.
   Despite a more candid approach to news reporting in recent days,
the state-run ADN news agency made no immediate mention of the
electronics workers' declaration.
   Boerger said the union declares solidarity with new opposition
political groups in East Germany and calls for a thorough
restructuring of the communist state's economy.
   The new leadership's attitude toward the Reform trade group was
not immediately made clear. The factory where it was founded is
named after East Germany's first president.
   On Sunday, the head of the state-controlled trade federation
called for more independence for labor organizations.
   Since Egon Krenz took over the nation's leadership from Erich
Honecker on Wednesday, the official news media have been filled
with unusually frank articles about the nation's troubles.
   But neither Krenz nor other senior Communists have indicated any
willingness to share power with opposition groups or allow an
independent trade movement like Poland's Solidarity to take root.
   The Communist Party newspaper Neues Deutschland today devoted
four pages to reform discussions that it said were ``going on all
across the nation.''
   The newspaper also gave prominent play to a lively, public
exchange between top communist officials in East Berlin and
pro-democracy activists on a downtown East Berlin street on
Saturday.
   Neues Deutschland devoted nearly a full page to discussions held
in Leipzig on Sunday concerning East Germany's economic and social
problems.
   For the first time, the newspaper quoted a member of the
outlawed Neues Forum (New Forum) opposition group as saying the
group does not consider itself a real opposition party, ``because
we want to improve socialism.''
   ``But democratic reforms are necessary,'' the newspaper quoted
Neues Forum member Petra Lux as saying.
   East Germany's Liberal Democratic Party, which like others in
the country is allied with the Communist Party, has urged the
government to recognize Neues Forum, which was banned as
``anti-social'' by authorities last month.

</TEXT>
</DOC>
