<FIRST>r a PM-SonOfLehder 1stLd-Writethru a0531 10-23 0358</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Son Of Lehder, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0531,0363</SECOND>
<HEAD>Closing Arguments Begin In `Son Of Lehder' Trial</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE with closing arguments beginning;
pick up 4th graf, `The government ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON WORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal prosecutor today outlined
evidence against five Americans charged with conspiring with
Colombian drug lord Carlos Lehder Rivas to smuggle and distribute
cocaine in the United States.
   In closing arguments in what has been dubbed the ``Son of
Lehder'' trial, Assistant U.S. Attorney Ernst Mueller told jurors
that the conspiracy began in 1974 and continued until early this
year.
   Following arguments from the five defense attorneys, U.S.
District Judge John H. Moore II will give instructions to the 12
jurors so they can begin their deliberations.
   The government contends the five defendants were involved in a
conspiracy with Lehder that began in 1974 and continued through
February of this year.
   Lehder, 40, was convicted last year and sentenced to life in
prison without the possibility of parole for running a massive
smuggling operation. He was convicted following a 7{-month trial.
   The latest case grew out of an investigation that followed
Lehder's trial.
   Defense attorneys say their clients either weren't part of the
Lehder conspiracy or withdrew from it so long ago that they should
come under the statute of limitations.
   On trial are Jack Carlton Reed, 59, who was convicted last year
on drug conspiracy charges and sentenced to 15 years in prison;
Thomas Herington, 35, of Mill Valley, Calif.; attorney Barry Kane,
52, of Hyannis, Mass.; Donald Lady, 41, of Pomona, Calif.; and air
charter service owner Samuel T. Stewart, 53, of Anaheim, Calif.
   Prosecutors claim Reed, who is charged with operating a
continuing criminal enterprise and conspiracy to distribute, often
acted as an intermediary between Lehder and his corps of Americans
pilots and distributors.
   Herington faces one count of conspiracy to distribute five
kilograms or more of cocaine. Kane, Lady, and Stewart face the
conspiracy distribution count and an addition charge of conspiracy
to import cocaine into the United States.
   If convicted, the men face sentences of 10 years to life.
</TEXT>
