<DOCNO> AP891023-0066 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-23-89 1055EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-SFQuake-Traffic 2ndLd-Writethru a0542 10-23 0830</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SF Quake-Traffic, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0542,830</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pleas To Ride Buses, Trains and Ferries Because of Quake Closures</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with more traffic details, quotes;
PICKS UP 5th graf pvs, `The effort ...' ^LaserPhoto Staffing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER McNULTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Morning traffic was heavy and stormy
weather played havoc with the elaborate transit plans of 3 million
commuters, many of whom abandoned their cars to board buses, trains
or ferries on the first major workday since an earthquake ravaged
the city.
   Normally crowded freeways and the Bay Bridge, which links San
Francisco and Oakland, remain closed because of damage. Commutes
that usually take 45 minutes were forecast at two hours.
   California Highway Patrol spokesman Don Gappa reported fewer
accidents than normal, and no major problems.
   ``The volume of traffic is worse than normal,'' Gappa said. ``If
we didn't have rain we probably wouldn't have as many problems as
we do. There are more problems with flooding and trees down than
traffic accidents.''
   Traffic on the Golden Gate Bridge was bumper-to-bumper but
moving shortly after 5 a.m. PDT, and many people appeared to be
carpooling. Highway 101 was a sea of lights, some parking lots at
subway stations were full, and one ferry that normally sails with
140 people carried 572 on an early trip.
   Gale warnings were posted early today, rain was heavy in some
areas and one ferry was turned back because of rough waters on the
San Francisco Bay, authorities said.
   On the 6 a.m. ferry from Oakland to San Francisco, a 30-minute
crossing took 55 minutes through heavy seas, with swells
occasionally washing over the top of the boat.
   ``I've just been through hell, but heck, I have to admit I made
it through it,'' said passenger John Trowbridge, 27, of Alameda,
who normally would drive across the Bay Bridge. ``It can only get
better, this can't get much wors.''
   ``Everybody's just going to have to go into slow-motion. That
includes all the bosses,'' said Karen Meyer, 42, of Oakland.
   The effort to avoid ``gridlock'' reached a feverish pitch
Sunday, when Rod Diridon, chairman of the Metropolitan
Transportation Commission, declared riding alone in a vehicle an
``anti-social act.''
   ``We've got to convince people that it's not business as usual
and that it won't be business as usual in some places for years,''
Diridon said.
   A fleet of ferries was called into service to make more than 225
trips shuttling an estimated 10,000 stranded residents from the
east side of the bay to San Francisco.
   But at best, conceded Joel Markowitz, MTC's manager of transit
coordination, post-quake planning ``might avoid a total disaster''
on the roads.
   ``We're optimistic, but I think that realistically, a lot of
people are still going to try to squeeze on the roads,'' he said.
   Experts predicted that two-thirds of commuters in the
nine-county Bay area would experience delays as they tried to get
to and from work.
   The collapse of a portion of the Bay Bridge, which typically
carries 65,000 people during rush hour every weekday, created the
biggest headache, and snarls were expected on other major arteries
as commuters tried alternate routes.
   In Oakland, the ruin of Interstate 880 cut off a major
thoroughfare that used to carry 170,000 vehicles daily. Repairs are
expected to take years.
   The Embarcadero Freeway along the waterfront in San Francisco,
which connects downtown with the North Beach district and
Fisherman's Wharf, has been deemed unusable until at least
mid-1990. A five-mile stretch of Interstate 280 in San Francisco
was closed from U.S. Highway 101 to Sixth Street.
   In Santa Cruz, State Highway 17 was closed to through traffic
because of landslides and mudslides. That four-lane road provides a
critical link for 20,000 people who commute daily to work in
Silicon Valley. It will be closed indefinitely, although one lane
is open to buses and emergency vehicles.
   The Bay Area Rapid Transit district, which runs trains through a
tube under the San Francisco Bay, beefed up service and planned to
start running trains around the clock beginning at midnight.
   BART telephone information lines were jammed Sunday, with delays
of several minutes common once callers got through the busy signals.
   Callers to a carpool service that matched riders with drivers
also had to be patient as workers fielded a steady stream of calls.
   ``There's two of us here and it's kept us busy,'' said Kathleen
McKinney of Solano Rideshare, a state-funded carpool operation.
   MTC's Markowitz said many large corporations had expressed
interest in offering flex-time schedules to help dilute the
commute, but no one dared predict how many workers would work
off-hours.
   Markowitz, who expressed hope the crisis would force long-term
changes in the way people get around in the Bay area, had only one
wish.
   ``I think we're going to see a lot of people who haven't tried
transit try it,'' he said. ``I just hope they'll be tolerant,
patient and have a good sense of humor.''
</TEXT>
