<HEAD>At Least 155 Cars Crash on Fog-Shrouded Superhighways In West Germany</HEAD>
<DATELINE>REGENSBURG, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 150 cars slammed into
each other today in chain-reaction pileups on fog-shrouded southern
highways, seriously injuring six people, police in Bavaria state
reported.
   Police said excessive speed was the major cause of the accidents
that occurred in heavy fog with visibility at less than 50 yards.
   One hundred vehicles were involved in the first collisions on
the A-93 Autobahn between Weiden and Regensburg, about 95 miles
north of Munich, police said.
   In a second chain-reaction crash, 55 vehicles piled up on the
A-3, another superhighway between Regensburg and Passau near the
border with Austria, police said in a statement released to the
news media.
   West German autobahns, many of which have long stretches with no
speed limits, are often the scene of crashes in the foggy autumn
months.
