<HEAD>Acid Spill Forces Evacuation of 2,000; 39 Treated</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with 39 treated, sted 29, authorities
citing cause of accident; pick up 4th graf pvs, `About half ...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PEACHTREE CITY, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Caustic fumes released by a spill of
hydrochloric acid forced the evacuation of more than 2,000
residents, and 39 people were treated for eye and throat irritation.
   Those evacuated were permitted to return to their homes early
today after a caustic cloud formed from the acid dissipated,
officials said.
   Authorities said a crack in a transmission pipe at Photocircuits
Atlanta Inc. in Peachtree City caused the spill of more than 300
gallons of the acid at 8 p.m. Sunday. Peachtree City is about 25
miles southwest of Atlanta.
   Thirty-nine people were treated at Clayton General Hospital for
minor eye and throat irritation apparently caused by caustic fumes
from the spill, hospital spokeswoman Sharon Lynch said. No one was
admitted.
   About half the people treated were plant workers, while the
others were workers at nearby businesses, some civilians in the
area and the first police officers to arrive at the scene, said
Fayette County Emergency Services Capt. Doug Morris.
   Officials evacuated residents from an area of about two square
miles around the plant. Emergency shelters were established at two
schools and four churches.
