<FIRST>r a PM-CampPendletonFire     10-23 0197</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Camp Pendleton Fire,0201</SECOND>
<HEAD>Blaze Over 11,000 Acres of Wilderness Substantially Contained</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAMP PENDLETON, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 600 firefighters got help
from rain to substantially encircle a blaze that has charred nearly
11,000 acres of wilderness since last week.
   The fire was declared 80 percent contained Sunday, with full
containment expected by tonight.
   The blaze began Wednesday during a military training exercise on
firing ranges at the Marine Corps' Camp Pendleton, spreading to the
San Mateo Canyon wilderness area in Cleveland National Forest. An
investigation to find a cause continued.
   Firefighters said they saw little of the fire smoldering.
   ``But the problem is until you get a couple days' sun on it
you're not sure where it's still hot,'' said Bruce Bundick of the U
.S. Forest Service. ``All it takes is one root or one stump still
smoldering that we don't notice, and the winds come up, and it's
off and running again.''
   Although there was activity on the northeastern flank of the
fire, the blaze did not spread Sunday, Forest Service spokeswoman
Audrey Hagen said.
   Firefighters using infrared detectors will examine the entire
fire line before the blaze is declared out, Bundick said.
