<SECOND>PM-Hastings-Governor,0327</SECOND>
<HEAD>Impeached Judge Opens Account in Governor's Race</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former federal judge Alcee Hastings,
who was removed from office last week after being impeached, filed
Monday as a candidate in the 1990 Florida governor's race.
   Hastings, 53, filed with the state Division of Elections to open
a campaign account as a Democratic candidate. He has sought public
office unsuccessfully on two prior occasions.
   ``I would be an inspirational leader for the people,'' said
Hastings, who added that the notoriety from his impeachment trial
would benefit him in his effort to win the Democratic nomination.
   ``It gives me an immediate bounce,'' he said. Hastings said more
people in Florida know him than his Democratic opponents, U.S. Rep.
Bill Nelson of Melbourne and state Sen. George Stuart of Orlando.
   ``I got fired by people who didn't read or understand the
dynamics of the evidence as it was presented,'' Hastings said of
his removal from U.S. District Court. ``I believe myself to be a
man of honor and integrity. I have not committed any crime at any
time.''
   Hastings said he would discuss the impeachment hearings early in
his gubernatorial campaign, but hoped the focus would soon shift to
matters relevant to the governor's race.
   ``My interests, I believe, are the interests of the people of
Florida,'' Hastings said.
   Hastings ran unsuccessfully for the U.S. Senate in 1970 and for
the Public Service Commission in 1974.
   He said he would campaign on a platform of restructuring
Florida's government and tax base. He favors abolishing the cabinet
and lieutenant governor's office and having a unicameral
Legislature.
   Hastings said he began thinking about the gubernatorial race six
months ago.
   ``I had to face the reality that I would be removed from
office,'' he said.
   Incumbent Gov. Bob Martinez and state Sen. Marlene
Woodson-Howard have announced they will run on the Republican side
of the race.
