<FILEID>AP-NR-10-23-89 1217EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-NATO-Maneuvers     10-23 0192</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-NATO-Maneuvers,0198</SECOND>
<HEAD>NATO To Stage First Computer-Simulated Exercises</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CASTEAU, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The NATO allies will stage their first
Europe-wide, computer-simulated combat exercises for top commanders
next month, NATO's Supreme Headquarters Allied Powers Europe said
today.
   ``Exercise ACE 89'' will be the first such exercise involving
all of NATO's top regional military commanders, a headquarters
official said. It is scheduled for Nov. 6-17.
   In the exercise, combat will be simulated by a central computer
near Ramstein Air Base in West Germany and computers at regional
NATO headquarters across Europe.
   The central computer will present NATO commanders with a combat
situation, involving conventional air, land and sea forces, to
which they must react, said Maj. Robert Bittmer, a headquarters
spokesman.
   No troops will leave their bases but ``to the senior commanders
it will appear as if there are troops in the field,'' Bittmer said.
   The central computer executes the combat decisions made by the
regional commanders who will discuss and assess the results of
their actions through daily teleconferences.
   NATO's major regional headquarters participating in the exercise
are those in Kolsaas, Norway; Brunssum, the Netherlands; Naples,
Italy, and High Wycombe, Great Britain.
</TEXT>
