<FILEID>AP-NR-10-23-89 1248EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Walesa     10-23 0420</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Walesa,0431</SECOND>
<HEAD>Walesa New Head of Solidarity Chapter in Lenin Shipyard</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lech Walesa promised workers at the Lenin
Shipyard who elected him head of their local Solidarity chapter
that he would mind their interests despite his many other duties, a
newspaper reported Monday.
   Walesa declined an offer to become honorary chairman of the
union chapter at the shipyard where he helped found the independent
Solidarity movement nine years ago and unexpectedly decided to run
for the office Saturday, according to the pro-Solidarity newspaper
Gazeta Wyborcza.
   The electrician defeated Alojzy Szablewski, a veteran shipyard
worker and longtime fellow union activist, by a vote of 87-37.
   ``I don't want honors, I don't want to be artificial, I want to
rule,'' Walesa told the workers, explaining why he did not want to
become only the honorary chairman, according to Gazeta Wyborcza.
   The Solidarity leader is still an employee of the shipyard, but
he has been delegated for union work since Solidarity became legal
again on April 17.
   Walesa served as unofficial chairman of the national Solidarity
organization after the 1980 strikes that led to legalization of the
East bloc's first independent trade union. He was chosen Solidarity
leader at a national congress in Gdansk in 1981.
   Walesa was the elected head of the shipyard chapter until the
national congress when he resigned from that post. Szablewski was
then elected leader of the shipyard chapter and served in that post
until his defeat Saturday.
   Asked whether he would be able to reconcile his new job as head
of the union chapter in the shipyard and his role as national union
leader, Walesa said he would try to keep in permanent contact with
his deputies in the shipyard and promised to visit the workers once
a month.
   After martial law was declared on Dec. 13, 1981, to crush the
union, Walesa guided the movement through nearly eight years of
underground activity and participated in the two strikes at the
shipyard in 1988 that prompted authorities to start a dialogue with
the opposition.
   Two months of talks this spring resulted allowing the
reinstatement of the union and democratic elections in June that
brought victory to the Solidarity-led opposition and paved the way
for a non-communist government.
   Some disgruntled Solidarity members say Walesa has too much
power and want a national congress to be convened as soon as
possible.
   Piotr Konopka, Walesa's spokesman, said Sunday the congress is
likely to be held in the spring, after Solidarity chapters have
chosen their delegates.
</TEXT>
