<DOCNO> AP891023-0082 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-23-89 1319EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-NATO     10-23 0710</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-NATO,0731</SECOND>
<HEAD>NATO Defense Ministers Meet on Nuclear Issues</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NATO defense ministers, grappling with
fast-paced changes in the Soviet bloc, probably will call for a
fresh look at how much nuclear firepower should be kept in Western
arsenals, officials say.
   U.S. Defense Secretary Dick Cheney will join defense chiefs of
the North Atlantic Treaty Organization for two days of nuclear
strategy talks, beginning Tuesday on the southern coast of Portugal.
   ``There are no major decisions required at this meeting,'' said
a senior NATO official. ``The nuclear affairs of the alliance are
running along very smoothly at this time.''
   Another official said: ``It will be a good occasion to take
stock of nuclear matters.'' A third added, ``It's going to be a
rather uneventful meeting, but that's not necessarily a bad
thing.'' All spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The meeting should be free of the tensions marking previous
sessions of the Nuclear Planning Group when U.S. and British
officials clashed mostly with West Germans over development of a
new theater nuclear missile.
   President Bush and other leaders of the 16-nation alliance
resolved the dispute at their 40th anniversary summit in May.
   With that on the backburner, the defense ministers can discuss
the dramatic events shaping East-West relations _ and how they
should react.
   NATO Secretary-General Manfred Woerner was expected to ``call
attention to the very positive changes'' in the Soviet bloc
countries, said the senior NATO official.
   Another official suggested the ministers urge the Soviet Union
to do more in reducing its nuclear stockpile. Soviet President
Mikhail S. Gorbachev has promised to pull out 500 short-range
nuclear weapons from Europe this year.
   According to Western estimates, the Soviet Union has 1,450
short-range nuclear missile launchers in Europe. NATO has 88 Lance
launchers, most based in West Germany.
   The ministers also were expected to discuss fresh contacts with
East bloc officials. Cheney met recently with Soviet Defense
Minister Dmitri Yazov.
   But it appeared the key outcome would be asking top aides to
make a thorough study of the alliance's nuclear role in an era of
reduced tensions.
   An official said the ministers would likely want ``an
examination of the implications of an agreement on conventional
forces in Europe ... for alliance nuclear forces.''
   NATO negotiators are bargaining with the Soviet-led Warsaw Pact
in Vienna to reach a quick agreement on sweeping reductions in
conventional, or non-nuclear, weapons in Europe.
   ``The positive nature of those (talks) gives us some hope that
we can look forward to a reduction in conventional forces and
subsequent to that a reduction in nuclear forces,'' said the
official. The deeper the conventional cuts, he said, the greater
the impact on NATO's nuclear strategy.
   ``I certainly wouldn't rule out that at some point in the future
we decide certain elements of our nuclear posture are not
necessary,'' he said. ``(But) I think we're going to have to see
some major changes on the other side before that's true.''
   He also said the allies ``see no time in which we will not need
some nuclear weapons.''
   The United States also was expected to bring its allies up to
date on bargaining with the Soviet Union on reducing long-range
nuclear forces.
   Bush and other NATO leaders in May worked out a compromise on
negotiating with Moscow cuts in conventional and nuclear arms in
Europe. The formula links reductions in conventional forces to the
start of talks on trimming short-range nuclear missiles in Europe.
   West Germany had demanded immediate negotiations with the Warsaw
Pact on slashing theater nuclear missiles. But U.S. and British
officials said attention should be focused first on cutting the
East's enormous superiority in conventional arms.
   They also agreed the question of deploying a new, more powerful
generation of surface-to-surface nuclear missiles would be dealt
with in 1992. The United States had wanted a strong endorsement of
its development program to replace aging Lance missiles. The work
is designed to more than triple the missile's range to just under
the limits of the 1987 Intermediate-range Nuclear Forces treaty.
   Defense ministers meet twice a year to discuss nuclear matters.
France, which is outside NATO's integrated military structure, does
not attend. Iceland, which has no armed forces, has observer status.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
