<FIRST>r i PM-Singapore-Refugees     10-23 0277</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Singapore-Refugees,0284</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sixty-Two Vietnamese Refugees Rescued, Six Others Die At Sea</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SINGAPORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sixty-two Vietnamese refugees arrived in
Singapore after being adrift at sea for 52 days during which they
say their crippled boat was deliberately towed away from Malaysian
waters, refugee officials said today.
   Six of the group died while their boat drifted near Malaysia and
Singapore, according to a statement from the office of the United
Nations High Commission for Refugees in Singapore.
   The refugees were brought here by the Greek-owned vessel
Anezina, flying the Cypriot flag, on Sunday, the statement said.
Many had to be assisted, and 12 were taken immediately to Singapore
General Hospital, where one pregnant woman in her thirties remains
in critical condition, it said.
   The woman's 4-year-old daughter was in satisfactory condition,
the statement added.
   Sixty-eight refugees left Cuu Long in southwest Vietnam on Sept.
1 in a 46-foot boat whose engine broke down after three days at sea.
   The refugees reported they survived on rain water, but on Oct.
14 one man died of dehydration and starvation. The next day a
Malaysian vessel spotted the group and brought them water, boiled
rice and vegetables, the report said.
   ``They claim to have been told they would be towed to shore. A
tow rope was attached to their boat and they were towed for
approximately 19 hours. The tow rope was cut without warning and
the boat set adrift,'' the statement said. ``Two more people, a man
and a woman, died of dehydration and starvation.''
   The Anezina rescued them about 75 miles off the coast of Borneo
shortly before another woman died, leaving two young chidren, the
statement said.
</TEXT>
