<FIRST>r i AM-Malawi-Railroad     10-23 0429</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Malawi-Railroad,0442</SECOND>
<BYLINE>Key Trade Route Reopens After 5 Years of Rebel Sabotage ^By MELINDA
HAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BLANTYRE, Malawi (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Malawi's shortest and cheapest route to
the sea, the Nacala railway line through Mozambique, has reopened
for the first time after five years of rebel sabotage.
   The government has urged Malawi's merchants to reroute external
trade through the Indian ocean port of Nacala, which is only 500
miles from this land-locked country _ a distance three times
shorter than the current route through Durban, South Africa.
   Tobacco, tea and sugar are the main exports likely to be
transported on the Nacala line.
   Tobacco alone earned 60 percent of this impoverished nation's
export income last year.
   No goods have yet traveled on the line, which reopened last
week. But armor-plated locomotives have made test runs since late
May, according to a diplomatic source in the Malawi capital of
Lilongwe.
   Since 1984, Malawi's traditional rail routes to the Indian Ocean
ports of Nacala and Beira have been closed because of repeated
attacks by Mozambique National Resistance guerrillas fighting
against the leftist Frelimo government in Maputo, the capital of
neighboring Mozambique.
   Malawi depended on links through South Africa to carry more than
90 percent of its trade, as well as a new northern route through
Tanzania that carries the remaining traffic.
   Until now, Malawi paid one of the costliest transport bills in
the world, amounting to more than $100 million last year, according
to Finance Minister Louis Chimango.
   The new northern route through Tanzania is being rehabilitated
for $160 million.
   Freight will be transported in stages by road to Lake Malawi,
container vessel across the water, by road again to the Tanzanian
border, and then by the Tazara railway to the port of Dar es Salaam.
   Once the Nacala line is at full steam, it would be able to carry
more than three-quarters of Malawi's trade and cut its transport
bill by two-thirds, said a spokesman for Malawi Railways.
   Since 1983, the nine-nation Southern African Development
Coordination Conference largely has been responsible for restoring
Malawi's lifeline to the sea.
   The regional bloc, which includes Angola, Botswana, Lesotho,
Mozambique, Swaziland, Tanzania, Zambia and Zimbabwe, has pledged
to loosen South Africa's traditional stranglehold on their
economies.
   The line is guarded by some 1,000 Malawian soldiers _ a fifth of
the national army _ and an undisclosed number of Frelimo troops.
   Britain, West Germany and the United States are contributing
only small amounts to the development of the line, but their
governments are providing uniforms, trucks and communications
equipment to Malawian troops.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
