<FIRST>u i PM-Israel-Peace 1stLd-Writethru a0448 10-23 0895</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel-Peace, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0448,0916</SECOND>
<HEAD>Talks At Low Point, Absence of Strong Leadership Hinders Progress</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 6th graf `Digging in...' to UPDATE with
Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin reopening debate on Baker proposals. Pickup
7th graf `While Shamir...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICOLAS B. TATRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With both the PLO and Israel rejecting U.S.
proposals for dialogue, efforts to arrange Palestinian-Israeli
negotiations appear to have reached a low point.
   Among the reasons for the stalemate is the fierce opposition of
hard-liners on both sides, and the lack of strong leadership that
can overcome the resistance.
   ``We are not in an era of great leadership,'' said Avraham Sela,
a political science professor at Hebrew University in Jerusalem.
``The problem is that both sides are in a quandary because of
internal politics.''
   Daoud Kuttab, a Palestinian journalist, said ``there is no
farsightedness in Israel, not enough statesmanship in the United
States and general apathy in the Arab world.''
   In Israel, Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir, 74, has portrayed
Egyptian and U.S. efforts to bring about talks with Palestinians as
disguised attempts at forcing Israel to negotiate with the
Palestine Liberation Organization.
   Digging in his heels, Shamir said in a speech last week that
``this is our land from the dawn of history, and it will be so
always. We will not be pushed nor pressured.''
   However, Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin of the left-leaning
Labor Party today opened fresh debate about the latest American
proposals by saying Israel was considering them despite Shamir's
objections.
   The U.S. proposals ``have not been rejected or accepted. Nobody
has been authorized to accept or reject them,'' Rabin told 500 high
school students in the Tel Aviv suburb of Kfar Sabah, adding that
Washington's latest ideas should be put to a Cabinet vote.
   While Shamir has eased his rhetoric following criticism by the
U.S. State Department, his ability to compromise is limited because
hawks in his own right-wing Likud bloc, led by ex-Defense Minister
Ariel Sharon, have put conditions on his peace proposals.
   The hawks oppose trading land for peace, curtailing the building
of Jewish settlements in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip or
even starting talks until the 22-month Palestinian uprising has
been put down.
   Part of the reason for a lack of progress, however, also lies in
Shamir himself. He lacks the strength of Likud founder and
ex-Premier Menachem Begin, who arm-wrestled skeptical colleagues
into making peace with Egypt in 1979.
   Shamir is also viewed by some analysts as an inflexible
ideologue who did not support the peace treaty with Egypt and who
does not want to risk getting into any process now that would lead
to yielding land or allowing exiled Palestinians to return.
   ``Shamir sees clearly the eventual result and doesn't want to
get into it. It is not a matter of discussions and proposals,''
said Sela, the political scientist.
   The rival Labor Party advocates negotiations without further
delay. But its leader, Finance Minister Shimon Peres, has lacked
the muscle in his party to force the issue, although there are
hints he may take action if Shamir returns empty-handed from a trip
to Washington next month.
   The internal Palestinian debate is almost as intense as that in
Israel. The only united stand came in Baghdad, Iraq, recently where
PLO leaders rejected U.S. Secretary of State James A. Baker III's
compromise proposals as an attempt to circumvent the PLO.
   PLO Chairman Yasser Arafat has spent most of his time battling
hard-liners within his movement rather than assuaging Israeli
doubts about his sincerity in pledging to renounce terror and
accepting the Jewish state.
   Palestinian Islamic fundamentalists have rejected any idea of a
peace agreement, and George Habash, a leading PLO leftist, has
threatened to assassinate Hosni Mubarak if the Egyptian president
continues to promote a Palestinian-Isreli meeting in Cairo.
   The confusing rhetoric from the Palestinian side has failed to
persuade the Israeli in the street of Arafat's sincerity in seeking
peace or his ability to live up to an agreement.
   Hence there is little pressure on Shamir to make concessions or
rein in his own hard-liners.
   Arab countries, with the exception of Egypt, have been silent or
negative about the peace efforts. This has reinforced Israeli
doubts about Arab intentions and has led to bitterness on the part
of Palestinians.
   Saeb Erakat, a leading Palestinian activist and political
scientest at An Najah University in the West Bank, says Arab
countries have failed to provide adequate political or financial
backing to the Palestinians. He says Arab states fear a successful
uprising against Israel could prompt challenges to their own
regimes.
   ``The Arab masses might imitate and revolt against their
regimes. That's why the Arab world does not support the uprising,''
he said.
   The United States also has been the target of criticism from
Palestinians and Israelis for not taking a more active role.
   In an editorial, the Labor-affiliated Davar newspaper said the
proposal to hold Palestinian-Israeli talks in Cairo about Shamir's
plan for elections in the occupied territories was headed for
failure.
   ``The responsibility for that is mainly with the Americans,''
the newspaper said, predicting a slow slide into violence unless
the Bush Administration stakes its prestige on forcing agreement.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Nicolas B. Tatro is AP bureau chief in Jerusalem
and has covered the Middle East for 12 years.
</TEXT>
