<FILEID>AP-NR-10-23-89 1411EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-China     10-23 0635</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China,0654</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chinese Gov't, Dissidents, Turn to East Bloc for Comfort</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Condemned by most capitalist countries for
crushing pro-democracy protests, China has turned to the socialist
world for support and comfort. So have its now-silenced protesters.
   Since the June army attack on student-led protesters caused
Japan and the West to halt high-level exchanges, Chinese diplomats
have busied themselves with meetings with East bloc and Third World
envoys.
   Chinese Vice Premier Yao Yilin visited East Berlin in October
and exchanged condolences with then-East German President Erich
Honecker over their mutual problems from ``imperialist class
opponents.''
   A succession of Soviet and East European scientific, educational
or Communist Party delegations have visited Beijing, many
expressing agreement with China's position that reforms are
intended to strengthen socialism, not topple it.
   But back in the visiting delegations' home capitals, changes are
occurring that can be of little comfort to the Chinese government
but warm the hearts of the dissidents. The widening of perestroika
in the Soviet Union, the rejection of communism in Hungary and
Poland and the mass exodus of East Germans have reinforced some
dissidents' belief that they, not the conservatives, will
eventually prevail.
   ``We are watching what happens very closely,'' said a woman
intellectual who supported China's democracy movment.
   ``There's a tide sweeping the socialist countries, and China
can't shut itself off from it. It can't become isolated again, even
if it tries,'' she said.
   Several former student protesters said the East Europeans'
demand for reform reinforced their beliefs that radical change is
necessary if China is to catch up with the developed world.
   ``It shows that socialism has failed everywhere, not just in
China'' and not just because of China's size and historic
backwardness, said one.
   China's TV news has ignored the East German marches _ dissidents
believe because of the similarities to China's mass protests for
democracy in the spring.
   In both countries, angry populations expressed impatience with
aging, out-of-touch leaders. Both East German and Chinese youth
used visits from Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev to call for
reforms modeled on Gorbachev's perestroika.
   The Xinhua News Agency, which provides all foreign dispatches,
has carried only a few brief, official East German reports on the
marches.
   Its other reports from the East bloc have created the impression
that old-fashioned, hardline Marxism predominates in the socialist
world.
   Xinhua has quoted East German attacks on the Western media, a
Bulgarian condemnation of Western human rights groups and
Czechoslovakian Communist leader Milos Jakes' pledge to ``never
concede to anti-socialist forces.''
   ``In the Soviet Union, the capitalist road won't do,'' read a
headline in Monday's People's Daily, quoting conservative Politburo
member Yegor Ligachev.
   Other headlines on the same page read, ``Soviet Union's Pravda
warns Western countries: don't plot to rock the socialist boat,''
and ``Yugoslav people's army opposes multiparty rule.''
   Chinese say they follow developments by reading between the
lines of Xinhua reports and listening to Voice of America and BBC
radio reports.
   A Western diplomat said that in internal debates some Chinese
theorists have dusted off the word ``revisionist'' to denounce the
reforms in the Soviet Union, Poland and Hungary. ``Revisionist''
was the late Chairman Mao Tse-tung's word for the Soviet Union,
which he accused of being too conciliatory toward the West.
   ``There are some arguing that China should come out in the open
and draw attention to the split in the international communist
movement, and that the ones who are faithful should draw
together,'' the diplomat said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
He listed North Korea, Bulgaria and Cuba among the hardline
``faithful.''
   But he predicted that China's current official stance _ that
each socialist country must follow its own road _ will prevail for
practical reasons: snubbed by the West, China cannot afford to snub
its remaining friends.
</TEXT>
