<FILEID>AP-NR-10-23-89 1507EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Nixon-China     10-23 0236</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nixon-China,240</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nixon to Visit China, Report to Bush</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Richard M. Nixon will visit
China around the end of the month, meeting with Chinese leaders and
reporting to President Bush on his return, a spokesman said Monday.
The White House said Bush looks forward to the report.
   Nixon spokesman John H. Taylor said in Woodcliff Lake, N.J., the
visit to Beijing had been delayed because of the deadly crackdown
on pro-democracy demonstrators last spring.
   For security reasons, Taylor said, Nixon's precise travel plans
were not disclosed.
   Bush banned high-level U.S. contact with the Beijing government
after the violence last spring. But that action does not apply to
trips such as Nixon's since he is not representing the U.S.
government, said presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater.
   ``While the former president is traveling as a private citizen,
President Bush looks forward to hearing his assessment of the
situation in China when he returns,'' Fitzwater said.
   He said that Nixon had discussed his upcoming visit with
National Security Adviser Brent Scowcroft.
   The trip will be Nixon's sixth since, as president, he re-opened
U.S. relations with the People's Republic of China in 1972.
   Nixon's spokesman, Taylor, said, ``He will give his assessment
of the leaders, their policies and Chinese-American relations in
general in writing to President Bush upon his return.''
   Taylor described the visit as ``solely a fact-finding trip''
with no sightseeing or social events.
</TEXT>
