<FILEID>AP-NR-10-23-89 1533EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Fashion     10-23 0621</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fashion,0642</SECOND>
<HEAD>Light Touch From Designers at Chanel, Dior</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto PAR5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUZY PATTERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Fashion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leggy fashions with a light-as-air appeal took over
in summer ready-to-wear shows Monday by fashion heavyweights Karl
Lagerfeld at Chanel and Gianfranco Ferre at Dior.
   Luxury fabrics and curvy silhouettes are ruling the runways as
strong silhouettes are bowing to the feminine appeal of bows and
softness.
   Lagerfeld turned the Chanel woman into a young girl with a raft
of flared shorts, tiny skirts, beautiful fitted long or short
jackets, and some asymmetrical draping to vary the menu.
   It was all a shadow game of black and white, pepped up by
pastels and some hot-color prints, as Lagerfeld played with a
girlish silhouette, outlining typically Chanel jackets in black
passementerie piping.
   He led off with a transparent-opaque contrast in asymmetrically
draped chiffon skirts under piped white jackets, later varying the
idea with transparent duster jackets over V-necked tunics and
micro-minis.
   This coy idea of pairing see-throughs with solids is a solid hit
in most Paris collections, and most beautifully done at Chanel.
   Some of the jacket ideas rich women will want to wear or copy
include tulip or decollete shapes done up with seed pearl patch
pockets and piping _ or sexier versions in black satin with
jet-bead trim and chains at the waist.
   The youth kick here means that the newest Chanel bag is worn as
a chic biker's pouch on a belt. The regular chain belt has become a
bold hip chain with huge links.
   The older Chanel client shouldn't panic. There's lots of choice,
especially in the ivory and white suits that don't have to be worn
open to show the bosom.
   Lagerfeld also offered soft, semi-transparent blouses with
floppy bows or deep-draped decolletes and dozens of lovely, long
pajamas.
   Gianfranco Ferre's first ready-to-wear collection for Dior also
was a symphony in grays, black and white, beginning with
tiny-checked suits and flared shortie coats.
   He too showed shorts, but topped them with billowy chiffon
babydoll jackets, raincoats and artists' smock tops.
   The Ferre signature big bow here became so outsized in organza
and taffeta that it made the strong silhouette of the outfits.
   The gift blouses were off-shoulder organza with big puffed
sleeves, or a fitted lace version, with black linen shorts or long
pants.
   The youth kick here became black workout suits, with black
leather jackets, or with ruffled wraparound stoles and skirts for
evening.
   Color finally came out at Dior in shades of periwinkle blue with
polka dots, plus some fitted linen or silk tulip jackets in tomato,
bright yellow and violet, often over black pants.
   For informal beachwear, Ferre offered bikinis and one-piece
ivory or off-white maillot swimsuits topped with terrycloth.
   Like Angelo Tarlazzi, he also used some hemstitched,
handkerchief-draped outfits right out of the linen closet.
   Designer Hanae Mori celebrated her 35 years in the industry with
fashions that look younger than ever. Last week she became a Knight
of the Legion of Honor for her years as a member of the Chambre
Syndicale, the powerful fashion association.
   Her sportier clothes were excellent in some soft day wear, with
short skirts, wide shorts, long and flared skirts in striped
chiffons with a Deauville regatta appeal.
   Her gray and white cloud prints and graphic Kabuki faces on
billowy kimono tops nevertheless didn't hide the female form. It
came out in fitted bustier trouser suits and fitted suits with
skirts above the knee _ younger than Mori's usual styles.
   She too went overboard for bows. She put her signature butterfly
bow on piped, colorful or navy linen suits, then the bow turned
giant on layers of chiffon in two colors for an iridescent evening
effect.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
