<FILEID>AP-NR-10-23-89 1541EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-DalaiLama     10-23 0309</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dalai Lama,0314</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tibetan Leader Says Nobel Prize Will Help His People</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TSETEN SAMDUP</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DHARMSALA, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Dalai Lama said Monday he will
remain ``a simple Buddhist monk'' despite winning the 1989 Nobel
Peace Prize, but it will make the world more aware of the Tibetan
struggle against Chinese rule.
   ``I will not be a different person,'' the Tibetan spiritual and
temporal leader said at his first public address since returning to
his exile home in Dharmsala after the Nobel Prize was announced
Oct. 5. ``I will remain the same galong (Buddhist monk), Tenzin
Gyatso, whether someone curses or praises me.''
   He told a crowd of 4,000 Tibetans celebrating the 29th
anniversary of the Tibetan Children's Village that the Nobel Prize
would make the Tibetan cause better known.
   ``Tibetans in Tibet today are undergoing a very difficult period
in Tibet's modern history,'' the Dalai Lama said. ``Martial law
continues in Lhasa and hundreds of Tibetans have been arrested and
and equal number have been killed.''
   The children's village, sprawling across a rocky ridge in the
Himalayan foothills, is home for 1,700 Tibetan children, including
about 500 who have been smuggled out of Tibet in recent years to
live in the Tibetan culture their parents fear will be denied them
under Chinese rule.
   The Dalai Lama fled to India 30 years ago when Chinese troops
surrounded his palace in Lhasa after a failed Tibetan uprising. His
followers set up a government-in-exile in Dharmsala, 300 miles
north of New Delhi.
   The Beijing government, which claims Tibet is an ancient and
integral part of China, has denounced the awarding of the Nobel
Peace Prize to the Dalai Lama as interference in China's internal
affairs. The Dalai Lama and the Tibetan government-in-exile say
Tibet was a separate and independent state before Chinese troops
arrived in 1950.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
