<FILEID>AP-NR-10-23-89 1438EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u p AM-VaGovernor Bjt   10-23 0676</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Va Governor, Bjt,0695</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wilder's Campaign Avoids Jackson, Civil Rights</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE TAYLOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lt. Gov. L. Douglas Wilder is striving to
be the nation's first elected black governor, but has avoided
emphasizing his race in a campaign without even a drive to register
black voters.
   The 58-year-old Democrat who grew up in the segregated South has
conducted a campaign designed to appeal to the moderate, urban
voters who helped put him in the state's No. 2 office in 1985, when
he got 44 percent of the white vote.
   But he showed a rare moment of anger on a matter close to the
hearts of black voters last week when his Republican opponent, J.
Marshall Coleman, invoked the name of slain civil rights leader
Martin Luther King Jr. in a televised debate.
   Wilder told Coleman, a 47-year-old former state attorney
general, that the late Gov. John Dalton cast a veto ``that you
encouraged'' of a bill to create a holiday honoring King. Wilder
pushed for years for a King state holiday.
   On Monday, at a rally at the University of Virginia in
Charlottesville, Wilder criticized a Coleman proposal to limit
out-of-state admissions to 10 percent at state-supported
universities and colleges.
   ``This university's richness and diversity are a result of
people coming from all over the world,'' Wilder told about 250
students at the rally.
   For the most part, Wilder's political success has been built on
a mixture of playing by the rules of the mostly white power
structure while challenging the establishment on occasion.
   Wilder played little part in the civil rights movement that
divided his home state in the 1950s and '60s. He has stayed away
from national black leaders such as Jesse Jackson, winner of
Virginia's 1988 presidential primary.
   Wilder did not endorse Jackson, and Jackson has not been invited
to campaign here this year on his behalf. ``I'm running a Virginia
campaign,'' Wilder said, a comment directed at President Bush's two
campaign trips to the state to support Coleman.
   When he first ran for the state Senate in 1969, Wilder was
chiefly known only as a criminal trial lawyer in Richmond. But he
became a symbol to Richmond blacks, defeating two white candidates
and taking the oath as the first black member of the chamber since
Reconstruction.
   About 17 percent of the state's 2.7 million voters are black.
   Wilder allied himself with a group of younger Democrats who were
about to overthrow the old-line conservative leaders in the Senate.
Eventually he rose to chairman of four committees, including the
powerful Rules panel, which makes committee assignments.
   He became identified with the King holiday bill, which
eventually became law, and an unsuccessful effort to change the
state song, ``Carry Me Back to Old Virginia,'' because of racially
offensive lyrics.
   Sometimes, Wilder turned against his allies. In 1982, he
single-handedly scuttled the U.S. Senate candidacy of Owen B.
Pickett, who was then-Gov. Charles S. Robb's choice for the
nomination.
   Pickett offended Wilder by praising the two men who held the
seat for a half-century: Harry F. Byrd Sr. and Harry F. Byrd Jr.,
whose legacy included resistance to school integration.
   Robb released a series of letters in 1986 in which the former
governor, now a U.S. senator, accused Wilder of being ungrateful
and unreliable. He took the action after Wilder's top aides said
Robb was getting too much credit for Wilder's 1985 victory.
   ``We've had differences and we've had serious differences,''
Robb said. ``But notwithstanding that, I'm still in Doug's corner.''
   Still, Robb has criticized both campaigns this year for focusing
too much on abortion.
   Coleman, who has used the Robb-Wilder feuds as fuel in his
campaign, said the abortion criticism was directed at Wilder, who
has run television ads that point out Coleman's anti-abortion views.
   A Wilder aide disagreed with Robb, saying voters consider the
issue important.
   But Wilder scarcely mentioned abortion in the debate last week.
   Coleman won the endorsement Sunday of the Richmond
Times-Dispatch, a week after Wilder got the nod from The Washington
Post.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
