<FILEID>AP-NR-10-23-89 1555EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-SouthAfrica     10-23 0503</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-South Africa,0515</SECOND>
<HEAD>ANC Leaders Hold Strategy Meeting, Unhindered by Police</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eight African National
Congress leaders, including seven freed from prison this month,
held a strategy meeting Monday, unhindered by police even though
their movement remains outlawed.
   A statement issued after the meeting said the men would consult
with exiled officials of the ANC and would address policy issues
Sunday at a mass rally at a soccer stadium near Johannesburg.
   The meeting marked a reunion for the seven recently released men
and a colleague, Govan Mbeki, who was freed from prison in 1987.
   Mbeki, 79, has been barred from traveling and attending
political gatherings since his release, but the government Sunday
lifted the restrictions for one week. He flew to Johannesburg on
Monday from his hometown of Port Elizabeth.
   The other seven were released unconditionally and have spoken
out freely on behalf of their guerrilla movement. They have
endorsed the ANC's use of violence as part of its campaign to end
white-minority domination and have demanded a series of concessions
from the government as a precondition for negotiations.
   The eight men met with other anti-apartheid leaders for more
than three hours behind closed doors at a community center in
Soweto. They engaged in ``an in-depth exploration of the way
forward,'' according to a statement issued by a coalition of
activists.
   Mbeki and five of those freed this month received life sentences
in 1964, along with paramount ANC leader Nelson Mandela, after
being convicted of treason for planning anti-government sabotage.
Mandela remains imprisoned, although the government is considering
his release.
   His freed co-defendants include Walter Sisulu, 77; Andrew
Mlangeni, 63; Raymond Mhlaba, 68; Ahmed Kathrada, 60; and Elias
Motsaoledi, 65.
   Also released Oct. 15 and present at Monday's meeting were
Wilton Mkwayi, 66, convicted of sabotage in a separate 1964 trial,
and Oscar Mpetha, 80, who began a five-year sentence for terrorism
in 1985.
   The unconditional release of the ANC leaders and the
government's decision to allow Sunday's rally have been depicted by
South African newspapers as a de facto legalization of the movement.
   Government officials have made clear in recent days they no
longer expect the ANC to make a formal repudiation of violence as a
precondition for joining negotiations. President F.W. de Klerk said
Monday that groups such as the ANC group could join the political
process by committing themselves to the concept of peaceful
solutions.
   ``If perspective participants in the negotiation process insist
on victories before entering negotiations, success will evade us,''
he told a party congress. ``What is necessary is a change of
heart.''
   He said the ANC, if it distanced itself from violence, could
help achieve its demand for lifting of the state of emergency.
   De Klerk has offered to negotiate a new constitution that will
extend political rights to the disenfranchised black majority. He
envisions a system which stops short of one-person, one-vote and
provides whites with some type of veto power over major policy
decisions.
</TEXT>
