<FILEID>AP-NR-10-23-89 1558EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-PostalPictures     10-23 0259</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Postal Pictures,240</SECOND>
<HEAD>For Release At 6:30 p.m. EDT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Post Office to Issue First Picture Postal Card</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Postal Service has decided to start
selling picture postal cards for the first time, entering a
business private firms have found lucrative for decades.
   The government agency will issue only a few cards, however. It
says it doesn't plan on jumping into the market to compete
nationwide for sales of the cards that are tourist favorites,
bearing beautiful photos of local attractions in cities across the
land, to make the folks back home envious.
   But visitors to Washington, and others interested in Washington
landmarks, will be able to purchase two official government picture
postal cards featuring the White House and the Jefferson Memorial.
   The White House card will go on sale Nov. 30 and the Jefferson
Memorial card Dec. 2, both being issued in Washington. The cards
will sell for 50 cents apiece which includes 15-cents postage.
   The government has sold plain postal cards for years, of course,
and recently many have carried colorful commemorative designs in
the corner. The new cards merely expand that to photos filling one
side of the card.
   Privately made cards will remain on sale, of course.
   Buyers will still have a wide choice of post cards featuring
many different photos of the White House and Jefferson Memorial.
The difference will be that the two postal cards, sold by the
government, include the 15-cent postage already printed on the
card, while a stamp has to be added to privately produced cards.
</TEXT>
