<DOCNO> AP891023-0105 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-23-89 1605EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Terrorism-Ceremony     10-23 0222</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Terrorism-Ceremony,210</SECOND>
<HEAD>Terrorism's Targets Remembered in Arlington Ceremony</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Families who have lost loved ones in terrorist
attacks gathered Monday to pray for peace on the sixth anniversary
of the devastating bombing of the U.S. Marine barracks in Lebanon.
   ``Terrorist acts ... can never be justified, can never be
condoned,'' said Ambassador Morris D. Busby, the State Department's
top counter-terrorism official.
   Busby placed a remembrance wreath at Arlington National
Cemetery, where the ceremony was held under brilliantly sunny skies.
   Many of the participants wore buttons inscribed with ``Beirut
Connection,'' signifying they had lost friends of relatives in the
terrorist attack on the Marine barracks in Beirut on Oct. 23, 1983.
   Joan Muffler's son, John, was one of the 241 servicemen killed
when a suicide bomber drove a bomb-laden truck crashed through the
barracks' gates. Fundamentalist Shiites claimed responsibility.
   Mrs. Muffler, a Philadelphia resident, said families stay in
touch with each other through a three-times-a-year newsletter.
   ``The pain is still fresh,'' said Aphrodite Tsaris, whose
daughter, Alexis, died when a bomb exploded on Pan Am Flight 103
over Scotland last December.
   But the incident has given the victims ``a renewed resolve to
effect change,'' replacing terrorism with peace, she said.
   The event was sponsored by No Greater Love, a non-profit,
humanitarian organization that tries to help the victims of
terrorism.
</TEXT>
