<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Ambulance     10-23 0253</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Ambulance,0261</SECOND>
<HEAD>London Ambulance Stations Paralyzed By Job Action</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police and volunteers answered dozens of emergency
calls Monday after a pay dispute involving ambulance drivers and
attendants shut down most ambulance stations in London, officials
said.
   Police helped a heart attack victim, women in labor and people
who had suffered minor injuries, a Scotland Yard spokesman said. In
all, more than 50 calls were answered.
   ``It looks like we're not really encountering too many
difficulties and we're coping OK,'' he said.
   Police converted about 30 vans into temporary ambulances
carrying stretchers, first-aid kits and oxygen, and staffed by
officers trained in first aid. But the officers were not qualified
to administer drugs intravenously or operate defibrillators used to
stimulate the heart.
   Ambulance workers have refused to work overtime for the past
five weeks and have rejected a 6.5 percent pay offer, demanding
instead an 11.5 percent raise. London ambulance workers with five
years' seniority are paid $16,906 a year.
   The workers' unions said they were ready to answer emergency
calls, but ambulance chiefs decided to suspend employees without
pay when they refused to handle other routine duties.
   Suspended crews then staged sit-ins at their stations, said the
unions' chief negotiator, Roger Poole.
   The pay dispute paralyzed 62 of London's 71 ambulance stations,
officials said.
   ``I would implore the ambulance men and women in London that
they have made their point and now is the time to go back to
work,'' said Tom Crosby, head of the London ambulance fleet.
</TEXT>
