<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs Radnor-dated 2nd item to CORRECT university location.</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release at 6 p.m. EDT</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RADNOR, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Daphne Maxwell Reid, co-star of CBS's
``Snoops,'' said she still has a ``bitter taste'' over what she
felt were racially motivated snubs when she was named Northwestern
University homecoming queen 22 years ago.
   ``I walked up, and the (university) president stuck a crown of
roses on my head and looked at me in total shock,'' she said in an
interview for the Oct. 28 edition of TV Guide.
   ``No one said anything to me. No one congratulated me. It was
like I had the plague,'' she said, adding that she was one of 36
blacks among 6,000 students at the Evanston, Ill., school. ``I was
presented with a cup, but it didn't have my name on it, and it
still doesn't have my name on it, and it's 22 years.''
   Ms. Maxwell Reid, whose co-star is her husband, Tim Reid, said
Northwestern today has ``changed and it's a fine school. But I
still have a bitter taste.''
