<FIRST>r w AM-Arms-Terrorists     10-23 0238</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Arms-Terrorists,230</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Approves Tighter Restrictions on Foreign Weapons Sales</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House voted Monday to tighten restrictions
on weapons sales to countries that support terrorism, approving
legislation that was spawned by the Reagan administration's
arms-for-hostages deal with Iran.
   The bill, expected to be approved later by the Senate, would
strengthen the current ban on arms sales to countries officially
designated as repeatedly supporting international terrorist acts.
That list now includes Iran, Libya, Syria, Cuba, North Korea and
South Yemen. Both government and private sales are affected.
   The measure was approved by a voice vote.
   It also would put tighter controls on the president's ability to
waive the prohibitions, requiring that the ban be lifted only if
national security requires it, and then only after Congress is
notified.
   Current law controlling arms sales abroad is ``sloppy and
confusing,'' said Rep. Howard Berman, D-Calif., who sponsored the
bill in an effort to eliminate the loopholes that allowed the U.S.
sale of missiles to Iran in 1986.
   The measure imposes new penalties on violators and requires more
detailed reporting of arms exports, including authority for
transfers of U.S. weapons from the initial purchaser to a third
country.
   It is similar to legislation passed last year by the House, but
which died in the Senate. Berman said the measure has been endorsed
by the White House this time around, and is now more likely to
receive Senate approval.
</TEXT>
