<SECOND>AM-South Yemen-US,0291</SECOND>
<HEAD>South Yemeni Says Talks Under Way to Resume Ties With U.S.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KUWAIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Yemeni Prime Minister Yassine Saeed No'man
said Monday his Marxist country has begun talks with the United
States seeking the restoration of diplomatic relations ruptured two
decades ago.
   At the end of a three-day official visit to Kuwait, No'man told
reporters that the talks with Washington were launched in New York
10 days ago on the sidelines of the U.N. General Assembly debates.
South Yemen's U.N. representative, Abdullah al-Ashkal, and U.S.
diplomats were involved in the negotiations.
   The prime minister said more meetings will be held in two weeks
but did not specify a venue or identify the officials involved.
   He said his country set no conditions for the resumption of
ties, adding that ``the reasons which led to the rupture should no
longer figure.'' He did not elaborate.
   In Washington, State Department spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler
confirmed a meeting recently took place between U.N. Ambassador
Thomas Pickering and South Yemen's U.N. ambassador. But, she said,
``these discussions were not negotiations and we did not raise the
issue of resuming diplomatic relations.''
   ``We expressed concern about terrorism and about South Yemen's
relations with its neighbors who are friends of the U.S.,'' she
said. ``We expect further discussions with South Yemen but no
further meetings have been scheduled.''
   Aden ruptured ties with Washington in 1969, two years after
indepndence from Britain and the subsequent rise to power of a
Marxist government.
   South and North Yemen, and Djibouti share control of the
strategic Bab al-Mandeb entrance to the Red Sea. South Yemen became
a major facility for Soviet naval units in the Indian Ocean in the
past two decades.
