<FIRST>r i AM-Poland-Lodz     10-23 0373</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Lodz,0384</SECOND>
<HEAD>Solidarity May Get Mayor's Job in Poland's Second-Largest City</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity could gain control of city hall
in Lodz, Poland's second-largest city, following a meeting Monday
in which local officials agreed to leave the choice up to Prime
Minister Tadeusz Mazowiecki.
   A meeting by representatives of Solidarity, the Communist Party
and other political groups decided after a lengthy discussion that
``the mayoral crisis ... is ripe for a decision by the prime
minister,'' the state PAP news agency said.
   Organizer Andrzej Grabski said some names were discussed at the
meeting that he could not reveal. Based on the discussion, he said
he was optimistic the matter would be settled soon.
   The appointment would end a nearly five-month impasse over the
selection of mayor of Lodz. It could also mark Solidarity's first
victory in taking control of provincial and municipal governments
from the Communist Party.
   Solidarity already has assumed leadership of the national
government after the election of Solidarity adviser Mazowiecki as
prime minister Aug. 24, and fully democratic elections for local
governing councils are being planned for sometime next year.
   With communist power on the wane in the central government and
in government-owned enterprises, provincial and municipal
governments remain the last bastion of communist power.
   The post of mayor for the city of 850,000 people has been vacant
since May 29, when the previous communist city president was ousted
in a no-confidence vote following complaints of poor administration.
   An Oct. 11 attempt to elect a mayor failed when the
communist-dominated city council refused to approve either of the
two rival Solidarity-linked candidates approved by Mazowiecki.
   Mazowiecki earlier had declined to nominate either of two
candidates proposed for the post by the Communist Party.
   Grabski said he could not guarantee the council would not reject
Mazowiecki's nominee again, but he said a consensus emerged during
Monday's discussion to give Mazowiecki ``full trust'' in his
decision.
   In the past, all provincial and municipal governments were under
the central government and the Communist Party.
   Under reforms being prepared by Solidarity and the Mazowiecki
government, local governments would be elected in fully democratic
voting by their communities and they in turn would choose mayors
and other local officers independent of Warsaw.
</TEXT>
