<FIRST>u w PM-SFQuake-FederalAid 9thLd-Writethru a0645</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SF Quake-Federal Aid, 9th Ld-Writethru, a0645,840</SECOND>
<HEAD>Californians Want $3.8 Billion, White House $2.5 Billion</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: TOPS with 10 new grafs on proposal, revising total figure from
$3.6 billion to $3.8 billion and including comments from Darman; picks
up 10th graf pvs: ``It sounds ....</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   California lawmakers today asked Congress for
an initial $3.8 billion package of federal aid for the
earthquake-ravaged San Francisco Bay area, while the Bush
administration proposed up to $2.5 billion in relief.
   The House Appropriations Committee arranged a late-afternoon
meeting on a bipartisan package put together by California's
47-member congressional delegation, with action by the full House
scheduled Tuesday.
   White House aides and committee leaders worked in advance of the
session to try to reach a compromise on the aid figure.
   ``Our current estimate is that the total federal contribution
will probably have to be a little over $2.4 billion,'' White House
Budget Director Richard Darman said upon emerging from a meeting
with Rep. Jamie Whitten, D-Miss., chairman of the appropriations
committee.
   ``That's obviously subject to refinement,'' Darman said, adding
the White House wants to avoid the ``kind of situation where you
have a bidding war and then a veto threat.''
   Rep. Leon Panetta, D-Calif., the House Budget Committee
chairman, said the Californians' package included $1.1 billion of
direct aid through the Federal Emergency Management Agency for a
wide variety of relief programs and $1 billion for rebuilding
highways and bridges.
   Another $1.2 billion in disaster loans would be provided through
the Small Business Administration for rebuilding damaged homes and
businesses. The bill also includes $100 million in loan guarantees
for public and private companies in low-income areas and $400
million in discretionary spending. President Bush would determine
how the discretionary money is spent.
   In an indication that Congress and the administration may not be
far apart, Darmon said his figure did not include ``raising the
ceiling on the ability of the Small Business Administration to
issue loans.''
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said up to $1 billion
could be taken from existing programs, including $250 million of
unspent money authorized for aiding victims of Hurricane Hugo.
   He said the adminstration was abandoning an effort to assemble
its own relief package and would work with Congress in fashioning
one because of the shortness of time involved.
   ``It sounds to me they are trying to set a parameter to cut a
deal,'' Panetta said of the White House proposal. ``Ultimately I
think we will resolve a final number between the administration and
Congress.''
   Rep. Jerry Lewis, R-Calif., chairman of the House Republican
Conference, described the administration's $2.5 billion figure as
an early number reached before the damage estimates escalated over
the weekend.
   ``It's my feeling the $2.5 billion, in the mind's eye of the
administration, has already been raised,'' Lewis said.
   Panetta, whose district south of San Francisco suffered severe
damage in last Tuesday's earthquake, said the aid package still
could become a vehicle for raising gasoline taxes or other levies.
But he acknowledged the prospects for that are uncertain.
   ``The bottom line is that we are going to need to develop more
resources,'' he said. ``If not, you're looking at this basically
feeding into the deficit. I don't like that approach, but our first
priority is to help the victims of this kind of disaster.''
   ``There is an urgent need for help for people now,'' Sen. Pete
Wilson, R-Calif., told the Senate Environment and Public Works
subcommittee on transportation and natural resources. ``FEMA is
stretched very thin.''
   Bush last Friday declined on several occasions to say whether he
would consider breaking his ``no new taxes'' pledge to help pay for
disaster relief, saying only that the government would do what it
had to do.
   However, Fitzwater said today that, ``We do not intend to raise
taxes'' to deal with the earthquake aftermath.
   ``President Bush viewed the human agony and the physical
destruction associated with this disaster'' when he toured the area
on Friday, the spokesman said.
   ``He is committed to providing all the federal help that is
possible'' short of proposing a tax increase, Fitzwater said.
   U.S. officials said the administration, as in the congressional
plan, would propose tapping the $12 billion federal Highway Trust
Fund to help California rebuild highways and bridges damaged in
last Tuesday's quake.
   The federal gasoline tax is the major source of revenue for the
trust fund.
   Barbara Clay, a spokeswoman for the Office of Management and
Budget, said OMB officials had worked through the weekend and were
still at work today on coming up with a preliminary cost estimate
for the damage.
   However, Sen. Alan Cranston, D-Calif., warned reporters on
Sunday in San Francisco, ``Unfortunately, all the cost cannot be
covered'' by government aid.
   ``There will be some loss,'' said Cranston, who predicted the
federal government would provide $3.5 billion in aid but estimated
property loss and damage to roads and highways at more than $7
billion.
   In addition to the amount of aid to be determined, Congress must
also decide how to raise the funds.
   Bush sidestepped questions Friday about whether he would support
a tax increase to finance the package. Some lawmakers have proposed
an exemption in the Gramm-Rudman deficit-cutting law to accommodate
the aid needed.
</TEXT>
