<FIRST>r w AM-Fernandez     10-23 0460</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fernandez,440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Justice Department Denies Unnecessary Delays in CIA Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department on Monday called
``totally off-base'' the Iran-Contra prosecutor's contention that
Attorney General Dick Thornburgh is using procedural delays to
thwart the trial of a former CIA agent.
   The Justice Department's ``effort, as it has been all along is
to protect the national security of the United States while
allowing the trial to go forward. That's our bottom-line objective
and we are trying to bring that about,'' said spokesman David
Runkel.
   ``I think the attorney general feels that those comments that
were made in the court filing last week to be totally off-base,''
Runkel said of the charge made in court pleadings by independent
counsel Lawrence E. Walsh.
   ``We are having discussions with a number of people on how best
to resolve the case'' of former CIA agent Joseph Fernandez, Runkel
said.
   The spokesman refused to say whether the Justice Department was
pressing the CIA and other intelligence agencies to release
material the CIA wants kept secret.
   Walsh, asking a federal appeals court to lift a stay in
Fernandez' trial, accused Thornburgh of using ``unjustifiable
delaying tactics'' designed ``to tie this case in a knot of endless
litigation.''
   Thornburgh was much less emphatic when asked about Walsh's
charge, saying: ``the court record speaks for itself.''
   Mary Belcher, a spokeswoman for Walsh, refused to comment.
   In his filing last week, Walsh asked the 4th U.S. Circuit Court
of Appeals to rescind its order granting the Justice Department at
least another month's delay to give Thornburgh's attorneys more
time to ponder secrecy issues raised by the Fernandez case.
   At issue is a trial judge's order that the defense could
disclose the locations of three CIA stations in Central America
when Fernandez was station chief in Costa Rica.
   The Justice Department wants to block references to the
locations during the trial even though they have been publicized.
Walsh said the CIA was merely trying to preserve a ``diplomatic
fiction'' by refusing to allow references to the stations to be
made in court.
   The appellate court ruled last month that the Justice Department
couldn't appeal the trial judge's order, saying Thornburgh could
exercise the politically distasteful option of filing an affidavit
blocking release of the secrets.
   Such an affidavit would likely result in dismissal of the
charges against Fernandez, who is accused of lying to the CIA and
to a presidential commission about his role in helping set up an
arms-supply network for the Nicaraguan rebels.
   In seeking a 30-day extension in the deadline on requesting an
appeal of the 4th Circuit's ruling, the department said the
solicitor general needed more time to decide whether to seek a
rehearing of the case.
</TEXT>
