<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     10-23 0341</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0351</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROSAMOND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chili is a major component of life in
the Southwest, so what's a man from the cooler Pacific Northwest
doing winning the $25,000 first prize in the World's Championship
Chili Cookoff?
   Maybe Sunday's weather at this former gold mining town on the
edge of the Mojave Desert _ cool and rainy, just like his home of
Seattle _ inspired winner Philip M. Walter.
   He was among 82 winners of prior state, regional or foreign
cookoffs who were entered in the annual event sponsored by the
International Chili Society, whose logo shows fire coming out of
the top of a pot instead of beneath it.
   Judges, including cast members from the television soap operas
``General Hospital'' and ``The Young and the Restless,'' wore
holsters equipped with bottles of stomach antacid.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MILLEDGEVILLE, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cartographer Idrova DeSoto was one of
the first to investigate the land's ins and outs, and the Golden
Age came when B. Wright Bach finished his ``Unfinished Symphony.''
   Those facts, along with everything everyone ever wanted to know
about the Islands of Pun and the Free Associations _ beginning with
their discovery by Hugo Yurway and Al Gomine _ is summed up in a
134-page manuscript titled ``Isthmus Be the Place.''
   The manuscript goes with a Pun Map that was put together five
years ago by Richard Amor of the forensics services division at
Central State Hospital and Will Humphrey, a music director at
Southside Elementary School in Milledgeville.
   At first Amor and Humphrey concentrated on recognizable place
names such as Mary Tyler Moor and Hugh Downs. Then they added old
sayings and fairy tale characters.
   Finally the map turned into something they could hawk. The
$7.50-per-copy map was copyrighted in 1984.
   Their as-yet unpublished ``Isthmus'' provides practical
information: fly the Receding Airline to get to Pun, don't forget
your umbrella during the springtime Claude Rains and try Pun City's
subway, Inner Tube. And be sure to see the fabled Triganomma Trees
and their famous square roots.
</TEXT>
