<FILEID>AP-NR-10-23-89 1620EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-SFQuake-BuckBallad     10-23 0238</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SF Quake-Buck Ballad,230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quake Survivor Honored in Song</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The grit of beefy Buck Helm was extolled by
a balladeer inspired by the longshoreman's miraculous rescue from
the rubble of an earthquake-flattened freeway.
   Bandleader Jimmy Price wrote ``The Ballad of Buck Helm'' for
crooning Monday at the New Orleans Room of the Fairmount Hotel, and
he also planned to record the tune.
   ``The idea came to me like a flash,'' said Price, 59, a native
San Franciscan. ``I popped out of bed at 6 a.m. (Sunday) and
frantically pulled out my music paper. It was like I was inspired
from on high.
   ``His story really moved me,'' Price said. ``Everybody's heads
were down after the earthquake, and then we had Buck Helm happen to
us.''
   Helm, 57, was plucked Saturday from the collapsed section of
Interstate 880 after 90 hours behind the wheel of his partially
crushed Chevrolet Sprint.
   The lyrics:
   ``Hey, Buck, we're pulling for you,
   ``Your heart is pulling us through,
   ``Our hopes were down, but you
   ``Opened our eyes to tomorrow.
   
   ``Four days down in the tomb,
   ``Looking in the face of doom,
   ``Then that small beam of light,
   ``Said everything would be all right, all right.
   
   ``Bobby said, `Don't worry, be happy,'
   ``But trouble came to shake us around.
   ``Then through that darkness before the light,
   ``You showed us that things would be all right, all right.''
</TEXT>
