<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-Spencer     10-23 0225</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Spencer,0231</SECOND>
<HEAD>Owner of Landmark Coffeehouse Dies at 66</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lena Spencer, whose Caffe Lena was
a training ground for a generation of folksingers that include Bob
Dylan, Arlo Guthrie and Maria Muldaur, died Monday. She was 66.
   Ms. Spencer died at Ellis Hospital in Schenectady of injuries
she suffered when she fell down a flight of stairs Sept. 10 at her
coffeehouse in Saratoga Springs, hospital spokeswoman Christine
DeCarlo said.
   Ms. Spencer and her then-husband, Bill Spencer, opened the
coffeehouse in May 1960, providing a needed stage early in the
careers of such folksingers as Dylan, Guthrie, Muldaur, Don McLean,
Pete Seeger, Ramblin' Jack Elliot, David Bromberg, Steve Goodman
and John Phillips.
   ``The Caffe is my whole existence, the be-all and end-all of my
life,'' Ms. Spencer said in a January 1989 interview.
   She and her husband divorced in the mid 1960s.
   When the popularity of folk music declined in the late 1970s,
Caffe Lena suffered and Ms. Spencer suffered as well. She earned
$32 for a bit role in the movie ``Ironweed,'' which was filmed in
the Albany area, and spent the last several years of her life
living in a back room of her coffeehouse.
   Ms. Spencer is survived by two brothers. Funeral arrangements
were incomplete Monday, but burial was planned at St. Mary's
Cemetery in Milford.
</TEXT>
