<FILEID>AP-NR-10-23-89 1652EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-SF-Quake-FerryCommute 2ndLd-Writethru a0651 10-23 0634</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SF-Quake-Ferry Commute, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0651</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nausea Replaces Romance</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf, bgn, The triple-deck ..., to CORRECT typo in
monohull</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Commuters tried many unfamiliar routes to their
jobs in San Francisco Monday. Associated Press reporter Rich
Cartiere made his way by ferry and filed this account.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By RICH CARTIERE</NOTE>
<NOTE>Associated Press Writer</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ABOARD THE CATALINA EMPRESS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Boarding one of the first
ferryboats pressed into emergency service Monday to carry commuters
across San Francisco Bay, I expected a romantic ride through the
fog. Reality brought nausea.
   The worst storm of the season struck just an hour before tens of
thousands of residents in Alameda and Contra Costa counties east of
San Francisco began the trek to work.
   This 127-foot ocean vessel, one of 14 being run on routes unused
by ferries for decades, met blustery winds, giant swells that
crashed across the bow and waves that sent it constantly lurching
from side to side. The song of the journey should be, ``I Left My
Stomach on San Francisco Bay.''
   The 55-minute voyage, made necessary because of the collapse of
a 50-foot section of the vital San Francisco-Oakland Bay Bridge
during last Tuesday's quake, was twice what was expected.
   The triple-deck monohull pulled away from the dock 40 minutes
late because of weather worries and a low passenger count. The
captain announced some boats might be turned back. A big groan.
   I arrived dockside before dawn, naively thinking I could relive
idyllic bay crossings created by writers like Jack London and in
such classic movies as Humphrey Bogart's ``Dark Passage.''
   I wasn't alone.
   ``I've just been through hell, but heck, I have to admit I made
it through it; it can only get better, this can't get much worse,''
said an ashen-faced John Trowbridge, 27, of Alameda, who came onto
the deck to alleviate sea sickness.
   I moved up to the bow, where a giant swell drenched me. Since I
was downwind, I figured it would be best to remain there in case I
lost my breakfast.
   The ferry, with a capacity of 700 people and carrying 338, was
supposed to dock at the Union Ferry Building in San Francisco. But
waves craching there forced the boats to divert to Fisherman's
Wharf.
   Altogether my commute _ from hearth to work station _ took 3{
hours. I used to do it in 45 minutes. At the wharf, I tried to
catch a cable car into downtown, only to find it shut down. I
walked another seven blocks in the drenching rain and caught a city
bus to work.
   Roughing it across the bay didn't dampen everybody's spirits.
   ``Considering everything, my commute has really gone smooth,''
said Maggie Faulkner, 46, of Oakland.
   Karen Meyer, 42, of Oakland, used to work on Long Island, N.Y.,
ferries, and was unflappable.
   ``Everybody's just going to have to go into slow motion,'' she
said. ``That includes all the bosses.''
   Elena Pierini, 44, of Oakland, recalled taking ferries to
Berkeley as a child. She relived those memories Monday morning.
   ``This makes up for all the bad things that came out of the
earthquake,'' said the San Francisco General Hospital research
nurse.
   The weather was trying for Dick Simpson, vice president of
marketing for Crowley Maritime, which operated the ferries. He rode
the Catalina Empress, which normally operates between Long Beach
and Catalina Island in Southern California.
   ``Mother nature is testing our mental state; normally this bay
is as smooth as glass at this time,'' said Simpson. About 3,000
people used the ferries Monday morning, Crowley said.
   The bay's ferryboat industry to the East bay, which began in
1863, grew to include hundreds of boats at its height in the early
1930s. It was discontinued shortly after the Bay bridge opened in
1937.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891023-0131 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-23-89 1933EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-NuclearLeakage     10-23 0640</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nuclear Leakage,0659</SECOND>
<HEAD>Official Worries that Salt Dome May Be Leaking Radiation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BAXTERVILLE, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An underground cavity in a salt dome
where two nuclear weapons were tested in the 1960s may be leaking
radioactive materials, state officials say.
   At least one federal official says there is no problem.
   ``I think a study should be done to answer questions we still
have about whether there are cracks in the dome and whether it's
leaking,'' said James Pinson, who helped the Department of Energy
conduct what he calls an inconclusive 1979-1980 study at the site.
   Pinson, a nuclear chemist at the University of Southern
Mississippi at Hattiesburg, said the study of the Tatum Salt Dome
left many unanswered questions about activities at the test site.
   Another underground salt formation, near Carlsbad, N.M., is the
site of the federal government's Waste Isolation Pilot Plant, a
complex of chambers intended for permanent storage of military
radioactive waste. The WIPP was supposed to open last October, but
questions about the long-term safety of the salt bed and
transportation of waste to the site have delayed the opening.
   Tests near the Tatum dome show tritium levels are increasing in
overflow ponds when they should be decreasing, he said.
   Some scientists fear the formation of solid salt may be cracked,
allowing potentially hazardous radioactive isotopes such as tritium
to escape from the cavity formed by the explosions a half-mile
beneath Lamar County in 1964 and 1966.
   Another theory is that the salt is squeezing together, forcing
radioactive brine from within the dome up toward the surface,
Pinson said.
   Test samples taken by the state Board of Health have found
relatively high levels of tritium at the surface above the salt
dome during the dry season. These levels diminish as the wet season
encroaches and water runs off into swollen creeks and overflow
ponds near ground zero.
   Since the levels of tritium appear to be restored each year,
some experts theorize a leak in the dome continually replenishes
the isotope in soil near the surface.
   Federal guidelines for safe drinking water limit tritium to
20,000 picocuries per liter. A picocurie is a measure of the rate
at which atoms disintegrate radioactively.
   Tritium has been found at levels as high as 1 million picocuries
per liter in mud around ground zero, the point directly above the
blast chamber, records show.
   ``Obviously there's a pretty good source of tritium down there
at the site,'' said Ron Forsyth, manager of the state Energy Plan
Development. ``And we've been asking ourselves for a decade ...
where it's coming from. Whether it's leaking? Of course that's
something we wonder.''
   The dome is free of leaks, said Stuart Black, nuclear radiation
advisor to the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency. ``That's a
pretty good salt dome,'' he said.
   Stuart said EPA tests have not found hazardous levels of tritium.
   Of the seasonal cycle of tritium, he said: ``We don't consider
that to be a problem.''
   The pattern of tritium found in shallow test holes several yards
from ground zero is also difficult to explain, said Bob Bell, a
health physicist for the state Department of Health's Radiological
Health Division.
   Bell said tests taken the farthest from ground zero should
reflect the lowest levels of tritium.
   But he found tritium levels decrease in tests of shallow wells
along the periphery of the dome site, then increase in wells
farther away.
   ``We would not expect this activity to show up,'' Bell said,
``and the Department of Energy is in fact trying to evaluate why we
are seeing these levels so far from ground zero.''
   Two non-nuclear natural gas explosions detonated inside the dome
on Feb. 2, 1969, and April 19, 1970, may have released ``some
radioactivity formerly trapped in recrystallized salt on the walls
and floors of the nuclear cavity,'' a 1978 DOE report says.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
