<HEAD>Man Due To Stand Trial in Alleged Defense Fraud Scheme Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   J. Lee Bonoff, a key figure in an
alleged defense fraud scheme who was due to go on trial this month,
has died at the age of 62.
   Bonoff, who died Saturday at a sister's house in Madison, Conn.,
was president of Pawtucket-based Carol Cable Co. from 1981 until he
retired in 1985.
   He was indicted in February on charges linked to an alleged
fraud and kickback scheme to sell defective cable to the military.
Two other Carol Cable employees pleaded guilty to charges in the
scheme, and the company paid $1.5 million to settle a civil suit
filed by the federal government.
   The cause of death was not immediately available, but Carl
Jordan, assistant police chief in Madison, said ``there were no
signs of violence.''
   Carl Lunkenheimer, an assistant U.S. attorney in Philadelphia,
where the charges against Bonoff were filed, said he would move to
dismiss the case as soon as he obtained a death certificate.
   Bonoff had been scheduled to go on trial Oct. 30.
   Bonoff is survived by his wife, Helene, a daughter and a son.
   Services were held Monday.
</TEXT>
