<FILEID>AP-NR-10-23-89 2001EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Mammograms     10-23 0325</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mammograms,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lobbying Urged to Retain Medicare Coverage for Exams</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KAREN BALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Women nationwide were urged Monday to lobby
Congress to salvage Medicare coverage of breast cancer tests from
the catastrophic health insurance program the House recently voted
to repeal.
   ``If this were a man's issue, it wouldn't be a problem,''
Deborah Dingell, chairwoman of the National Women's Health Resource
Center, said following a ceremony honoring people who have raised
awareness about breast cancer, which strikes one in 10 American
women.
   Rep. Mary Rose Oakar, D-Ohio, was cited for her efforts in
Congress, such as including mammography tests in the Medicare
Catastrophic Coverage Act of 1988.
   Ms. Oakar, noting that the House recently voted to repeal the
act, urged the 275 doctors, community leaders and others on hand to
lobby Congress to accept a Senate provision retaining coverage for
breast cancer tests. She called on women across the country to join
the lobbying effort.
   House and Senate negotiators are trying to work out differences
on the program. The mammography program would initially cost $60
million but would ultimately save millions more through early
detection that would save hospitalization costs, Ms. Oakar said.
   If Congress allows mammograms to remain covered by the insurance
program, then Medicare, as of Jan. 1, would pay for the tests every
two years for women aged 65 and over. Women over age 35 who are
eligible for Medicare because of disability would also be covered
for exams, either yearly or every two years depending on their risk.
   According to the American Cancer Society, breast cancer will be
diagnosed in 142,000 women this year and will cause 43,000 deaths.
   Susan Ford Bales, spokeswoman for National Breast Cancer
Awareness Month, said 37 percent of American women over age 40 have
never had a mammogram, even though medical experts say breast
cancer deaths could be reduced by one-third if all women over 40
had regular mammograms.
</TEXT>
