<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     10-23 0355</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0364</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rain Adds Insult to Injury in the San Francisco Bay Area</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A storm system moving inland from the Gulf of Alaska spread rain
across much of the northern and central Pacific Coast region
Monday, with some locally heavy downpours.
   Heavy rain in the San Francisco Bay area combined with the soil
movements of last week's earthquake to increase the danger of
mudslides. One landslide closed a section of California 17 in Santa
Clara County, southeast of San Francisco, state officials reported.
   Rain fell across the Pacific Northwest and the northern half of
California during the afternoon. Thunderstorms produced wind gusts
to 66 mph at Redding, Calif., and thunderstorms also were reported
in the area of Sacramento, Calif.
   Heavier rainfall for the six hours up to 2 p.m. EDT was 1.80
inches at Crescent City, Calif., 1.14 inches at San Francisco and
1.09 inches at Redding, Calif.
   Inland, a winter storm warning was posted into Tuesday for
elevations above 7,000 feet in the Lake Tahoe and Truckee area of
California and Nevada, where up to 2 feet of snow was possible.
   A winter storm warning also was posted for elevations above
7,000 feet in the northern Sierra Nevada range, and the Mount
Shasta and Siskiyou mountain region of northern California.
   A gale warning was in effect along the northern California
coast, and a high wind warning was issued in Nevada for the Reno
and Carson City area. Wind gusted to 67 mph at Reno during the
morning.
   Indian summer weather prevailed across the central part of the
nation with temperatures warming into the 70s, and Texas warmed
into the 80s.
   Temperatures warmed into the 50s and 60s in the East, with
readings in the 70s across the Southeast, a day after a cold snap
that saw temperatures in the 30s as far south as northern Florida.
   Only vestiges of the cold air remained Monday in Florida, where
Miami had a record overnight low of 61, and Fort Myers tied its
record of 55.
   Monday's low for the Lower 48 states was 13 degrees above zero
at Gunnison, Colo.
</TEXT>
