<FIRST>r w AM-BarbaraBush     10-23 0440</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Barbara Bush,440</SECOND>
<HEAD>First Lady Says President Shies From Confrontation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush is ``like all men now, he
doesn't like confrontation'' and seldom argues at home, first lady
Barbara Bush said in a television interview broadcast Monday.
   Mrs. Bush, interviewed by entertainer Oprah Winfrey, also said a
role model is former first lady Lady Bird Johnson, that she seldom
worries about security and that the White House is ``the most
beautiful place in the world.''
   Asked by Winfrey whether she and the president argued, Mrs. Bush
responded: ``Not much, after 44 years'' of marriage. ``We sort of
grew up together.''
   ``He listens,'' she continued. ``He's like all men now, he
doesn't like confrontation. It's very hard to argue when only one
fellow will argue.''
   ``I'm feistier than George,'' she said.
   Mrs. Bush said that she was ``the enforcer'' in the Bush
household when their five children were growing up, disciplining
them and even spanking them on occasion.
   ``I didn't spank hard, but I spanked,'' she said.
   ``I gave them enormous stablity (and) a lot of advice, none of
which they took,'' she said.
   She said that listening to her children was tedious at times,
``mine were so boring, they wanted to tell you the whole movie.''
   And, before selecting their present wives, her four sons
sometimes brought girlfriends home who were ``real dogs,'' Mrs.
Bush said. ``I treated them like they were neat nice people.''
   The first lady's press secretary, Anna Perez, said the interview
for the syndicated television show was taped two weeks earlier.
   Asked whom she most admired among other first ladies, Mrs. Bush
said, ``I think most often of Lady Bird Johnson. I've known her for
a number of years ... she lived a life very much like I lived.''
   ``She said ... if you can help people by talking about your
cause and making people aware of it, and if by chance it reflects
well on your husband, that's what life is all about. I like that.''
   She also praised Betty Ford for being ``very courageous'' and
called Nancy Reagan a ``very close friend. ... She really made the
White House sparkle. She fixed the plumbing and the electricity.
All those things you take for granted that I didn't have to do.''
   ``And I kind of admired old Bess (Truman). She did what she
wanted.''
   Asked about her concerns for the safety of her family,
especially in light of recent alleged threats from Colombian drug
lords, Mrs. Bush said: ``Why waste your time?''
   ``I have a great belief in God and enormous belief in the Secret
Service, in that order,'' she said.
</TEXT>
