<FIRST>u i AM-Nazis 1stLd-Writethru a0666 10-23 0778</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nazis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0666,0796</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rabbi Clashes With Right-Wingers at Nazi War Crimes Conference</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5-10 pvs `For Gryn ... Hetherington said' with 8 grafs
to UPDATE with new name of alleged criminal, where rabbi from. Picks up
graf 11 pvs, `Parliament is ...' DROPS final 3 grafs to TRIM</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDITH M. LEDERER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Right-wing extremists yelling that the Holocaust
was a lie had a shouting match Monday with a concentration camp
survivor outside an international conference on Nazi war crimes.
   ``You are Nazis! You are Nazi terrorists!'' shouted Rabbi Hugo
Gryn. ``You probably would have killed me.''
   Experts from the United States, Canada, Australia and Britain
had to pass the 14 protesters who were waving British flags,
shouting ``Six Million Lies!'' and passing out newspapers headlined
``Holocaust Story An Evil Hoax'' at the entrance to the Royal
Westminster Hotel.
   For Gryn of the West London Synagogue, who was born 59 years ago
in Czechoslovakia and spent 1944-45 in the Birkenau concentration
camp, it was too much.
   ``I lost my temper,'' he said. ``They're really obscene and
they're young, and the awful thing is, they would have put in the
gas pellets. They're the haters. What breeds them?''
   The clash highlighted some of the opposition to changing British
law to allow prosecution of alleged Nazi war criminals living in
Britain, the theme of a conference called ``Time For Justice''
sponsored by the All-Party Parliamentary War Crimes Group.
   Sir Thomas Hetherington, coauthor of a report recommending the
prosecution of alleged war criminals, said there is enough evidence
to prosecute three people living in Britain, whom he refused to
identify.
   He said three other cases that had been investigated in detail
needed further inquiries and another 75 cases should be
investigated. He also appealed for information on 46 alleged war
criminals whom his inquiry team had been unable to trace.
   ``I am quite unshaken on this, that having weighed all the pros
and cons, we in this country ought to legislate to take the
necessary jurisdictional powers,'' Hetherington said.
   Efriam Zuroff of the Los Angeles-based Simon Wiesenthal Center
said he had turned over the name of one more alleged Nazi war
criminal living in Britain to the British Home office on Monday.
   ``We're talking about a person who served in a unit which
carried out the mass murder of thousands upon thousands of innocent
men, women and children,'' he said in a British Broadcasting Corp.
television interview. He did not identify the person.
   Parliament is due to debate the war crimes report this autumn
and vote on whether to introduce legislation enabling prosecutions
to take place.
   Labor lawmaker Merlyn Rees, chairman of the Parliamentary War
Crimes Group, predicted victory for those favoring prosecution
would not be easy.
   ``I believe there will be those, particularly among the younger
generation, perhaps among the older generation, too, who will say
it is all 50 years ago,'' he said.
   Opening the conference on behalf of Home Secretary Douglas Hurd,
Home Office Minister John Patten gave a hint of the government's
position saying: ``It is his view and it is my view that we should
certainly forgive, but we should certainly not forget.''
   Patten led a string of condemnations of the flag-waving
protesters, saying they were trying ``to clothe their own attempts
to rewrite history in some form of public acceptance.''
   He added: ``I think what they are doing outside is perfectly
disgusting and I condemn it utterly in every way.''
   One demonstrator, Richard Edmonds, said they were all members of
the British National Party, a small white supremacist party.
   ``The gas chambers were lies produced by Britain and America to
justify their activities in World War II,'' Edmonds said. ``These
(war crimes) trials are absolutely wicked. They are trials based on
evidence of the KGB, and who believes them?''
   If Parliament approves legislation, Britain would be following
the United States, Canada, Australia, East Germany and West Germany
in prosecuting war criminals.
   ``It truly is an issue which should have no territorial
boundaries,'' said Neal Sher, director of the Office of Special
Investigation at the U.S. Justice Department.
   He said more than 1,200 people had been brought to the attention
of U.S. authorities. Using existing laws on extradition and
deportation, more than 30 war criminals had been kicked out, 35
others had been stripped of U.S. citizenship and 25 cases were in
the courts, he said.
   Sher stressed the importance of prosecuting all Nazi war
criminals, even the ``small fry.'' But he guessed that possibly
10,000 ``small fry'' Nazi criminals living in the United States
were getting away with their crimes because nobody knows who they
are.
</TEXT>
