<FILEID>AP-NR-10-23-89 1819EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-PostalTrial     10-23 0452</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Postal Trial,440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Consultant Had Details of Closed Postal Service Meetings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A consultant supplied a Texas company with
details of closed sessions of the U.S. Postal Service's governing
board, according to testimony at a criminal trial Monday.
   Robert Buzard, president of Electrocom Automation Inc. of
Arlington, Texas, testified that his firm hired lobbyist Mark Bragg
in the company's effort in 1985 to win hundreds of millions of
dollars in postal contracts.
   Bragg's business partner at the time was Lyn Nofziger, the
former White House political director in the Reagan administration
who was convicted of illegal lobbying in matters unrelated to the
postal service. Nofziger's conviction was overturned by a federal
appeals court in June. Bragg was a co-defendant at Nofziger's trial
and was acquitted.
   Electrocom's competitor, Recognition Equipment Inc., and two of
REI's top officers, are on trial in U.S. District Court for
conspiring to defraud the postal service in connection with the
award of automation contracts.
   Buzard testified that Electrocom hired Bragg for about a year
``to keep the playing field level'' in the competition with REI.
   At the time, REI had hired a politically well-connected
consultant, John Gnau, at the suggestion of then-board of governors
vice chairman Peter Voss. Voss later pleaded guilty to taking an
illegal gratuity from Gnau in connection with the competition for
the postal automation equipment.
   During one hectic week in the competition with REI in November
1985, Buzard said Bragg supplied him with names of governors who in
a closed session had given speeches in support of Electrocom.
   Buzard also acknowledged it was Bragg who reported to him that
REI's closed-door presentation to the board on the automation
contract hadn't been persuasive and had provided ``nothing new.''
   Buzard sought to deemphasize the information Bragg provided,
saying it dealt with the ``quality, not content'' of board of
governors' meetings.
   Under questioning from REI legal counsel John Cooney, Buzard
said he hadn't been aware the information Bragg was providing was
from meetings that were closed.
   Buzard said he never asked and that Bragg never said where he
got his information about board meetings.
   Buzard acknowledged that in 1986 he refused to identify Bragg by
name to postal inspectors investigating allegations of contract
irregularities. Buzard simply told them that Electrocom had hired a
Washington consultant who was ``well-placed.''
   Buzard said he refused to identify Bragg because the consultant
didn't want the identity of his clients disclosed.
   Electrocom has been awarded the work for the automation
equipment.
   In a brief interview, Bragg said he was unfamiliar with Buzard's
testimony and so would have no immediate comment.
   Outside the courtroom, Buzard declined to say how much
Electrocom had paid Bragg.
</TEXT>
