<FILEID>AP-NR-10-23-89 1837EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-SFQuake-Survivor 2ndLd-Writethru a0715 10-23 0943</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SF Quake-Survivor, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0715,940</SECOND>
<HEAD>Earthquake Survivor Amazes His Doctors</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs to UPDATE condition, comment from former
wife; picks up 5th graf pvs, `Helm, 57...' SUBS 17th graf pvs, `Inside,
Helm...' with 2 grafs to include quote from daughter.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto staffing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARNARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Buck Helm astounded his doctors Monday by
nodding his head to show he had no pain, despite being trapped for
90 hours in his tiny car under tons of concrete.
   ``In the next 24 to 48 hours, if he continues the way he is now,
he will be out of the woods,'' said Dr. Floyd Huen, medical
director at Highland General Hospital.
   ``His love for us and our love for him is one of the major
things that kept him going,'' his former wife, Lorrie, said at a
hospital news conference Monday also attended by three of his
children.
   ``Buck is a strong-willed man. For him to survive this long he
has proved it,'' she said, adding later, ``He's always been there
when I needed him, and this is when he needs us.''
   A wave of joy spread through the hospital at news of Helm's
condition, Huen said.
   ``When he was asked about whether he was hurting anywhere, he
shook his head and everbody was incredulous,'' Huen said.
   Helm's condition was upgraded Monday from critical to very
serious and may improve again to serious, Huen said, adding that
Helm was likely to spend two or three more days on a respirator.
   Helm, 57, had been trapped in his silver Chevrolet Sprint under
tons of steel and concrete since the earthquake Tuesday toppled a
double-decker section of Interstate 880 in Oakland.
   A ship's clerk at the Port of Oakland's Charles P. Hamilton
Terminal at the foot of Market Street, Helm was headed up the
freeway to Emeryville to a legal poker parlor when the quake hit,
dockworkers said.
   And in the freeway rubble is where he remained, slumped on his
right side along the front seat, until rescue workers freed him
Saturday.
   Helm's kidneys, which doctors had feared were so severley
damaged by dehydration that he might need dialysis the rest of his
life, appeared to be resuming normal function, Huen said.
   When a person is severely dehydrated, the kidneys shut down to
preserve the fluids in the body, Huen said. However, doctors had
feared that byproducts of muscle damage could have poisoned the
kidneys.
   ``In his case, he has responded so quickly we feel it was just
severe dehydration,'' Huen said.
   Doctors felt Helm's recovery was coming along so well that they
began feeding him through a tube inserted in his stomach and gave
him a pencil and a tablet of paper to communicate.
   Helm, 5-foot-11 and 230 pounds, can't talk because a respirator
tube has been run down his throat.
   However, the broken ribs and chest wall separation appear to be
mending and doctors have been lowering the amount of oxygen
delivered through the respirator, Huen said.
   Mrs. Helm said she has read newspaper accounts of the earthquake
to him, and he understands although he drifts in and out of
consciousness. He communicates by nodding, blinking, squeezing her
hand, she said.
   The night before the earthquake, Helm apparently slept, as he
usually did, in his rusty yellow Chevrolet panel truck parked at
the docks.
   On the left side of the truck, Helm had painted in orange the
words ``Weaverville Flash,'' referring to the little logging town
250 miles away in the Trinity Mountains of Northern California
where he drove every weekend to be with his children.
   On the right side, he painted a cartoon rabbit and ``Desirees's
Delight,'' after his 12-year-old daughter.
   ``He always calls me his rabbit,'' Desiree said at the news
conference. ``I love him.''
   Inside the van, Helm had a mattress, a Snoopy sleeping bag, two
alarm clocks, some clothes, and a panel of photographs of his
children, including one of a small child in a huge pair of football
shoulderpads.
   Before work, Helm usually drove to a YMCA to wash up, then
arrived at his job a little before 8 a.m., said Ralph Bucher, chief
clerk at the terminal.
   ``He was a Weaverville local,'' said Bucher. ``He has tried
living down in this area. He had several business enterprises
around Alameda. I believe he had a sandwich shop and a rent-a-wreck
type auto rental which kind of went sour.''
   Helm worked out of a small cubicle paneled in tan T-111 siding,
where he checked through the big trucks hauling shipping containers
bound for overseas.
   Inside the cubicle, there is nothing to identify Helm. Just a
computer terminal, a digital read-out for the truck scale outside,
and a printer for papers directing truckdrivers with their loads.
   During his coffee break, Helm routinely joined the other ship's
clerks at a round table in the back of a mobile office to play
tonk, the card game of the docks, at a quarter a hand.
   At lunchtime, none of the other clerks knew where Helm went, but
he might have taken a walk, because he was trying to lose weight,
said clerk Joe Marotto.
   Some of the ship's clerks took off early to watch the World
Series, but Helm said he was going to Emeryville to the Oaks Club
to play poker, ship's clerk Roger Phelps said.
   Maybe he felt lucky, because that day he'd been a winner at
tonk, ship's clerk Enrique Roman said.
   Bucher said Helm's car had more than 200,000 miles logged from
the commute to and from Weaverville. ``You look at it and think
that any collision would kill the occupant.''
</TEXT>
