<FIRST>r i AM-Belgium-Abortion     10-23 0366</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Belgium-Abortion,0380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Abortion Issue Reaches Belgian Parliament After 16-Year Battle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHILIPPE NEURAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate opens debate Tuesday on a
bill to legalize abortion in a showdown that has been put off for
16 years by legislative maneuvers in this predominantly Roman
Catholic country.
   The issue has divided the center-left government of Prime
Minister Wilfried Martens.
   It the Senate approves the bill, and a vote could be held by
Friday, the measure then goes to the more powerful Chamber of
Deputies.
   The measure would allow abortions during the first 12 weeks of
pregnancy for ``women in distress.''
   Abortions have been illegal in Belgium for more than 100 years
but in 1973 pro-abortion lawmakers sought to introduce legislation
changing the law. Catholic legislators successfully blocked all
efforts to bring the issue before Parliament until this year.
   The Senate's justice and public health committees voted to
change the law that bans abortions and provides for a penalty of up
to five years jail for women who have an abortion and those who
perform it.
   In the committees the Socialists voted for legalizing abortion
while Christian Democrats voted against.
   The dispute has divided Martens' five-party coalition of
Socialists and Christian Democrats, each split into Dutch and
French-speaking factions, and the Flemish People's Union.
   The greatest opposition comes from Martens' Dutch-speaking
Christian Democrats, Belgium's largest single political force.
   Many political observers believe the Christian Democrats are
willing to risk the fate of Martens' government on the outcome.
   Opinion polls have shown a majaority of Belgians favor
legalizing abortions.
   Although the procedure is banned, enforcement of the law has
been spotty and the courts have been lenient to those convicted of
violating the measure.
   It is estimated that 16,000 women have abortions in Belgium each
year and many more go to neighboring Holland, where abortions are
legal.
   On the eve of the parliamentary debate, there were indications
some Christian Democrat legislators would approve a change that
would approve abortions if granted by a special panel that would
hold hearings with the women seeking abortions.
   Pro-abortion forces reject such a compromise, saying the
decision must be made only by the woman and her doctor.
</TEXT>
