<FILEID>AP-NR-10-23-89 1854EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-US-Panama     10-23 0495</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Panama,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Seeks to Calm the Waters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush, seeking to smooth relations
with Congress, said Monday he has ``no differences at all'' with
the chairman of the Senate Intelligence Committee on the ground
rules for covert actions overseas.
   Bush grew testy when questioned by reporters about the issue at
the end of a 3{-hour golf outing at Andrews Air Force Base in
suburban Maryland.
   Bush complained to Senate Republican leaders in private last
week about congressional restrictions on actions by U.S. agents
overseas.
   The president reportedly griped that the restrictions, if
narrowly interpreted, could have required American officials to
warn Panamanian Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega in advance of any
impending coup that could endanger his life.
   Sen. David L. Boren, D-Okla., the chairman of the intelligence
panel, responded angrily Sunday night, saying ``the American people
are being deliberately misled'' by selective leaks of ``highly
classified correspondence.''
   But Bush told reporters, ``I have no differences at all with Mr.
Boren on all of this, and he knows it, and we know it, and that's a
good thing for the whole situation.''
   Asked specifically about Boren's complaint about leaks, Bush
replied: ``He's in good shape. He and I are thinking together on
these things.''
   Bush brushed aside another question about rewriting the
intelligence guidelines.
   ``Let me tell you something,'' said the president, who was once
director of the Central Intelligence Agency. ``I don't discuss
intelligence matters. It's just not intelligence if you do that.
That's not the way you treat it.''
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said earlier that Bush
and Boren had ``discussed the whole question of micromanagement and
of intelligence activities in these areas. The president feels that
any differences they may have had have been ironed out.''
   Fitzwater said Bush was working with Boren and the committee on
possible changes, but added, ``There will be no change in the ban
on assassinations _ bar none.''
   A policy imposed by then-President Gerald Ford in 1976 bars
American agents from taking part in any effort to assassinate
foreign leaders.
   Defense Secretary Dick Cheney has complained that Intelligence
Committee guidelines inhibited the administration's flexibility in
responding to events in Panama leading up to the failed attempt
Oct. 3 to oust Noriega, who is under federal indictment in Florida
on charges of drug trafficking.
   Boren said the report of Bush's complaints about the policy was
a ``selective leak'' that distorted the situation at the time of
his panel's October 1988 letter to then-President Ronald Reagan.
   While not acknowledging details of the policy, Boren said his
letter merely restated the committee's understanding of CIA
guidelines to carry out a 14-year-old ban on U.S. involvement in
assassinations of foreign leaders.
   ``Our letter stated their policy as it had been told to us,''
said a committee source.
   Boren, in a statement, said, ``The plain truth is, there are
ambiguities in the record'' on both the congressional and executive
side.
</TEXT>
