<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Libel     10-23 0262</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Libel,0272</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lord Slightly Injured in Courtroom Stumble</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lord Toby Aldington required hospital treatment
Monday after he stumbled in a courtroom during a High Court libel
trial over allegations that he is a war criminal.
   The 75-year-old peer fell as he stepped down from a bench beside
his lawyer's desk and suffered a graze on the head and a bloody
nose.
   Aldington, the former deputy chairman of the Conservative Party,
is claiming libel damages over allegations in a pamphlet published
by historian Count Nikolai Tolstoy and Nigel Watts, a property
developer.
   The pamphlet claimed Aldington, an army chief of staff at the
end of World War II, arranged the repatriation in 1945 of 70,000
Cossacks and Yugoslavs to the Communists knowing they would be
massacred on their return.
   Many of the 70,000 had fought on the German side during the war.
They had fallen into Allied hands on the collapse of Germany at the
end of the war.
   Their return was demanded by the late Soviet leader Joseph
Stalin.
   Historians say many people repatriated after the war were shot
by the Communists.
   Aldington, the ex-chairman of the Sun Alliance Insurance Group,
has said he is the victim of harassment by Watts. He claims Watts
was angered by the company's failure to provide payments after the
death of his brother-in-law.
   Aldington needed no stitches after he was taken to the hospital
Monday, and X-rays showed no damage, Judge Michael Davies said. He
said Aldington was expected to be back in court Tuesday.
   The trial was in its third week.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891023-0163 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-23-89 2058EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-UN-Nicaragua     10-23 0548</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-Nicaragua,0564</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Claims Sandinistas Rigging Elections</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Nicaragua</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Ambassador Thomas R. Pickering
suggested Monday that Nicaragua's ruling Sandinistas are rigging
the campaign for the Feb. 25 general elections.
   During debate in the General Assembly, Pickering said the
Sandinista government views democratic reform as ``little more than
another obstacle to be overcome in continuing to violate
international, hemispheric and regional commitments.''
   His allegations disputed a report by U.N. election monitors sent
to Nicaragua.
   The report, released last week, said the monitors found
Nicaragua's Supreme Election Council gave ``no undue benefits'' to
the Sandinistas and ``there is appreciable concern on the part of
the members of the council to ensure the broadest possible
participation by political groups and citizens.'' The U.N.
monitoring mission is led by former U.S. Attorney General Elliott
Richardson.
   Pickering told the assembly, ``We remain concerned over actions
by the Nicaraguan government to limit the access by the Nicaraguan
opposition parties to the media and to limit the opposition's
ability to campaign to a broad public.''
   He said Washington also is ``concerned by the reported presence
of armed soldiers at Nicaraguan voter registration centers.''
   The U.N. report noted opposition parties receive free time on
Nicaragua's channel 2, which reaches only the Pacific coast and
interior, while the Sandinistas have sole use of the more powerful
channel 6. But the report added ``the use of radio and television
for political propaganda began too recently for any in-depth
discussion of the question to be possible at this stage.'' The
report covered the period from July 5 to Sept. 30.
   Voter registration for the Feb. 25 elections was held on the
first four Sundays in October. The Supreme Electoral Council said
that on the first three Sundays 1,336,342 citizens had registered
out of an estimated 1,970,486 eligible voters.
   The General Assembly adopted by consensus a resolution praising
progress toward peaceful resolutions of the conflicts in Central
America following agreements by five Central American presidents at
a conference in August.
   Pickering, however, accused Cuba and Nicaragua of undermining
the peace process by shipping weapons to the leftist rebels
fighting the U.S.-backed government in El Salvador.
   ``There is no doubt that Cuba and Nicaragua regularly,
systematically and continually aid, arm and train'' the Salvadoran
guerrillas, he said.
   In another development, Nicaraguan Ambassador Alejandro Serrano
Caldera said his government might bar Nicaraguan rebels, known as
Contras, from returning to the country after a Dec. 5 deadline.
   The August agreement, known as the Tela Accord, involves among
other issues the disarming and disbanding of the Contras by Dec. 5.
Many of the Contras are in bases across the border in Honduras.
   Serrano Caldera, speaking with reporters outside the General
Assembly, said, ``Non-compliance with the agreement would mean
Nicaragua could adopt the position that it is not bound by the
agreement to receive the Contras.''
   ``I would emphasize that the Tela Accord must be totally
complied with,'' he said.
   The United States has said the Tela Accord requires only the
voluntary disbanding of the estimated 11,000 Contras in Honduras
and many of the rebels do not want to return to their homeland
until democratic elections have been held.
   Free and democratic elections in Nicarauga are a provision of
the Tela Accord.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891023-0164 </DOCNO>
