<FIRST>r i AM-Grunwald 1stLd-Writethru a0726 10-23 0216</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Grunwald, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0726,0221</SECOND>
<HEAD>PRECEDE WASHINGTON</HEAD>
<HEAD>U.S. Ambassador to Austria Resigns</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS thruout to ADD background, details. No pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Ambassador Henry A. Grunwald, who
oversaw U.S. relations with Austria during a period of unease over
President Kurt Waldheim's role in World War II, is resigning for
personal reasons, U.S. officials said Monday.
   Grunwald, 67, has been ambassador since January 1988. His
resignation will be effective Jan. 1, a U.S. Embassy representative
said without elaborating on the reasons.
   Grunwald replaced Ronald Lauder, the cosmetics company heir who
was defeated in a New York City mayoral Republican primary in
September.
   During Grunwald's tenure, U.S.-Austrian relations reached a low
point over reports that accused Waldheim of complicity in Nazi war
crimes. In April 1987, the U.S. Justice Department placed Waldheim
on a list of undesirable aliens.
   Born in Vienna, Grunwald, a Jew, was forced to flee Austria as a
child after Adolf Hitler took over the country and merged it with
Germany in 1938. Most Jews who remained were sent to death camps.
   In New York, Grunwald worked his way from copy boy at Time
magazine to foreign editor and then editor-in-chief. He retired
from that post in 1987.
   He was expected to hold a press conference on Tuesday in Vienna.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
