<FIRST>u a AM-BoxOffice     10-23 0582</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Box Office,0604</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Look Who's Talking' Still Making Box Office Noise; `Fat Man' Bombs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Look Who's Talking'' claimed the No. 1 box
office spot for the second weekend in a row, proving John
Travolta's comeback was not short-lived, according to figures
released Monday.
   Grossing $14.1 million, the comedy starring Travolta, Kirstie
Alley and Bruce Willis as the voice of a baby from conception to
infancy finished almost $10 million ahead of second-place ``Next of
Kin.''
   ``Next of Kin,'' featuring Patrick Swayze and Liam Neeson
pursuing their brother's killer, collected $4.8 million in ticket
sales, according to Exhibitor Relations Co.
   Overall weekend business for the Top 10 was $38.5 million, up
63.5 percent from a year ago, said Entertainment Data Inc., which
also tracks box-office business.
   ``Look Who's Talking,'' playing on 339 more screens than a week
ago, was up 17 percent from its debut weekend, Entertainment Data
reported.
   In third place with $3 million was ``Sea of Love,'' the romantic
thriller starring Al Pacino as a policeman whose murder suspect,
played by Ellen Barkin, is also his lover.
   ``Black Rain,'' the international adventure movie starring
Michael Douglas, finished fourth with $2.84 million. In fifth place
with receipts of $2.83 million was ``Gross Anatomy,'' a new
medical-school comedy featuring Matthew Modine and Daphne Zuniga.
   The dead-teenager sequel ``Halloween V: The Revenge of Michael
Myers'' landed in sixth with a gate of $2.79 million, down a sharp
45 percent from its opening weekend. In seventh was ``The Fabulous
Baker Boys,'' with Jeff Bridges and Michelle Pfeiffer, which took
$2.78 million.
   Falling four notches to eighth was Tom Selleck's prison movie,
``An Innocent Man,'' grossing $2.3 million. In ninth was the
bittersweet family comedy ``Parenthood,'' with $1.51 million.
   In last place among the Top 10 was the new ``Fat Man and Little
Boy,'' starring Paul Newman in the story of the creation of the
atomic bomb. The movie failed to explode, collecting only $1.48
million for a terrible opening per-screen average of $1,752.
   Although Woody Allen's ``Crimes and Misdemeanors'' didn't make
the leader board, it was up 1.5 percent from its opening weekend on
positive word of mouth.
   Here are the top movies for the weekend as tallied by Exhibitor
Relations, with distributor, weekend gross, number of theater
screens, average per screen, total gross and number of weeks in
release.
   Figures are based on a combination of actual box-office receipts
and studio projections where actual figures are not immediately
available.
   1. ``Look Who's Talking,'' Tri-Star, $14.1 million, 1,547
screens, $9,145 per screen, $30.1 million, two weeks.
   2. ``Next of Kin,'' Warner Bros., $4.8 million, 1,358 screens,
$3,539 per screen, $4.8 million, one week.
   3. ``Sea of Love,'' Universal, $3 million, 1,419 screens, $2,080
per screen, $46.4 million, six weeks.
   4. ``Black Rain,'' Paramount, $2.84 million, 1,615 screens,
$1,761 per screen, $36.4 million, five weeks.
   5. ``Gross Anatomy,'' Disney, $2.83 million, 853 screens, $3,318
per screen, $2.83 million, one week.
   6. ``Halloween V: The Revenge of Michael Myers,'' Galaxy, $2.79
million, 1,495 screens, $1,868 per screen, $9.1 million, two weeks.
   7. ``The Fabulous Baker Boys,'' 20th Century Fox, $2.78 million,
860 screens, $3,231 per screen, $7.3 million, two weeks.
   8. ``An Innocent Man,'' Disney, $2.3 million, 1,520 screens,
$1,544 per screen, $15 million, three weeks.
   9. ``Parenthood,'' Universal, $1.51 million, 1,183 screens,
$1,275 per screen, $89.4 million, 12 weeks.
   10. ``Fatman and Little Boy,'' Paramount, $1.48 million, 843
screens, $1,752 per screen, $1.48 million, one week.
</TEXT>
