<FIRST>u a AM-DrunkenDriving     10-23 0452</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drunken Driving,0465</SECOND>
<HEAD>N.J. Supreme Court Justice Pleads Guilty to Drunken Driving</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM KRATTENMAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TRENTON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New Jersey's most senior supreme court
justice pleaded guilty to drunken driving charges Monday, and
promised not to participate in any drunken driving decisions for at
least a year.
   ``My shame and embarassment are beyond my ability to express,''
Supreme Court Justice Robert Clifford, 64, of Chester said in a
statement following his plea and sentencing in a courtroom a block
from his own chambers.
   Superior Court Judge Samuel Lenox suspended Clifford's license
for a year after the justice pleaded guilty to driving while
intoxicated and refusing to submit to a Breathalyzer test.
   Earlier Monday, Clifford followed court custom and excused
himself from oral arguments in a case questioning the legality of
the Breathalyzer test, which police use to determine the amount of
alcohol in the blood.
   Clifford, who has served on New Jersey's seven-member high court
longer than any other justice, was arrested in Princeton early Oct.
12 after an officer saw him crossing the highway center line and
driving 46 mph in a 35-mph zone. Clifford, who was returning from a
dinner, refused to take the test.
   Lenox also fined Clifford $500 plus court costs, and ordered him
to pay a $100 surcharge to a rehabilitation fund for alcoholics.
Clifford will also have to pay a $3,000 auto insurance surcharge
over the next three years.
   Clifford, who is known for his wit and penetrating questions
during oral arguments before the high court, displayed little
emotion at his own hearing.
   Asked by Lenox whether he had driven under the influence and
refused to take the Breathalyzer test, Clifford replied, ``Yes,
sir.''
   In his statement, the justice said he would not participate in
any drunken driving case for at least the year of his license
suspension.
   ``I have concluded that the best way to prevent any repetition
of drinking and driving is to avoid drinking,'' Clifford said.
``That is my intention, and I will not hesitate to draw on whatever
support is necessary to help me fulfill it.''
   Clifford and his attorney, Bernard Conway, refused to make any
further comments.
   The office later issued a statement saying Clifford's case would
be referred to the court's Advisory Committee on Judicial Conduct,
which could recommend disciplinary measures.
   Clifford said his conduct let down former Govs. William Cahill,
who appointed him to the high court in 1973, and Brendan Byrne, who
reappointed him in 1980.
   ``Most importantly, I did not fulfill the legitimate
expectations of the people of New Jersey, who are entitled to
nothing short of irreproachable conduct from members of the
judiciary,'' he said. ``To all of them I apologize.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
