<FILEID>AP-NR-10-23-89 2018EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-SFQuake-Evacuation     10-23 0380</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SF Quake-Evacuation,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quake's Newest Homeless Displaced by Damaged Freeway</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-SF Quake, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDY LIPPMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Charles Burns had just moved into an
apartment Friday near the site of the Cypress offramp of the Nimitz
Freeway, which had collapsed only days earlier in a massive
earthquake.
   On Monday, Burns was temporarily homeless because of a decision
to remove a portion of unstable freeway near his apartment.
   Burns and more than 100 residents of a West Oakland public
housing project were told to leave their homes Sunday afternoon
after engineers concluded the freeway section near four of the
project's buildings might collapse.
   Residents were told to leave their homes immediately _ and leave
most belongings behind.
   ``We were all scared,'' Burns said. ``We were all wondering,
`What's going on now?' I thought there'd been another earthquake.''
   While some residents were able to find their own temporary
shelter, Burns took his Bible and some other books to the Lowell
Middle School, where he joined about 160 other people, some of whom
had been there since last week.
   They sat on cots in the school gymnasium, eating food provided
by local agencies and trying to figure out relief forms.
   ``I'll be glad when it's all straightened out,'' Burns said.
``One minute you're home and the next minute you're out and you
don't know why. There's confusion and chaos here.''
   Engineers estimate it may take 48 hours to take down the section
of freeway which imperiled the neighborhood, and it may be 24 hours
more before the residents can return.
   ``We are very aware of the problems people are going through,''
said Oakland police Lt. Kris Wraa. ``But the safety of the citizens
overpowered the need to let them get their belongings.''
   The west end of the housing project is within 20 feet of the
endangered freeway and if it had fallen on its own, ``a tremendous
amount of damage could be done and people could be hurt,'' said
CalTrans representative Kyle Nelson.
   What caused the most confusion was the short notice given, with
residents first being told they had to begin leaving immediately at
3:30 p.m. Sunday. Rumors bounced from house to house, ranging from
another earthquake to the possibility of a gas leak.
</TEXT>
