<DOCNO> AP891023-0180 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-23-89 2126EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-SpaceShuttle 3rdLd-Writethru a0746 10-23 1022</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Space Shuttle, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0746,1048</SECOND>
<HEAD>Atlantis Returns to Earth as Galileo Speeds on to Jupiter ^Eds: INSERTS
4 grafs after 9th graf, `The Galileo...', with astronauts returning to
Houston. Picks up 10th graf pvs, `The successful ...</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto EAB2, HT1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EDWARDS AIR FORCE BASE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Space shuttle Atlantis
streaked down through the atmosphere and glided safely home Monday
after a five-day mission that sent the long-delayed Galileo
spacecraft on a 2.4-billion-mile journey to Jupiter.
   Atlantis touched down at 9:32 a.m. in a light breeze, cutting
short its mission by two 90-minute orbits to get down before
predicted high winds came up on Rogers Dry Lake. Before the
landing, dense fog had shrouded the base.
   ``Atlantis, congratulations on an outstanding mission,'' said
capsule communicator Ken Cameron in Houston. ``You've extended the
shuttle's reach to the outer planets.''
   ``It's nice to be home,'' shuttle commander Donald E. Williams
replied.
   A relatively modest crowd estimated at about 20,000 was on hand
to watch Williams, pilot Michael J. McCulley and mission
specialists Shannon W. Lucid, Ellen S. Baker and Franklin R.
Chang-Diaz come home.
   ``The vehicle looks amazingly clean. We did not see, with a
quick inspection, any significant tile damage _ a little nick here
and a nick there,'' William Lenoir, an acting associate
administrator of NASA, said at a post-landing news conference.
   After thanking a crowd of several hundred cheering NASA workers,
the astronauts left Edwards shortly before 2 p.m. aboard two
Gulfstream jets bound for their home base in Houston.
   ``This is a great beginning for the study of Jupiter,''
Chang-Diaz said after Galileo project manager Richard Spehalski
teased the astronauts for nicknaming ``our lovely spacecraft `the
Critter.'''
   ``The Galileo critter is on its way and doing very well,''
Spehalski said.
   The crew and their spouses returned to Houston at about 6:30
p.m. CDT, and they were greeted by their children and nearly 300
friends and co-workers.
   ``Atlantis was a magnificent ship,'' Williams said. The
commander also thanked the workers at Mission Control who helped
the crew during their flight.
   ``We had a great time,'' said Mrs. Baker, a mission specialist
who made her first trip into space aboard Atlantis. ``I'm really
proud to be part of the Galileo mission.''
   After having most of the day off Tuesday, the astronauts will
return to the Johnson Space Center on Wednesday to begin a series
of briefings about their flight, officials said.
   The successful deployment of the nuclear-powered Galileo
accomplished the mission's main goal about 6{ hours after blastoff
Wednesday from Cape Canaveral, Fla.
   The $1.5 billion spacecraft was said to be operating
flawlessley, passing the million-mile mark at a speed of nearly
9,000 mph, relative to Earth, on a looping, 6-year trip to explore
Jupiter.
   Problems in the shuttle program, including the 1986 Challenger
explosion, helped delay the start of Galileo's trip by seven years.
While a shuttle sent the Magellan orbiter toward Venus in May and
will deploy the Ulysses spacecraft to orbit the sun's poles next
October, scientists plan to use unmanned rockets to launch
subsequent planetary spacecraft.
   ``We're obviously relieved the shuttle gave us a magnificent
ride,'' said Neal Ausman, Galileo mission director for NASA's Jet
Propulsion Laboratory. ``But we're also pleased we're not going to
be depending on the space shuttle as the only way into space.''
   Several groups unsuccessfully sought to prevent the shuttle
launch for fear that an accident could release radioactive fuel
into the atmosphere over Florida. A federal judge refused to halt
the flight.
   The crew fired Atlantis' big braking rockets to drop out of
orbit, and the 97-ton winged spaceship made a fiery descent toward
California, crossing the coast at four times the speed of sound,
105,000 feet over Malibu.
   Automatic control systems put the hurtling orbiter through
speed-shedding maneuvers, rocking the Los Angeles area with the
shuttle's signature twin sonic booms. Then Williams lightly set
Atlantis on the clay runway where it rolled to a stop on the
black-dotted centerline.
   Reflecting jitters from last week's Bay Quake, the Santa Monica
Police Department got about a dozen calls around 9:30 a.m., said
Officer Kim Neal. Nervous callers thought the resonating boom as
Atlantis descended was an earthquake or gunshots.
   The shuttle passed through high winds aloft but surface winds
were reported at only about 4{ mph, with gusts at just under 6 mph
moments before touchdown.
   Fourteen minutes later, controllers told the crew they could
remove their bulky flight suits. An astronaut called back, ``Just
out of curiosity, Houston, what's the temperature outside?''
   At around 60 degrees, the astronauts were comfortable, exiting
the orbiter in their orange flight suits. They inspected the belly
of the shuttle, chatting, laughing and hugging each other before
leaving the dry lakebed for debriefing.
   Unofficial elapsed mission time was 4 days, 23 hours and 41
minutes.
   The astronauts had gone to bed early in anticipation of the
early landing and were awakened by a recording of Steve Miller's
``Fly Like an Eagle'' beamed up from Mission Control.
   ``Well I'm not sure we're flying like eagles, but it's been fun
so far,'' Williams remarked.
   If winds were too strong, the landing could have been postponed
until Tuesday or Wednesday, the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration said.
   The forecast predicted gusts up to 35 mph in the afternoon.
Safety rules forbid landings if headwinds reach 29 mph or
crosswinds reach 18 mph.
   The astronauts also conducted several scientific experiments,
including one that measured the Earth's protective ozone layer.
   Two other shuttle experiments involved processing materials and
growing corn plants. The astronauts also photographed lightning
systems for a weather project and grew ice crystals for a student
experiment.
   Time also was spent photographing various parts of the world
with the IMAX movie camera. The footage will be used for a
documentary film about Earth.
   Crowds numbering in the hundreds of thousands have sometimes
greeted shuttle returns. Officials attributed the small turnout to
the fact that it was a weekday landing.
   There also were rain showers in Los Angeles, 80 miles south of
Edwards, and dense early morning fog around the base.
</TEXT>
