<HEAD>Rescue Workers Recover Body from Beachfront Landslide</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to ADD `s' to middle name, Phillips, sted Phillip;
SUBS 3rd graf to recast, changing avalanched to tumbled; Pick up 4th graf
prvs: The National ...</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-SF Quake, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHARON COHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONNY DOON, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Slickered rescue crews, working in a
driving rain, on Monday recovered the body of a waiter who had been
buried in a beachfront landslide during last week's earthquake.
   The victim was identified by authorities as Gary Phillips West,
41, a San Francisco waiter from Napa. He had been missing since the
quake. His car was located in the Bonny Doon Beach parking lot
about 10 miles north of Santa Cruz, authorities said.
   West's body was found shortly before 2 p.m. Monday, the second
day of a search for him along the beach where a cliff gave way and
tumbled onto the sand.
   The National Guard, California Department of Forestry and Santa
Cruz paramedics helped in the search, using a front-end loader to
shovel and scoop dirt out of the 90-foot-high cliff. They were
assisted by a search dog amed Eros, said Capt. Mike Martin of the
California Department of Forestry.
   ``As they were trying to excavate the area, every time they
brought out a shovel full of dirt, more dirt was falling in,''
Martin said.
   The 30 to 40 rescue workers waded through muck and mud to search
the area, struggling to keep the front-end loader upright.
   The search had to be called off Sunday night at sunset because
of high tides and concern that more of the cliff would cave in,
Martin said.
   Martin said an autopsy would have to be performed before a cause
of death would be available.
   West, a waiter at the McArthur Park Restaurant in San Francisco,
was found wearing shorts and buried under 15 feet of rock and dirt,
Martin said.
   No air pockets were found that might have spared West's life,
said forest service Capt. Steve Delagadillo.
   Residents near the area noticed West's car and contacted
authorities. The victim's sister identified the car on Sunday and
the search was started.
</TEXT>
