<FIRST>r w AM-USAToday-DrugPoll     10-23 0237</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-USA Today-Drug Poll,210</SECOND>
<HEAD>One in Four Would Turn in Child</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Almost one in four American adults would turn
over to the police a child of theirs if they caught that child
selling cocaine, according to a poll to be published Tuesday.
   Nearly one in three would turn in their best friend, according
to the poll results appearing in Tuesday editions of USA Today.
   About seven out of eight would turn in a stranger, according to
results made available on Monday by the newspaper
   Here is how the 814 respondents broke down on turning in someone
found selling cocaine: own child, 24 percent; best friend, 32
percent; stranger, 86 percent.
   Only half the respondents said the war against drugs could be
won, while 41 percent said it could not. Eighty-eight percent said
the drug problem is worse than most people realize.
   Seventy-one percent said they were worried ``a great deal'' that
someone they care about could become a victim of drug-related
violence, 58 percent said they feared drug use would result in the
ultimate decline of the country and 62 percent said they would be
willing to pay higher taxes to fight drugs.
   On taxes, 53 percent said they would be willing to pay between
$100 and $500 more.
   The newspaper's announcement did not say how the poll was
conducted or when. The likely margin of error is 3.5 percentage
points either way.
</TEXT>
