<HEAD>Plane Hits Deer Strolling Across Runway</HEAD>
<DATELINE>REDMOND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A commuter airliner carrying 16 passengers
crashed during takeoff into a small group of deer walking single
file across the runway at Redmond Municipal Airport.
   No one aboard the 19-seat United Express airliner was injured in
Sunday's accident, but the plane suffered up to $50,000 in damage,
said Shelley Swanke, spokeswoman at the United Express office in
Pesco, Wash.
   The plane was accelerating down the runway but had not left the
ground.
   None of the six deer made any attempt to flee as the plane
approached. The pilot was so near that he could not avoid them, she
said.
   Redmond is about 40 miles east of the Three Sisters mountains in
Oregon's Cascade Range. The plane was bound for Portland
International Airport.
