<HEAD>Ousted Federal Judge Opens Campaign For Governor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENT KALLESTAD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former federal judge Alcee Hastings
officially entered the 1990 Florida governor's race Monday, just
three days after the U.S. Senate removed him from the bench.
   ``I understand people will have a negative perception, but it
will be dispelled,'' said Hastings, who will run as a Democrat.
   Hastings, who became Florida's first black U.S. District judge
10 years ago, was removed Friday when the Senate convicted him in
an impeachment trial of conspiring to take $150,000 to fix a case.
   ``I got fired by people who didn't read or understand the
dynamics of the evidence as it was presented,'' said Hastings, who
was acquitted in a criminal trial. ``I believe myself to be a man
of honor and integrity. I have not committed any crime at any
time.''
   Hastings, who was an unsuccessful candidate for the Senate in
1970 and the state Public Service Commission in 1974, filed the
necessary paperwork with the state Division of Elections.
   He predicted victory despite the noteriety of impeachment and a
lack of funds and campaign organization.
   Also vying for the Democratic nomination are U.S. Rep. Bill
Nelson and state Sen. George Stuart of Orlando. If no candidate
wins a majority in the primary, the top two vote-getters would
advance to a runoff.
   Gov. Bob Martinez, a Republican, is running for re-election. He
faces a challenge for the GOP nomination by state Sen. Marlene
Woodson-Howard of Bradenton.
