<HEAD>Parliamentarian Urges Poland Restore Its Pre-Communist Name</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS graf 2 pvs `Bender, a...' with one graf to RESTORE dropped
first name; pickup graf 3 `He outlined...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hungary, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former parliament member Monday urged
Solidarity deputies to follow Hungary's example and drop
``People's'' from Poland's official name, ``The Polish People's
Republic.''
   Ryszard Bender, a member of the previous parliament who lost his
race against Solidarity in June elections, had proposed in the last
parliamentary session that the country's name be changed and the
phrase inscribing the leading role of the party in the constitution
be eliminated.
   He outlined his latest proposal in a letter to the 160 members
of the Citizens Parliamentary Club _ the caucus of Solidarity
deputies in parliament. The official news agency PAP carried
excerpts of the letter.
   ``I appeal ... for the quickest possible legislative initiative
aimed at elimination of the name PPR (Polish People's Republic) and
restoration of the historic name of the Polish Republic,'' he wrote.
   The chairman of the Polish Historical Society made a similar
proposal earlier this month.
   Bender urged the Solidarity deputies not to fall behing Hungary,
which has restored its pre-communist name of the Republic of
Hungary.
   ``Last week, following a decision of the Hungary parliament, the
old name of the country was restored. The Stalinist People's
Republic of Hungary disappeared. And our country is still called
the Polish People's Republic,'' Bender said.
   ``Time is running out. Let's not remain far behind the
Hungarians,'' the letter said.
   Hungary and Poland are leading democratic reforms in the East
bloc, with Hungary firmly committed to free multiparty elections
and Poland having elected the first non-communist government in the
Warsaw Pact.
</TEXT>
