<SECOND>AM-Hazing Death,0213</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Expelled, Eight Suspended in Fatal Hazing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Morehouse College announced Monday that two
students have been expelled because of a fraternity hazing that led
to a potential member's death last week.
   Eight other students were suspended for one year.
   Although officials did not release names of the students
disciplined, the college said all were members of the Alpha Rho
chapter of Alpha Phi Alpha fraternity, the nation's oldest black
Greek-letter fraternity. The fraternity had been suspended by the
college earlier.
   Joel Allen Harris, 18, of New York City, died Wednesday after
students interested in pledging the fraternity were allegedly
shoved when they did not answer questions correctly. Officials said
Harris had an enlarged heart, which contributed to his death.
   Cobb County police also are investigating.
   ``Clearly we want to send a message to fraternities that hazing
of any kind is not tolerated and will not be tolerated,'' Morehouse
spokesman Robert Bolton said Monday. ``From our standpoint, the
college defines hazing as harassment, mental and-or physical.''
   The penalties were decided by a Morehouse College judiciary
court, which included administrators and faculty members. Bolton
said at least two rules were broken: the pledging process began
before the sanctioned Oct. 19 date and hazing occurred.
