<FIRST>s i BC-Kurds-Turkey Adv29   10-23 0548</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Kurds-Turkey, Adv 29,0567</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv29</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Oct. 29, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Kurdish Civilians in Turkey Caught in Guerrilla War</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Kurds-Iran, b0537</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EMEL ANIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANKARA, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 5-year-old war between Marxist Kurdish
guerrillas and security forces is driving thousands of Kurdish
civilians from their villages in southeastern Turkey to safer areas.
   Of 2,000 people killed so far in the conflict, at least 700 have
been listed as Kurdish farmers.
   Guerrillas of the outlawed Kurdish Labor Party are fighting to
establish an independent Marxist state in the Kurdish areas in
eastern and southeastern Turkey.
   The scope of the support they have from Kurdish civilians could
not be independently determined but Kurdish resentment toward
Turkish security forces has been building. It reached a high poiint
in mid-September when a crowd clashed with police in the township
of Silopi while protesting the killing of six Kurds a few days
earlier.
   The security forces maintained the victims were guerrillas, but
local residents claimed they were farmers taking fruit to the town
market. The locals charged the victims were shot as suspected
rebels.
   An investigating group from Turkey's Parliament bore them out.
   ``It is very sad but the people are right,'' said Nurettin
Yilmaz, a member of Parliament from Premier Turgut Ozal's
Motherland Party. ``Our investigation in the town and taped
testimony of many witnesses support their claim.''
   Yilmaz and two other Parliament members have urged the
prosecution of those responsible.
   For years, the local Kurds have complained that if they don't
help the guerrillas, they risk being killed by them. If they do
help them, they face imprisonment by the security forces and
sometimes torture.
   Security officials contend it is difficult to distinguish the
guerrillas from the farmers and herdsmen of the 300 small hamlets
in the region.
   Some officials acknowledge that local support for the guerrillas
is increasing, mainly out of fear and in some cases because of
mistreatment by government forces.
   Residents complain most about the special anti-terrorist police
in the southeastern area, the Parliament group said.
   ``Maybe it is because of their commando training but they are
very harsh with the local people,'' Yilmaz said.
   ``The people are increasingly becoming alienated from the state.
There is cause for anxiety,'' said Fuat Atalay, a Social Democrat
from Diyarbakir, the largest province in the area.
   During a recent parliamentary debate, Interior Minister
Abdulkadir Aksu said that only those suspected of aiding and
harboring guerrillas were detained.
   He contended that police and soldiers were trying to save lives
in an area where he said the guerrillas had killed 618 civilians
and 336 security personnel in the past two years.
   However, the aspirations and grievances of the Kurdish minority,
a taboo subject in Turkey until recent years, now find expression
even in parliamentary debates in Ankara.
   Members from the Kurdish areas are demanding increased
government investment in the Kurdish provinces, where the jobless
rate of 35 percent is double the national average.
   The Kurds also are demanding that the education, publications
and broadcasts in the Kurdish language _ now forbidden _ be allowed.
   ``Like ostrichs burying their heads in the sand, we are still
debating, in this day and age, whether there are Kurds in Turkey,''
said Yilmaz.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Friday PMs, Oct. 27</NOTE>
