<FIRST>s i BC-Luxembourg-1992 Adv29-1stadd   10-23 0541</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Luxembourg-1992, Adv 29-1st add,0562</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv29</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Oct. 29, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>LUXEMBOURG: 10 percent.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The proposal, requiring unanimous approval, was fought by
Luxembourg and other countries.
   ``I think at this point it is a dead issue,'' said Prime
Minister Santer.
   In pushing the measure, the commission argued it was needed to
halt tax evasion once capital controls were lifted.
   ``There is thus a risk that, once investors are free to open
bank accounts in other member states, they will not declare their
interest income to their national tax authorities and will thus
illegally evade payment of tax,'' it said.
   That might lead, it added, to a substantial loss of revenue in
many countries.
   West German authorities introduced a 10 percent withholding tax
at the start of the year, only to repeal it in the summer. Analysts
believe a substantial amount of money flowed out of the country,
some into Luxembourg.
   Most analysts do not expect much to happen on July 1 since many
capital controls already have been lifted.
   James Cornish, European markets strategist at County NatWest in
London, noted, however, ``In principle, if there's a lot of money
pent up in Italy by the restrictions, the money could flow out.''
   Fresh from apparent victory on the withholding front,
Luxembourgers shrug off suggestions they might be hurt by greater
competition from other money centers.
   ``We've always had open frontiers,'' said Fernand Rau, managing
director of Credit European, a subsidiary of a Belgian bank, and
head of the national legislature's finance committee.
   ``We are probably the country least concerned among all the 12
with the lifting of (capital) controls in 1990,'' he said.
   Jean Krier, senior executive vice president of the Banque
International of Luxembourg and president of the Luxembourg
Association of Banks and Bankers, agreed: ``Luxembourg has certain
advantages which cannot disappear.''
   The nation's bankers must be innovative to keep pace, Santer
said.
   ``The bigger the capital markets where a banking center can
operate, (the) more opportunities there are _ of course, the more
competition there is,'' said Pierre Jaans, general director of the
Luxembourg Monetary Institute.
   Officials believe some banks want to move to Luxembourg before
the 1992 deadline for the European-wide market.
   The number of banks has grown from 112 in June 1984 to 156 now.
Officials expect it to reach 160 by year's end.
   The majority of the banks have European parents, with West
Germans topping the list at 37 banks as of June.
   Banks with Luxembourg or Belgian roots reached 19, and 13 were
counted as Swiss. Only nine were American, the same as Japanese.
   Luxembourgers bridle at questions about dirty money operations,
often attracted to banking centers steeped in secrecy.
   The legislature recently enacted a measure setting tough
penalties for the laundering of drug money.
   ``We have no interest ... to have this reputation, and therefore
we are very strongly against this situation,'' Santer said.
   Agreed Jaans, ``Since we are so small ... we have to be
particularly cautious.''
   The United States last year accused a bank owned by a Luxembourg
holding company of taking part in an international ring that
laundered millions of dollars in profits for the Colombian cocaine
trade. The bank denied the charges.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Oct. 29</NOTE>
