<FIRST>s i BC-IrelandToday Adv29   10-23 1002</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Ireland Today, Adv 29,1028</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv29</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Oct. 29, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Ireland's Economy Surges But Country Still Has Long Way To Go</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: an accompanying story is BC-Ireland-Youth, b0544.</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto, LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BARR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DUBLIN, Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ireland's economy is surging ahead, but
it's a long, long way to full employment.
   Inflation is down to a modest 4 percent and economic growth is
expected to surpass 5 percent next year. Exports are projected to
reach an all-time high of $19.3 billion this year with a trade
surplus of nearly $700 million.
   Unemployment has decreased from 19.7 percent in January 1987,
but only to 17.3 percent, and the rate of emigration has climbed.
   Ireland is enjoying ``a very strong recovery from a fairly
dismal period of no growth,'' says John Fitz Gerald, a senior
researcher at the Economic and Social Research Institute in Dublin.
   The indicators have improved just since summer, Fitz Gerald
said, and the institute has revised its economic growth forecast
for this year upward by a full percentage point.
   The institute forecasts that growth will stay above 4 percent a
year through 1993, inflation will remain low and the government can
expect budget surpluses by 1992.
   ``There are few economies in the industrialized world now in a
position to make the kind of optimistic projections we can, or to
point to such an improvement in such a short space of time,'' Prime
Minister Charles Haughey said recently.
   ``The emphasis now must be on translating rising economic growth
into more jobs,'' he added.
   While the unemployment rate has declined in the past two years,
it still is nearly double the average of 9.3 percent in the
12-nation European Economic Community, of which Ireland is a
member. Only Spain, at 17.4 percent, reported worse.
   ``There are fewer people with jobs in Ireland than there were in
1950,'' says the Rev. Sean Healy of the Justice Office of the Roman
Catholic Conference of Major Religious Superiors.
   As the number of jobless more than doubled in the 1980s, the
economic institute reported, the standard of living for the
unemployed declined. That decline, it added, may continue despite
the upward trend of the economic indicators.
   Emigration, a signal of Irish distress since the famine days of
the 19th century, is on the rise again. The government's Central
Statistics Office reported that 46,000 people left in the 12 months
through last April, up from 32,000 the year before.
   A recent report based on the 1986 census found that net
migration from Ireland between 1981 and 1986 totaled 72,000 _
two-thirds of them 15 to 24 years old.
   The economic institute's survey predicted that Ireland will add
82,000 jobs and cut emigration to 11,000 by 1994. Unemployment is
projected to drop to 12.7 percent.
   Ireland bailed itself out of deep deficits by slashing public
spending, supported by a broad, informal coalition of the
politically dominant parties of the right.
   When Haughey called an election this past summer, however, his
Fianna Fail party found the voters unhappy about austerity,
especially cuts in the health service. Fianna Fail lost seats and
Haughey clung to power by forming a coalition, a deeply unpopular
move within his own ranks, with a splinter party.
   Fianna Fail, Ireland's dominant party since the 1930s, no longer
pursues the dream of a Gaelic-speaking, mostly rural and united
island espoused by Eamon de Valera, the party founder and former
prime minister and president.
   Like other mainstream parties, it aspires to a united Ireland.
Indeed, that goal still features prominently in the constitution
drawn up by de Valera. But under the 1985 Anglo-Irish Agreement,
Ireland has accepted that Northern Ireland can only become part of
Ireland when a majority of the British province's people want to.
   In its seventh decade of independence from Britain, this nation
of 3.6 million people is still remarkably dependent on the British
economy, which absorbs 30 percent of Ireland's exports and the
largest portion of Irish emigres.
   In economic terms, the people of the Republic of Ireland have
reason to envy the life in Northern Ireland. A married couple in
Dublin earning 25,000 Irish pounds pays 9,625 pounds in tax, while
a couple in Belfast earning 25,000 British pounds pays 5,467 pounds
in income tax.
   The cost of living in Dublin, excluding rent, matches London,
though wages are 27 percent lower, according to a 1988 survey by
the Union Bank of Switzerland.
   Making a virtue of adversity, the government's Industrial
Development Authority is promoting Ireland as a low-cost base
within the European Economic Community, whose members are to
abolish internal tariff barriers by the end of 1992 and create a
single market of 320 million people.
   Labor costs in Ireland averaged about $10 an hour in 1988,
compared with $11.21 in Britain and $18.38 in West Germany, the
development authority says.
   Fitz Gerald says improvements in employment are restrained by a
baby boom now working its way through the schools. The children
from the peak of that boom are now 9 years old and will be entering
the job market within a decade.
   Though the constitution no longer grants a special role to the
Roman Catholic Church, Ireland remains 93 percent Catholic and
divorce and abortion are illegal.
   Even though the birth rate has fallen by more than 25 percent
from 1980 to 1987, it remains the highest in the European Economic
Community, at 16.6 per 1,000.
   Michael Barry, senior lecturer at the National College of
Industrial Relations in Dublin, says that unless Ireland reduces
its population growth, it risks becoming ``a permanent low-wage
economy and a backwater and peripheral slum region of the new,
enlarged Europe.''
   He does not believe Ireland can ever support all its people, at
current rates of growth.
   ``With the industrial development policy, with its very best
efforts to attract foreign companies, they have only managed to
replace jobs _ low-wage jobs with high-wage jobs,'' Barry said in
an interview.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Oct. 29</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891023-0223 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-23-89 1531EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s i BC-Ireland-Youth Adv29   10-23 0686</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Ireland-Youth, Adv 29,0710</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv29</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Oct. 29, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Youth Getting a Boost in a Poor but Historic Dublin Neighborhood</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Ireland Today, b0543</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BARR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DUBLIN, Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The ladder of ambition for some of the
young men in old Dublin begins with breaking a car window, then
stealing what's inside the car, then stealing a whole car.
   Then they burn it, without stripping a few saleable parts.
   ``They don't think that far,'' says Gus Monaghan, who works with
young school dropouts in the rough and ready streets of the
Liberties, hoping to steer them away from a life of breaking into
cars.
   The neighborhood where Jonathan Swift wrote ``Gulliver's
Travels'' and George Frideric Handel premiered his ``Messiah'' can
be described today by what it lacks: parks, jobs and, for many, a
future.
   At a school established by the South Inner City Commmunity
Development Association, Monaghan starts with the basics, teaching
often unruly young school dropouts how to iron a shirt, cook a meal
or do simple carpentry.
   ``These young people have never been asked to accept the
consequences of their own actions,'' says David Orr, the school's
director.
   They and their neighbors are quite unprepared for any economic
miracles that may occur, Orr added.
   ``If Toyota walked in here and created 2,000 jobs, there would
be no one here to take them,'' he said.
   The Liberties, so called because it is outside the medieval city
walls, stands apart from an Irish economy that is generating record
trade surpluses and strong economic growth of 5 percent this year.
   That fortunate Dublin is seen on Grafton Street, where Ralph
Lauren and Laura Ashley set the marketing tone, but not on Meath
Street, the gritty strip in the Liberties where the inner city
assocation has its offices.
   ``It's a different world really,'' says Roisin Elliott, whose
work at the association includes counseling frightened people in
debt to loan sharks.
   Employment at the Guinness brewery, the neighborhood's biggest
industry, has dropped from 4,000 jobs two decades ago to 1,400.
   Liam Fenlon, who is chairman of the association's board, says
the group has put 175 young people to work _ ``people who normally
never ever got work, three-fourths of whom, I have no hesitation in
saying, would end up in jail.''
   The school's courses include woodworking, sewing and
photography, and it is placing 60 percent or more of its graduates
in fulltime jobs, he says.
   Three students have been studying German and will go to West
Germany for three months' work experience.
   ``If I get a job I'll stay, because there is nothing here,''
says Jinet McGuinness, 17, who left school three years ago.
   Glen Duggan, 17, also bound for Germany, joined the training
program a year after being expelled from school _ for throwing
chairs, he explains. Then he drifted on the streets.
   Stephen Domican, 16, is learning carpentry and wants to stay in
Dublin but says the neighborhood needs ``more houses, more jobs,
more construction.''
   Others cannot wait to leave.
   ``I'd go now but you're not allowed,'' said Audrey Langley, 15.
   ``I'd hate leaving my family and friends and where you grew up
and all,'' she added. ``Still, they can't expect you stay here and
live on the dole for the rest of your life.''
   Poverty is an ancient presence in the Liberties.
   Jonathan Swift, the dean of St. Patrick's Cathedral, raged at
Ireland's deprivation and in 1729 offered ``A Modest Proposal for
Preventing the Children of Ireland from being a Burden to their
Parents or Country.'' In that famous satire, his modest proposal
was to eat the young.
   Swift's grave in St. Patrick's Cathedral is a highlight of a
Liberties tour developed by the inner city association to create
four part-time jobs.
   Margaret Doyle always points out the banners of the Order of St.
Patrick in the cathedral and retells the story, possibly
apocryphal, of how prospective members demonstrated aristocratic
credentials.
   ``You had to prove that your family hadn't worked in 200
years,'' she said. ``We'll all qualify for it soon.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Oct. 29</NOTE>
