<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--OnShow Adv00   10-23 1030</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--On Show, Adv 00,1172</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Anytime</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>On Show: Museum and Gallery Exhibits and News</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Martin Friedman, who during 28 years as director of the Walker
Art Center in Minneapolis built the museum from a primarily
regional facility into a major national institution, has announced
his retirement, effective Nov. 1, 1990.
   Friedman, who has been associated with Walker for his entire
museum career, said he will turn 65 next year and it seemed time to
move on.
   A search committee has been formed to select a successor, said
Bruce Atwater, president of Walker's board.
   ``Martin Friedman's long and successful identification with the
Walker Art Center is well known throughout the art world, as well
as in this community,'' Atwater said. ``Thanks to his leadership,
the Walker Art Center is in excellent artistic and administrative
condition.''
   Friedman joined the Walker's staff as chief curator in 1958. He
served as Walker's acting director in 1960 and was named director
in 1961.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Here is a list of exhibits and shows at some musuems and
galleries in the United States:
   
   HOUSTON
   
   The Museum of Fine Arts:
   ``Containers and Vessels,'' an exhibition of 40 containers from
the Neolithic period to present. Through Jan. 21.
   
   ``The Grand Elegance Venice: Costumes of Mariano Fortuny.'' More
than 50 gowns, costumes and accessories created by Venetian
painter, engraver, theater designer and photographer Fortuny
(1871-1949). Through Dec. 31.
   
   NEW YORK
   
   Gallery Henoch:
   Recent sculpture by Carole Jeane Feuerman. Through Nov. 15.
   
   Opsis Gallery:
   ``Summer Light,'' the works of Norwegian photographer Dag
Alveng. Through Dec. 2.
   
   Union Square Gallery:
   ``Images From Haiti,'' works by Maggie Steber. Through Nov. 11.
   
   Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum:
   First major American exhibition of works by Italian artist Mario
Merz, who integrates natural materials into his work. Through Nov.
26.
   
   Washburn Gallery:
   ``Anne Ryan: A Centennial.'' Paintings, collages of artist-poet
Anne Ryan (1889-1954). Through Nov. 4.
   
   Metropolitan Museum of Art:
   Compositions by Diego Rodriquez de Silva y Velazquez, including
his ``An Old Woman Cooking Eggs'' (1618) with its haunting reality,
and ``The Forge of Vulcan'' and ``Joseph's Coat,'' two large works
painted during a trip to Italy in 1629-31. Through Jan. 7.
   ``Masterworks of Ming and Qing Painting From the Forbidden
City.'' Paintings dating from the Ming (1368-1644) and Qing
(1644-1911) dynasties. Through Oct. 29.
   Flemish drawings and prints from 16th and 17th centuries.
Through Nov. 12.
   
   Museum of Modern Art:
   ``Picasso and Braque: Pioneering Cubism.'' Through Jan. 16.
   
   Phillippe Staib Gallery:
   Bronze sculpture by Louis Derbre. Through Nov. 18.
   
   New York Historical Society:
   ``An American Sampler: Folk Art From the Shelburne Museum,''
featuring more than 120 works from the Vermont museum's Americana
collection. Through Jan. 7.
   
   DALLAS
   
   Dallas Museum of Art:
   ``Patrick Faigenbaum: Roman Portraits.'' Through Nov. 12.
   ``American Art, 1700 to 1950.'' Through April 8.
   ``Artful Deception: The Craft of the Forger.'' Through Dec. 17.
   
   Kimbell Art Museum:
   ``Style and Expressionism in Modern Chinese Painting: Robert
Hatfield Ellsworth Collection at the Metropolitan Museum of Art.''
Through Jan. 14.
   
   FORT WORTH, Texas
   
   Amon Carter Museum:
   ``Bourke-White: A Retrospective.'' Through Nov. 12.
   ``Hand, Eye and Stone: The Lithographs of Thomas Hart Benton.''
Through Nov. 19.
   
   PHOENIX
   
   Phoenix Art Museum:
   Cowboy Artists of America annual exhibition. Through Nov. 19.
   ``Rodin: Sculpture from the B. Gerald Cantor Collections.''
Through Dec. 3.
   Sino-Tibetan bronzes. Through Dec. 31.
   ``Word and Image.'' Works by Chinese painters and calligraphers.
Through Oct. 29.
   ``European and American 19th Century Works on Paper.'' Through
Nov. 19.
   ``2-D or Not 2-D?: Art as Illusion.'' Through Jan. 14.
   
   The Heard Museum:
   ``Exotic Illusions: Art, Romance and the Marketplace.''
Selections from the Heard's permanent collection demonstrate how
artists from Africa, Oceania and the Americas have produced exotic
materials for external consumption: pottery, carvings, paintings,
jewelry. Through Dec. 31.
   Recently cataloged acquisitions and other aspects of the
museum's permanent collection to highlight the work of contemporary
American Indian artists, including Fritz Scholder, Amado Pena, R.C.
Gorman and John Lightfoot. Through March.
   
   Meseo Chicano:
   ``Arte, Sweat and Tears,'' featuring works of Arizona Hispanic
artists and of Mexican painter Jose Luis Cuevas. Through Jan. 15.
   
   BOSTON
   
   Museum of Fine Arts:
   Lucas Samaras, ``Objects and Subjects, 1969-1986.'' Through Nov.
12.
   ``Textile Masterpieces.'' Through Dec. 31.
   ``Mary Cassatt: The Color Prints.'' Through Nov. 5.
   
   Institute of Contemporary Art:
   ``The Situationists International, 1957-1972.'' Works from the
anti-art movement of France. Through Jan. 15.
   
   Boston Museum of Science:
   ``Animal Art.'' Paintings of animals by various artists. Through
Jan. 15.
   
   CHICAGO
   
   Art Institute of Chicago:
   ``Western Textile Masterpieces From Coptic Times Through the
19th Century.'' Through Jan. 2.
   Continuing shows of Ellsworth Kelly paintings, Greek Island
embroideries and ``The Human Figure in Greek Art.''
   
   PHILADELPHIA
   
   Philadelphia Museum of Art
   ``As Pieces Here to Pieces Join: American Applique Quilts
1800-1900.'' Quilts from Museum collection. Through Dec. 31.
   ``Perpetual Motif: The Art of Man Ray.'' Through Jan. 7.
   
   STAMFORD, CONN.
   
   Whitney Museum of American Art, Fairfield County:
   ``Realism and Romanticism in 19th Century New England
Seascapes.'' Works of 30 artists ranging from ship portraits and
seascapes to pirate scenes and sunsets. Through Nov. 29.
   
   RICHMOND, Va.
   
   Virginia Museum of Fine Arts:
   Prints by art deco French artist Marie Laurencin (1885-1956).
Through Dec. 3.
   ``Robert Jessup _ Paintings.'' Through Oct. 29.
   ``Imperial Taste: Chinese Ceramics From the Percival David
Foundation.'' Through Dec. 10.
   
   WASHINGTON
   
   National Gallery of Art:
   Works of Frederic Edwin Church. Through Jan. 28.
   
   SEATTLE
   
   The Seattle Art Museum:
   ``Shadowy Evidence: The Photography of Edward S. Curtis and His
Contemporaries.'' Curtis was one of photography's masters of
pictorialism, an early 20th century practice characterized by soft
focus and eccentric composition. Through Nov. 19.
   
   Greg Kucera Gallery:
   ``Taboo.'' An exhibit of controversial art by 20 artists,
including Anores Serrano, Gale McCall and Joel-Peter Witkin.
Through Oct. 29.
   
   PORTLAND, Ore.
   
   Portland Art Museum:
   Minor White, a photography retrospective. Through Nov. 12.
   ``Grafica Popular,'' 20th century Mexican prints. Through Nov.
19.
</TEXT>
