<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--Annaud Adv03-05   10-23 1080</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Annaud, Adv 03-05,1102</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv03</HEAD>
<HEAD>$adv04</HEAD>
<HEAD>$adv05</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, Nov. 3-5, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Star Watch: A Different Kind of Movie</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: `The Bear' opened Oct. 27 in limited theaters.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   French filmmaker Jean-Jacques Annaud recently
talked about why he has spent the last 10 years making three highly
original films, ``Quest for Fire,'' ``The Name of the Rose'' and
``The Bear.''
   ``I always see audiences begging for something different,'' he
said. ``It's difficult to make something different today. Many
films have been made, and there are many good filmmakers around. To
bring something fresh to the screen is difficult, let's face it.
   ``This is what pushes me. It's so pleasant seeing people come
out of the cinema having the impression that they discovered
something new. They are happily surprised, and I think that's a
great reward.''
   ``The Bear'' is unquestionably different. Based on the old James
Oliver Curwood novel ``The Grizzly King,'' it tells the battles of
a small cub and a huge male bear against hunters and nature. The
film already has grossed more than $100 million in Europe.
   ``The large part of the battle is to explain to the public the
nature of this film. It's an entertainment. It's not documentary.
It's not the old-fashioned Disney animal picture. It's not a
wilderness picture,'' he said.
   ``When I tell people my last film is about two bears, they're
convinced it's for kids. It's not a National Geographic
(television) special. How can I explain to people that it is
something that they have not seen _ yet? Fortunately when I arrived
here, the Hollywood Reporter said it was similar to `E.T.' Thank
you.''
   Annaud's history with ``The Bear'' dates back to 1981, when he
had finished his prehistoric adventure, ``Quest for Fire.'' He fell
in love with Curwood's book, then was sidetracked by ``The Name of
the Rose.''
   ``The Bear'' was launched in 1986. Annaud, himself a bear of a
man with curly, graying hair and a charming accent, plunged himself
into the new project, exploring locations, checking out bear
trainers, steeping himself in animal behavior.
   ``The Bear'' was filmed in Europe's Dolomites from May 18, 1987,
to the following Sept. 21. The difficulties with animals, weather
and managing a 200-person crew were enormous, but Annaud was
exhilarated by his actors.
   ``Bears are very fascinating animals,'' he said. ``They are as
intelligent as dogs, but they have something dogs do not: They
spend a lot of their time standing up. Because of that, there is
immediate identification with human beings.
   ``Take a lion. A fascinating animal, but it remains a beast. A
bear is a beast in the four-leg version. Very hairy. Very noisy.
It's fascinating, he's so powerful. Suddenly, he stands up (Annaud
demonstrates, bearlike). The front legs look like arms. They use
their paws like arms. Their claws like fingers. If you see a bear
eat an apple, it's just like a human.''
   The two principals were played by Bart, a Baltimore Zoo grizzly
trained by Doug Seus of Utah, and Douce (``sweet''), a cub from a
French zoo. Were there days when the two stars simply didn't want
to act?
   ``Of course,'' said the director. ``Any star you work with has
bad days. Stars are very temperamental. So are bears. You cannot
push them. In any case, I would not advise a director to push a
star. A star must be happy in front of the camera _ especially when
they are bears and they can kill you if you're not.
   ``I swear that if you try to get something from an animal who is
not in a good mood, not only will you not get it that day, you will
never get it. What you have to do is organize the set so the animal
will be happy with its own instincts, digging in its own nature to
discover what it would do in such a circumstance. He would in
effect rewrite the script.''
   He cited the example of a scene in which the grizzly scratches
its back on a tree. The scene took days of preparation: finding a
tree with rough bark, laying a cement platform at the base and
covering it with moss, surrounding the tree with rocks, putting
sand on the bear's back so it would itch. A few seconds on the
screen, the scene took a day to shoot.
   ``My first concern with the film was that no animal would get
hurt,'' said Annaud. ``Second concern, although there is no Society
for the Prevention of Cruelty to Technicians nor Actors _ because
they're not endangered species _ I was very worried about working
every day with those enormous monsters.''
   He became more worried toward the end of shooting because no
incidents had occurred. One girl had tried to remove her finger
from the cub's mouth and nearly lost her finger when the cub bit
down. The only other casualty was Annaud himself. He ``foolishly''
posed for photographs with Bart in the cage. Like some stars in the
past, Bart turned on his director in a bad mood ``and decided to
kill me.''
   Annaud followed the safety instruction of playing dead when
menaced, and Bart retreated.
   A scene that amazes previewers comes when Bart roars at hunter
Tcheky Karyo at close range on a mountain ledge. It's the real
thing, the director assured. Bear and actor were a few feet apart,
but Karyo had the option of leaping to a net 30 feet below.
   ``The Bear'' credits list Jim Henson's Creature Shop as creators
of ``animatronic bears.'' But Annaud assured that the Henson fakes
were used only for battle scenes.
   ``Henson's contribution was to avoid putting the animals in any
situation where they were at risk,'' said Annaud. ``For instance, I
have a fight between bears and dogs. As long as there is no body
contact, there is a real bear. But when you see the dogs biting the
fur, you don't need a real bear. But the fur needs life in it, so
that was where Henson came in.'' The same with a fight between the
cub and a puma.
   His next project?
   ``I don't know. Even though `The Bear' is a success in Europe, I
want to see how it does here. My films have not been terribly
successful here. I hope that will change.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, Nov. 3-5</NOTE>
