<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--Norman Adv03-05   10-23 0880</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Norman, Adv 03-05,0908</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv03</HEAD>
<HEAD>$adv04</HEAD>
<HEAD>$adv05</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, Nov. 3-5, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Books and Authors: The Inspiration of Lobbies</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HILLEL ITALIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Howard Norman isn't writing, he lobbies.
Actually, he sits in lobbies _ hotel lobbies, and especially, movie
lobbies.
   The author likes watching people buy tickets and walk inside. On
a cold day, he appreciates the smell and warmth of the popcorn
maker and coffee machine. And in his beloved Savoy Theater in
Vermont, there's a book left out for suggestions.
   So hotels and movie houses appear often in his work, which
includes the 1987 novel ``Northern Lights,'' nominated for the
National Book Award, and the recently published ``Kiss in the Hotel
Joseph Conrad (Summit, $18.95), a collection of short stories.
   ``In lobbies, one lives in a pure state of expectation,'' said
Norman, 40. ``You're in between. You're sort of safe. You haven't
been disappointed yet by anything that has happened.
   ``You're off the street. It has something to do with being
protected and not responsible but being able to observe and take
everything in.''
   Lobbies are like sneak previews for Norman, opportunities for
eavesdropping and observation. In his stories, lobbies are where
young lovers meet, old ones reunite and former actresses recapture
their past.
   In the title story of ``Kiss in the Hotel Joseph Conrad,'' a man
spends his entire life drifting from lobby to lobby as he pursues
an unrequited love from his youth, a woman who worked a kissing
booth during World War II.
   ``I was trying to show how one single event can consume a
person. Just seeing a woman and making that person your entire life
without any rhyme or reason except for an emotional one,'' he said.
   ``I didn't want to psychologize too much in these stories. It's
a conscious effort to take yourself out of the story. You always
tell young writers, `Show, don't tell.'''
   Norman, born in Iowa, had traveled extensively in Canada as a
writer for wildlife magazines and learned the native languages well
enough to produce three collections of translated works.
   The death of a friend helped inspire ``Northern Lights,'' in
which a teen-age boy, Noah, shuttles between a broken home in
Toronto and life in Quill, a northern Manitoba settlement where his
best friend, Pelly, has been killed in a freak accident.
   The seasons are important in ``Northern Lights.'' Summers, the
time for experience, are spent in Quill. As the days shorten and
winter arrives, Noah returns home.
   ``In summer you're out and time seems to be totally open to
you,'' Norman said. ``Everything seems possible.
   ``Winter seems to have direct conflicts in terms of your sense
of time. It closes you in, you have to bundle up. One's moods are
more acute. These characters seem to be very moody characters.''
   The novel's title is derived, naturally, from a movie theater
that Noah's mother purchases with the hope of bringing the family
together. In ``Whatever Lola Wants,'' a story from Norman's new
book, movies at the Moonlight drive-in theater shine on falling
snow.
   ``I've worked in two movie theaters, one when I was 16 and one
in college,'' Norman said. ``The first time I went to work in a
movie theater I thought that's what I'd be doing. I saw it as a
possible occupation. So I guess in that sense there was a domestic
aspect to it.''
   Disappointment, Norman said, is another important part of his
work. Not just unrequited love, but the loss of innocence, the
inability to enjoy life without complications.
   In ``Whatever Lola Wants,'' the title character is a former
actress from the 1940s who persuades her husband to show one of her
old films, ``White Savage,'' at the Moonlight. Watching the film,
in which she is captured by cannibals, Lola sadly reflects on
dreams long faded:
   ``That scene when the camera is on me, just before the cannibals
arrive. Just by campfire light that way, with everything about my
face and character calm and brave and just right. When I was a
girl, that's who I wanted to be.''
   The friendship of Noah and Pelly in ``Northern Lights'' is
written with the same longing for simplicity.
   ``I thought of how at that age you have a friendship without
what happens later when you start to psychologize,'' the author
said. ``The kind of friendship you have at that age, which is why
coming-of-age novels are fundamentally of such interest to people.
   ``Those friendships are unlike anything you have later. You're
almost entirely relating on an emotional level to the other person.
You're just interested in his company. You aren't alone.''
   But for Norman, the teen-ager's desire for companionship has
given way to a writer's need for privacy, even in a crowded lobby.
   ``It has something to do with the fact that as you get older,
you feel your time is less your own,'' he said. ``You have
responsibilities, like money, no matter how isolated you're living.
Your time is precious.
   ``You can live vicariously in a hotel lobby like the Algonquin.
You watch people come and go, just sit in the lobby and totally
live a vicarious existence.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, Nov. 3-5</NOTE>
