<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--Craddock Adv03-05   10-23 0554</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Craddock, Adv 03-05,0565</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv03</HEAD>
<HEAD>$adv04</HEAD>
<HEAD>$adv05</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, Nov. 3-5, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Nashville Sound: Billy `Crash' Craddock Is `Back on Track'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE EDWARDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Billy ``Crash'' Craddock, who had a
litany of hits in the 1970s, but who gave up making records in
1981, has returned with an album aptly titled ``Back on Track.''
   After releasing such hits as ``Knock Three Times,'' ``Rub It
In,'' ``Easy as Pie'' and ``Broken Down in Tiny Pieces,'' Craddock
quit the studio to ponder his future and keep an eye on his bank
balance.
   Nicknamed for his crashing style of play in high school
football, he kept active by making personal appearances. He signed
with Atlantic Records and ``Back on Track'' is his first recording
for the label.
   He won't go into detail about his problems, but he was a party
to a lawsuit involving the country group Alabama.
   Craddock was a co-owner of a booking agency that promoted
concerts by the award-winning four-piece band. Alabama and the
agency became embroiled in a $3 million suit over commissions. The
matter was settled out of court in 1987 and the terms were never
announced.
   ``Nobody ever needs to be in a lawsuit,'' Craddock said.
``Everything is cool now. Nobody wins in a lawsuit. It's going to
hurt you one way or another. You may win one way but it's going to
hurt you in another.
   ``When you are involved in a lawsuit, you've got other things on
your mind when you try to do a road show. You can't get your mind
on recording. So I backed away a little.
   ``When you have certain problems, you kind of feel rejected. I
didn't know whether to retire or make another stab at it. I kind of
wanted people to accept me again. I wasn't sure if they would or
not.''
   His version of ``Knock Three Times'' in 1971 ignited a string of
nine No. 1 records and 20 others that reached the Top 10 of the
country charts. He took Tony Orlando's pop version of the song,
added fiddles and came up with a country alternative that made the
tune one of the most heard of its time.
   In his heyday, Craddock gave one of the most dynamic concerts in
country music. Clad in form-fitting outfits, he gyrated across the
stage and flirted with fans.
   His show hasn't changed much, as he does up-tempo songs, ballads
and a rock 'n' roll medley of old tunes. His followers have
remained loyal.
   The first single released from Craddock's comeback album is
``Just Another Miserable Day (Here in Paradise),'' which is about a
man in Florida separated from his lover. Other cuts include his
version of the Hank Williams Sr. hit ``I Can't Help It (If I'm
Still in Love With You)'' and the nostalgic ``The Girls That
Everybody Knew,'' whose lyrics rattle off the names of girls
mentioned in hit songs down through the years (Barbara Ann, Mary
Lou, Peggy Sue).
   ``I think we're headed in the right direction now,'' he said.
``I don't think it (the recording hiatus) hurt too much because
we've been traveling lots of days and the fans have still been
coming out.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, Nov. 3-5</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891023-0233 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-23-89 0733EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-DangeratWork-Stats     10-23 0584</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Danger at Work-Stats,0640</SECOND>
<HEAD>Facts, Figures on Worker Injures</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Danger at Work</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are some statistics on worker safety and production
provided by the National Safety Council, the National Safe
Workplace Institute, the Institute for Southern Studies, the United
Food and Commercial Workers Union, the United Autoworkers Union and
federal government agencies.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   INJURIES _ ALL INDUSTRIES (PER 100 FULL-TIME WORKERS):
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   _Total cases recorded
   1983: 7.6
   1986: 7.9
   1987: 8.3
   _ Total lost workdays
   1983: 58.5
   1986: 65.8
   1987: 69.9
   _ There were about 3,600 work-related deaths and 5.6 million
occupational injuries and illnesses among 83 million private-sector
employees, a 1986 Bureau of Labor Statistics survey said. One-third
of the injuries and illnesses were in manufacturing, which accounts
for more than 20 percent of the work force.
   _ One of 11 workers will be seriously injured or killed at work,
according to the National Safe Workplace Institute.
   _ A U.S. worker is injured every 16 seconds and one of every six
workers will die from occupation-related diseases, the institute
said.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   DISABILITIES:
   _ Permanent work-related disabilities increased from 60,000 to
70,000 from 1986 to 1987 _ a 16 percent increase, the National
Safety Council said.
   _ However, the rate of disabling work injuries per 1 million
exposure hours dropped from 8.3 to 8.1 in the same period, the
council noted.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   DANGEROUS INDUSTRIES:
   _ In 1987, ship building and repairing led the nation with 40.1
injuries and illnesses per 100 full-time workers, the government
said. Among other hazardous industries were meatpacking and mobile
homes construction.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   U.S. VS. OTHERS:
   _ The United States had the highest worker fatality rate
compared with six other industrialized nations, the workplace
institute said. Figures compiled by the International Labor Office
showed the industrial accident death rate was 3.6 per 100,000
workers.
   Japan was second-highest with 2.3 deaths, followed by Italy,
1.6, France, 1, West Germany, 0.8, the United Kingdom, 0.4, Sweden,
0.1. (All figures 1986 except Italy, 1984).
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   REPETITIVE TRAUMA:
   _ Reported repetitive trauma disorder cases, including hearing
loss, rose from 26,700 in 1983 to 72,940 in 1987, the government
said.
   _ They accounted for 38 percent of occupational illnesses in
1987, compared with 28 percent in 1984, according to a Labor
Department survey. Such ailments hit 4 out of every 100 poultry
processing and meatpacking workers in 1987.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   MEATPACKING:
   _ More than a third of packinghouse workers will suffer a
serious illness or injury this year, translating into more than
52,000 workers annually or 200 daily, the United Food and
Commercial Workers Union said.
   _ Between 1981 and 1983, meatpacking production jumped by 52
percent, the union said, while employment declined by almost 20
percent.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   POULTRY:
   _ Workers doing evisceration work handled 50-70 birds a minute
in the '70s; now they're processing up to 90 birds a minute, the
Institute for Southern Studies said.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   CONSTRUCTION-MINING-MANUFACTURING:
   _ In construction, total lost workdays per 100 workers in 1987
came to 135.8, compared with 69.9 for all private-sector
industries, the government said. It was 144 in mining, 95.5 in
manufacturing.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   AUTOS:
   _ Total injury rates in large plants in the motor vehicle
industry reported to the Bureau of Labor Statistics in 1987 were
2.5 times those reported in 1985, according to congressional
testimony by the United Autoworkers Union.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   COSTS:
   _ The workplace institute estimates a worker fatality, including
lost income and taxes, costs the economy $1.4 million. Other
estimates have ranged from $900,000 to $1.9 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
