<DOCNO> AP891023-0235 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-23-89 0736EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-T-Shirts     10-23 0366</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-T-Shirts,0379</SECOND>
<HEAD>T-Shirts: $10 Billion Business in `Wearable Art'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Don't call them T-shirts. ``Imprinted sportswear''
is the language preferred these days in a $10 billion business that
has its roots in the tie-dyed 1960s.
   ``It started ... when people found out you could take a T-shirt
and put a message on it,'' said Milt Anglin, general merchandise
manager for Waco-based Plus Companies, which owns the nation's
largest chain of retail T-shirt stores.
   Screen printers, monogrammers and applique-makers vied with
clothing manufacturers, distributors and designers for attention at
the Imprinted Sportswear Convention here last week.
   About 6,000 people attended the convention, which featured
displays ranging from neon-bright shirts and shorts to basic black
and white shirts. Decorations included fabric paint, sequins, foil
transfers and various trinkets.
   Officials said 1.6 billion T-shirts were sold in the United
States last year, with more than 20 percent of American shoppers
buying 10 or more shirts. Anglin estimated that 90 percent of the
T-shirt business is in shirts and other articles priced from $15 to
$35 and imprinted with everything from favorite colleges to rock
groups to cartoon characters _ Mickey Mouse and Batman are big this
year _ to free-form designs with ``tons of glitz.''
   ``T-shirts have moved up to high fashion and high profits,''
Anglin said. ``A dollar's worth of trim should yield up to five
times the original value of the shirt.''
   For Dino Calabrese, a design consultant for Transfermania Inc.,
clothing is a canvas for wearable art.
   Calabrese, said he once used transfers to create a $900 evening
dress and spends much time looking for new things to stick on
clothes. ``Right now, I'm looking at a fabric developed out of
cork,'' he said.
   And yes, tie-dye is back, meaning hipsters of 25 years ago can
impress their children.
   Upon seeing an old tie-dyed shirt, Anglin said his 20-year-old
daughter was dumbfounded. ``I had no idea you were so cool,'' she
told him.
   Calabrese said imprinted clothing _ shoes, jackets, caps or
T-shirts that become dresses _ allows individuality. ``People are
very much into doing their own thing these days,'' he said, echoing
the tie-dyed era.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
