prevent Sony Corp. from hiring producers Peter Guber and Jon Peters
to head the entertainment company Sony plans to acquire, Columbia
Pictures.
   A motion for a preliminary injunction, filed Thursday in Los
Angeles Superior Court, asks a judge to bar Sony from hiring the
``Batman'' producers, who are trying to get out of a five-year
contract they signed with Warner earlier this year.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co. and Saab-Scania AB said they were
calling off talks analysts said might have been aimed at developing
a European truck operation for Ford.
   The companies said in a joint statement Friday that the
discussions were friendly but produced no agreement ``that could
make long-term business sense for both parties.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British Petroleum Co. PLC said it has agreed to
sell its Australian coal business to CRA Ltd. for $275 million in
cash, as part of a recently announced restructuring of the
London-based company.
   The deal, announced Friday after a meeting of British Petroleum
executives and securities analysts in New York, is expected to be
closed on Nov. 30. The sale is subject to approval by government
regulators.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market posted mixed results Friday, closing out a week
of record-setting recovery from the scary selloff of Oct. 13. The
Dow Jones industrial average rose 5.94 to 2,689.14, stretching its
gain for the week to 119.88 points.
   The dollar ended higher in quiet trading.
   Government bond prices finished lower.
   Copper futures prices plummeted to new lows for the month;
precious metals were nearly flat; energy futures fell; grains and
soybeans retreated; livestock and meat futures were mixed; and
stock-index futures advanced.
