<FIRST>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     10-23 0347</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0362</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Higher in Calm Trading, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was slightly higher in calm trading in
Europe early today and dealers said they expected little movement
in the currency until the publication of U.S. economic growth
figures on Thursday.
   Gold prices moved lower.
   The dollar was fluctuating in a narrow range between 1.85 and
1.86 West German marks, and likely would stay there until the
release of U.S. gross national product estimates for the third
quarter, dealers said.
   ``The bulls and bears are in balance, so I don't see major
changes until Thursday,'' said Dieter Manderbach, a trader at
Norddeutsche Landesbank Girozentrale in Hanover, West Germany.
   Another dealer, at a European bank in Frankfurt, said: ``It's
very sluggish right now. ... A trend in one or the other direction
should crystallize after the (GNP) figures.''
   Economists expected the third-quarter growth rate to be little
changed from its moderate 2.5 percent in the second quarter, but
some traders anticipated a sharp slowdown.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar rose 1.05 yen to a closing 142.40 yen. Later, in
London, it was quoted at a higher rate of 142.47 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Friday's
prices, included: 1.8570 West German marks, up from 1.8535; 1.6295
Swiss francs, up from 1.6255; 6.3040 French francs, up from 6.2962;
2.0970 Dutch guilders, down from 2.0973; 1,365.00 Italian lire, up
from 1,363.65; and 1.1730 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1732.
   In London, the dollar gained against the British pound. It cost
$1.5875 to buy one pound, compared with $1.5885 late Friday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $365.80 a troy ounce,
compared with late Friday's $366.75. At midmorning, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price also of $365.80.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $365.90 compared with $366.00 late
Friday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell 53 cents to close at a bid
$366.54.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $5.08 a troy
ounce, down from Friday's $5.09.
</TEXT>
