<FIRST>u f PM-Japan-Markets     10-23 0329</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0343</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Up In Tokyo, Stocks Edge Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose against the Japanese yen today,
while share prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange advanced slightly.
   The dollar closed at 142.40 yen, up 1.05 yen from Friday's close
of 141.35 yen. After opening at 141.95 yen, the dollar ranged from
141.95-142.40 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, a 112.16-point
gainer Friday, added 99.14 points, or 0.27 percent, closing the
day's session at 35,585.52.
   Currency dealers said the dollar remained relatively strong
against the yen despite a lack of fresh market-affecting news.
   ``The market tried the downside of the dollar in Sydney,'' said
Minori Takeuchi, a trader at Chemical Bank. ``Then in the afternoon
in Tokyo traders began to cover their short dollar positions. There
weren't any strong trends.''
   Traders said the market was closely watching the activity of the
U.S. Federal Reserve Board, the American central bank, for signs of
an ease in monetary policy.
   ``Market players are interested in whether the Federal Reserve
Board will consider taking an easy credit policy in view of U.S.
economic indices'' to be released this week, said a dealer with the
Bank of Tokyo, speaking anonymously.
   The upcoming U.S. economic figures include the nation's
third-quarter gross national product, due out Thursday, and the
personal income and consumption spending figures for September, due
Friday.
   On the stock market, the Nikkei index continued to gain for the
fifth consecutive trading day.
   ``Volume was low at 600 million shares, but good for a Monday.
People were feeling quite confident,'' said Stephen Hill, head of
sales at Jardine Fleming Securities.
   He said non-life insurance companies rose on stories of mergers
and acquisitions, and recovered from their drop following the San
Francisco earthquake last week. ``There was a realization that they
were not as exposed as people had thought,'' he said.
   Shipping issues were up, while pharmaceuticals were strong on
merger and acquisition rumors and new drugs, he said.
</TEXT>
