<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   10-23 0345</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0357</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grain Markets Mostly Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices were mostly
lower in early trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade, with
harvest pressure offsetting the positive impact of new export sales.
   The corn market fell after opening nearly unchanged, surprising
analysts who had expected a higher opening based on the Agriculture
Department's announcement late Friday that the Soviet Union had
bought 2.8 million metric tons of U.S. corn.
   The confirmation brought to more than 7.8 million metric tons
the total amount of corn purchased by Soviets since the new crop
year began Sept. 1.
   ``The question from here is, are they going to buy more or are
we pretty well done,'' said William Biedermann, director of
research with Allendale Inc., a futures brokerage in Crystal Lake,
Ill. ``That's why we're kind of stalled here.''
   Further selling was linked to the fine harvest weather that
occurred in the Midwest over the weekend and is predicted for the
region through Friday.
   In early trading, wheat futures were 1{ cents to 2} cents lower
with the contract for delivery in December at $2.41 a bushel; corn
futures were { cent to 2 cents lower with December at $2.41 a
bushel; oats were { cent lower to \ cent higher with December at
$1.44} a bushel; soybeans were 1{ cents lower to 3{ cents higher
with November at $5.62 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mostly higher in early trading
on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange after Friday's USDA report
showing fewer cattle on feed than the market had expected.
   Live cattle futures were .22 cent to .68 cent higher with
December at 75.37 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .20 cent to .65
cent higher with October at 83 cents a pound; live hogs were .05
cent lower to .45 cent higher with December at 47.25 cents a pound;
frozen pork bellies were .07 cent lower to .18 cent higher with
February at 52.95 cents a pound.
   Cattle futures settled lower on Friday while pork futures
advanced.
</TEXT>
