<FILEID>AP-NR-10-23-89 1318EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-McDonald's     10-23 0248</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-McDonald's,0258</SECOND>
<HEAD>Overseas Sales Help Lift Third-Quarter Earnings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OAK BROOK, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   McDonald's Corp. reported on Monday a 14
percent increase in its third-quarter earnings due largely to
strong sales overseas and domestic promotional programs.
   For the latest three months, the company that made the Big Mac a
worldwide phenomenon reported net income of $217.9 million, or 59
cents a share, up from $191 million, or 51 cents a share, a year
earlier.
   Third-quarter revenue rose 9.4 percent to $1.63 billion from
$1.46 billion in 1988. Systemwide sales, which includes sales at
franchised restaurants as well as those that are company-owned,
rose 9 percent to $4.58 billion from $4.19 billion in third-quarter
of 1988.
   The company said sales growth was particularly strong in markets
outside of the United States, especially in Europe.
   Contributing to improved U.S. sales were marketing and
promotional programs that include ``Happy Birthday Big Mac'' and
the firm's Scrabble game, McDonald's said.
   ``In addition, sales were positively impacted by the national
introduction of the McChicken sandwich in the United States in May
... .'' the company said.
   For the nine months that ended Sept. 30, net income rose 12
percent to $555 million, or $1.49 a share, from $494 million, or
$1.31 a share, a year ago.
   Nine-month revenue totaled $4.5 billion, up 11 percent from $4.1
billion for the first nine months of 1988, the company said.
Systemwide sales rose to $12.8 billion, up 8 percent from $11.9
billion a year earlier.
</TEXT>
