<FILEID>AP-NR-10-23-89 1331EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-CumminsEngine     10-23 0223</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Cummins Engine,0234</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reports $39.7 Million Third-Quarter Loss</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cummins Engine Co. on Monday reported
third-quarter losses of $39.7 million, blaming a decline in engine
orders from makers of heavy-duty trucks, the company's largest
single market.
   Cummins said the losses, equal to $4.12 a share, compared with
losses of $17.6 million, or $1.84 a share, in the same 1988 period.
   The engine maker reported third-quarter sales of $807.6 million,
compared with $808.3 million in last year's quarter.
   Cummins also noted a 30 percent decline from a year ago in sales
of generator sets for marine and recreational vehicle markets at
its largest subsidiary, Onan Corp.
   For the first nine months of 1989, Cummins reported profits of
$3.6 million on sales of $2.65 billion. But after deducting
preferred and preference stock dividends, the company reported a
per-share loss of 31 cents.
   In the first three quarters last year, Cummins had losses of
$8.43 million, or $1.36 a share, on sales of $2.44 billion.
   Anticipating the quarterly loss, the company recently laid off
300 production workers and temporarily reduced the pay of some
salaried employees and executives.
   Salaried workers' pay was reduced by 5 percent, while some
company officers reduced their pay by 7.5 percent to 10 percent.
   The cut-cutting measures affected only employees at the
company's plants in southern Indiana.
</TEXT>
