<FILEID>AP-NR-10-23-89 1412EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Allied-Signal     10-23 0232</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Allied-Signal,0242</SECOND>
<HEAD>3rd-Qtr Earnings Rise Slightly</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MORRIS TOWNSHIP, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Allied-Signal Inc. said Monday its
third-quarter profit edged up 1.7 percent as lower returns from its
automotive operations offset increases in aerospace and engineered
materials.
   Net income for the third quarter was $121 million, or 81 cents
per share, compared with $119 million, or 80 cents per share, a
year earlier.
   Third-quarter revenue slipped to $2.83 billion from $2.86
billion a year earlier.
   Excluding onetime charges, the company said net income from its
aerospace business rose 34 percent to $55 million while net income
from its engineered materials business rose 4.8 percent to $66
million.
   However, the company reported net income from its automotive
operations fell to $11 million this year from $33 million last
year, excluding onetime charges. It blamed overall declines in
original equipmnmet car and trucks sales, increased investment in
anti-lock brake systems, unfavorable foreign exchange conversion
and an unusually low effective tax rate last year.
   ``We foresee continued strength in both our aerospace and
engineered materials businesses and a rebound in our automotive
operations,'' said Edward L. Hennessy, Jr., the company's chairman
and chief executive officer.
   For the first nine months, Allied-Signal said it earned $413
million, or $2.77 a share, up 15 percent from $359 million, or
$2.40 per share, a year earlier.
   Nine-month revenue slipped to $8.88 billion from $8.90 billion a
year earlier.
</TEXT>
