<FIRST>u f BC-BritishStocks 1stLd-Writethru f0024 10-23 0238</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-British Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0024,0244</SECOND>
<HEAD>London Shares Close Higher</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: RECASTS throughout to UPDATE with later activity, closing indices;
No pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices closed modestly higher Monday on the
London Stock Exchange, in the lightest volume so far this year,
ahead of Tuesday's release of British trade figures for September.
   Dealers said the day's modest gains signaled some support for
London equities. They pegged the support largely to anticipation
that Britain's trade imbalance cannot be much worse than the
near-record deficits seen in July and August.
   But the very light volume reflected nervousness, dealers said.
   Volume was 276.8 million shares, breaking the year's previous
low of 280.5 million shares recorded on Sept. 25. Last Friday,
351.3 million shares changed hands.
   ``It's a case of the market being too high to buy and too afraid
to sell,'' said a senior dealer with the London investment firm
Kleinwort Benson Securities. ``It's better to wait.''
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index finished 10.6
points, or 0.5 percent, higher at 2,189.7.
   The index opened at a session low of 2,179.5 and rose to a high
of 2,195.9 shortly before Wall Street opened on a slightly weak
note.
   The early action in New York helped knock London's 100-share
index down a bit in late trading.
   The Financial Times 30-share index closed 11.6 points higher at
1,772.6. The Financial Times 500-share index rose 5.2 points to
close at 1,215.62.
</TEXT>
