<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   10-23 0251</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0259</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grain Futures Close Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Futures prices of grain and soybeans closed
narrowly mixed Monday on the Chicago Board of Trade with prices for
near-month corn and wheat deliveries supported by export demand and
other contracts weakened by harvest pressure.
   Indications that China was seeking to buy 330,000 metric tons of
subsidized U.S. wheat prompted buying of December wheat futures,
analysts said.
   The Agriculture Department's confirmation last Friday of a sale
of 2.8 million metric tons of U.S. corn to the Soviet Union helped
to limit losses in the December corn market. The confirmation
brought to more than 7.8 million metric tons the total amount of
corn purchased by the Soviets for delivery in the new crop year,
which began Sept. 1.
   Contracts for deferred delivery of corn finished moderately
lower on selling linked to forecasts for continued good harvesting
weather in the Midwest.
   A USDA report released after the close of trading showed a 20
percent increase in the amount of wheat inspected for export last
week compared with the previous week, while corn and soybean
inspections were little changed.
   At the close, wheat futures prices were 2{ cents lower to } cent
higher with December at $4.07} a bushel; corn was \ cent to 2{
cents lower with December at $2.41\ a bushel; oats were unchanged
to 1 cent higher with December at $1.45} a bushel; soybeans were {
cent lower to 2{ cents higher with November at $5.63 a bushel.
</TEXT>
