<FILEID>AP-NR-10-23-89 1913EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Banks     10-23 0363</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Banks,0378</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bankers Trust Posts $1.42 Billion Loss</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bankers Trust New York Corp. on Monday posted a
third-quarter loss of $1.42 billion, confirming an amount revealed
recently when Bankers Trust announced a big boost in its loan-loss
reserve to cover problem debt.
   The loss for the three months ended Sept. 30 came to $17.39 a
share and compared with a profit of $162.1 million, or $2.01 a
share, in 1988's third quarter.
   Last week the New York-based bank holding company said it was
making a $1.6 billion special addition to its provision for
potentially bad Third World loans, joining a long list of major
U.S. banks that have bolstered their reserves.
   The special addition raised Bankers Trust's allowance for credit
losses to $2.91 billion, or 14 percent of total loans on Sept. 30.
   If it hadn't set aside the additional funds, Bankers Trust would
have earned $180 million, or $2.18 a share, in the third quarter,
up $17.9 mlilion or 11 percent from a year earlier.
   Bankers Trust Chairman Charles S. Sanford Jr. said that apart
from the loan-loss provision, third-quarter results benefited from
higher noninterest revenue and a lower effective tax rate.
   These were partially offset by increases in noninterest expenses
and provisions for debts _ other than the special addition.
   Noninterest revenue totaled $505 million in the third quarter,
up $57.7 million or 13 percent from a year earlier. Higher fees and
commissions plus increases in trust and custodian revenue
contributed to the overall gain in noninterest revenue.
   A decline in revenue, however, partially offset the increases.
Revenue fell $33.7 million to $82.3 million.
   The effective tax rate was 18 percent in the third quarter
compared with 31 percent in the third 1988 quarter.
   Total noninterest expenses were $470.5 million, up $54.4 million
or 13 percent over 1988.
   For the first nine months of the year, Bankers Trust lost $1.08
billion, or $13.27 a share, compared with earnings of $462.2
million, or $5.80 a share, a year earlier.
   Excluding the third-quarter loan-loss provision, nine-month
earnings would have been $518.9 million, $6.34 a share, up $56.7
million or 12 percent from the first three quarters of 1988.
</TEXT>
