<SECOND>BC-Earns-Cap Cities,0254</SECOND>
<HEAD>Capital Cities Posts 29 Percent Earnings Rise in Third Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Capital Cities-ABC Inc. said Monday its
third-quarter earnings climbed 29 percent from a year earlier,
citing significantly higher revenue at its ABC Television Network,
its TV stations and the ESPN cable network.
   The company, which also has interests in radio and publishing,
said it earned $80.8 million, or $4.56 a share, in the three months
ended Sept. 30 compared with $62.6 million, or $3.55 a share, a
year earlier.
   Third-quarter revenue rose 9 percent to $1.10 billion from $1.01
billion a year earlier.
   Chairman Thomas S. Murphy said stronger advertising demand
boosted revenue at the ABC Television network, the company's eight
TV stations and the 80 percent-owned ESPN cable network.
   Operating income rose 14 percent to $157.3 million, as income
from broadcasting rose 18 percent and publishing edged up 1 percent.
   The TV stations and ESPN reported significant increases in
operating earnings, while higher program and news-gathering costs
moderated the earnings improvement at the ABC Television Network.
   For the first nine months, Capital Cities-ABC said net income
rose 23 percent to $303.7 million, or $16.97 a share, from $246.9
million, or $14.43 a share, a year earlier.
   Nine-month revenue slipped to $3.45 billion from $3.46 billion a
year earlier.
   Capital Cities-ABC also owns the ABC Radi Networks and 21 radio
stations, and publishes nine daily newspapers as well as weekly
newspapers, shopping guides, books and specialized periodicals.
