<DOCNO> AP891023-0261 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-23-89 1628EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-MarketReform     10-23 0725</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Market Reform,0752</SECOND>
<HEAD>Treasury, SEC Heads Talk to Congress This Week About Market Drop</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress hopes to get an inside look at how
the federal government handled the recent stock market plunge when
two key officials testify at separate hearings this week.
   On Wednesday, a House panel is slated to hear from Securities
and Exchange Commission Chairman Richard C. Breeden, in his first
congressional appearance since the market slid more than 190 points
on Friday, Oct. 13.
   The following day, Treasury Secretary Nicholas F. Brady is to
appear before the Senate Banking, Housing and Urban Affairs
Committee.
   The hearings were scheduled before the stock market's Oct. 13
decline, but that market drop and continuing concern about another
crash like the one in October 1987 are expected to overshadow both
sessions.
   Rep. Edward J. Markey, D-Mass., has told Breeden the stock
plunge ``adds new and compelling impetus to your testimony.''
   He asked Breeden and his staff to reconstruct what happened
during the selloff for the House Energy and Commerce Committee's
telecommunications and finance subcommittee, which Markey chairs.
   Legislation is pending in both houses of Congress that would
expand the SEC's powers to monitor the markets in several ways,
some of them opposed by various segments of the industry.
   The market reforms were proposed by the SEC after the stock
market crash in 1987.
   The ones that have sparked controversy include giving the SEC
authority to request reports on large securities and options trades
to track who's trading what to whom. Another would requires rules
for assessing the financial soundness of holding companies that are
the parent companies of broker dealers.
   In congressional testimony earlier this month, the heads of the
New York Stock Exchange and the American Stock Exchange supported
those changes, but the president of the National Association of
Securities Dealers, Joseph R. Hardiman, had some reservations.
   Edward I. O'Brien, president of Securities Industry Association,
said Monday that the trade group ``is opposed to both bills, as
written, but we are hopeful a compromise can be reached to achieve
the SEC's goals.''
   O'Brien is expected to spell out the SIA's position at
Wednesday's hearing before Markey's subcommittee. In addition to
O'Brien and Breeden, George S. Bissell, chairman of the
Boston-based Keystone Group of mutual funds also is to testify on
proposed market reforms.
   But the main topic is expected to be Wall Street's Friday the
13th. That's when the Dow Jones average of 30 industrial companies'
stocks, a key market indicator, plunged 190.58 points in the final
hours of trading.
   Many nervously compared the drop to October 1987 when Dow fell
more than 100 points on a Friday before plummeting a record 508
points in the Black Monday crash.
   This time around the market rebounded, closing up 88.12 points a
week ago Monday. Washington officials, headed by Brady, worked to
restore calm over the weekend while quietly conferring with the
exchanges, various government agencies and foreign trading partners.
   Some Democrats in Congress, however, say it's time to re-examine
changes recommended, but never implemented, by a presidential task
force headed by Brady before he took the Treasury post.
   ``Recent events have indicated the need to review the
recommendations of the Brady Commission,'' Sen. Donald W. Riegle,
D-Mich., chairman of the Senate Banking, Housing and Urban Affairs
Committee, said.
   Brady will be the sole witness before that committee Thursday.
   The Brady Commission proposed having one agency coordinate
regulation of all financial markets. The plan never was implemented
by the Reagan administration.
   Then and now, the SEC oversaw stock and options markets, the
Commodity Futures Trading Commission regulated futures markets and
the Federal Reserve set stock margins and supervised the payments
system among banks and brokerage houses.
   The market reforms proposed by Congress include giving the SEC
chairman the authority to halt trading for up to 24 hours in
emergencies. Currently, only the president can order such a
shutdown.
   But Breeden has said he does not want that power and does not
think it should be exercised.
   In written answers to questions during Senate confirmation for
the SEC post, Breeden said such authority would create too much
uncertainty about when the markets would close and for how long.
   ``In a crisis, this uncertainty and the related rumors
concerning its likelihood could have seriously adverse
consequences,'' he wrote.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
