<FIRST>r f AM-Qintex-Restructure     10-23 0533</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Qintex-Restructure,0555</SECOND>
<HEAD>Erstwhile Buyer of MGM-UA Announces Restructuring</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SYDNEY, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Resort-entertainment company Qintex
Australia Ltd., hurt by financial problems including the collapse
of its $1.5 billion deal to buy MGM-UA Communications Co.,
announced a broad restructuring Monday aimed at generating hundreds
of millions of dollars in savings and asset sales.
   The announcement came after the Australian Stock Exchange
suspended trading in Qintex because the company hadn't answered an
exchange question about its loans, investments and deposits to
Qintex Entertainment Inc., a U.S. affiliate.
   Los Angeles-based Qintex Entertainment filed for protection from
creditors late Thursday under Chapter 11 of the U.S. Bankruptcy
Code. The filing gives the company a repreive from creditors while
it works out a way to pay debts.
   Qintex Australia, a Sydney-based operator of resorts and
television stations, plans to sell its remaining 51 percent stake
in Mirage resorts in Australia and Hawaii, said Chairman
Christopher Skase.
   Skase said in a news release that the company also will
accelerate plans to sell its Adelaide television station in
southern Australia and two regional stations in Queensland.
   The sales are expected to generate more than 600 million
Australian dollars, or about $460 million, reduce interest costs
and eliminate other financial liabilities, Skase said.
   Qintex intends to retain a long-term management contract on the
resorts to generate fee income.
   In March, Qintex sold a 49 percent stake in the three Mirage
resorts to Nippon Shinpan Co. and Mitsui &amp; Co. for 433 million
Australian dollars, or about $333.4 million. At the time, Skase
said that new resorts were planned for southern California and
Florida.
   The announcement Monday didn't say if the Japanese companies
would acquire Qintex's remaining stake in the resorts.
   The planned corporate restructuring involves the merger of
Qintex Australia with Qintex Ltd., which owns 55 percent of Qintex
Australia. Skase said this move would ``significantly reduce
administrative costs.''
   Before trading was suspended, Qintex Australia shares had
plunged to 16 Australian cents from 33 cents Friday. The shares had
traded at around 1.50 Australian dollars in March, when Qintex
announced the plan to acquire MGM@UA.
   MGM@UA on Oct. 10 scrapped the agreement, saying the Australian
company failed to deliver a $50 million letter of credit that it
was supposed to supply as security in the transaction.
   Skase said Monday that ``group cash flow has been negatively
impacted by an excess of 200 million Australian dollars'' because
of four recent problems.
   The problems included what Skase characterized as an ``unlawful
termination'' by MGM@UA of the acquisition pact and ``consequential
impact on Qintex Entertainment,'' which was denied access to
banking facilities after the deal dissolved.
   High Australian interest rates also are hurting its business,
Skase said. He traced some of the troubles at the Australian Mirage
resorts to a strike by domestic airline pilots.
   The deferral of a settlement in a previously announced sale of
two Queensland regional TV stations also hurt, Skase said.
   Monday's announcement responded to the stock exchange's question
about Qintex's exposure to Qintex Entertainment, which is 43
percent-owned by the Australian company. The U.S. affiliate owes
Qintex Australia $38.1 million in unsecured loans.
   Qintex Australia said it has a further investment of $83.3
million in Qintex Entertainment shares.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
