<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     10-23 0470</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0487</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede BC-LONDON</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar drifted lower in lackluster trading
Monday as currency markets around the world awaited direction from
U.S. economic reports due this week.
   Gold prices declined. On the Commodity Exchange in New York,
gold for current delivery settled at $367 a troy ounce, down 30
cents from Friday's settlement. Republic National Bank of New York
quoted a 4 p.m. EDT gold bid of $366.25 an ounce, 25 cents lower
than Friday's late bid.
   Dealers at home and abroad reported that there recently has been
reluctance to establish significant new positions in dollars until
a clearer economic picture emerges.
   The reluctance has kept the dollar trading in a narrow range
against other major currencies.
   A report on orders for durable goods is due Tuesday from the
Commerce Department followed Thursday by the department's first
estimate of third-quarter growth in the gross national product, the
government's broadest measure of economic health.
   The dollar also has been weighed down by speculation that U.S.
interest rates might recede in the near future. Lower rates would
reduce returns on dollar-denominated investments and tend to lessen
demand for dollars.
   In Tokyo, the dollar rose to a closing 142.40 Japanese yen from
141.35 yen at Friday's close. Later, in London, the dollar ended
unchanged at 142.40 yen. It was quoted at 141.90 yen in New York,
down from 142.42 yen on Friday.
   In London, the British pound rose to $1.5945 from $1.5885 late
Friday. A pound cost $1.6030 at the end of New York trading,
compared with $1.5885 Friday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Friday's
quotes, included: 1.8470 West German marks, down from 1.8578;
1.6190 Swiss francs, down from 1.6285; 6.2740 French francs, down
from 6.3105; 1.1704 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1741; and
1,356.00 Italian lire, down from 1,367.00.
   Late rates for the dollar in Europe, compared with Friday's late
rates, included: 1.8550 West German marks, up from 1.8535; 1.6270
Swiss francs, up from 1.6255; 6.3050 French francs, up from 6.2962;
2.0965 Dutch guilders, down from 2.0973; 1,364.50 Italian lire, up
from 1,363.65; and, 1.1720 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1732.
   Gold bullion fell in what dealers called one of the slowest
sessions in months.
   In London, the metal fell to a late bid price of $365.75 a troy
ounce, down from $366.75 bid late Friday.
   In Zurich, Switzerland, gold declined to $365.60 bid from $366
bid late Friday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell 53 cents to close at $366.54.
   Silver bullion barely budged in quiet dealings and closed
unchanged. Silver was quoted in London at a late bid price of $5.09
a troy ounce, unchanged from Friday's late bid price. On New York's
Comex, silver bullion for current delivery settled at $5.089 an
ounce, the same as late Friday.
</TEXT>
