<FILEID>AP-NR-10-23-89 1754EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Iacocca-Japan     10-23 0400</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iacocca-Japan,0414</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iacocca Scores Sony Chairman's Criticism Of U.S. Business</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAPLES, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chrysler Corp. Chairman Lee A. Iacocca on
Monday criticized Japan for maintaining what he called a ``rigged
market'' that owed much of its business success to restrictive
national trade policies.
   Iacocca, speaking to more than 600 members of the Magazine
Publishers Association and the American Society of Magazine
Editors, specifically complained about critical remarks by Akio
Morita, chairman of Sony Corp., in the recently published book,
``The Japan That Can Say No.''
   ``I resent like hell being lectured on fairness by a guy who got
to be a multibillionaire in our market _ wide open to him _ while
we were being systematically shut out of his,'' Iacocca said.
   ``The guy even has the audacity to say that American car
companies won't even try to sell in Japan. Well, we try alright,
but it's tough. I send a Jeep to Japan and the price goes up 70
(percent) to 90 percent.
   ``Japan is a rigged market ... If Morita didn't know any more
about electronics than he does about fairness, he'd still be trying
to figure out how to put together a crystal radio set.''
   The book, written by Morita and Shintaro Ishihara, a former
novelist, Cabinet minister and candidate for prime minister,
examines Japan's relations with the United States and the two
nations' frequent trade frictions.
   In the book, Morita argues that the United States must regain
the competitiveness its industries once enjoyed and scolds American
managers' short-sightedness. Ishihara contends that Japan
constantly capitulates to U.S. pressure and he blames racial
prejudice as the basis of U.S.-Japan friction.
   Iacocca urged U.S. business to halt the present system that
emphasizes short-term planning and encourages hostile takeovers. He
also suggested readjusting the capital gains tax to raise the levy
on short-term investments.
   ``The whole country seems to be in a short-term feeding
frenzy,'' said Iacocca. ``We really are strange people. We load up
on oat bran in the morning so we'll live forever, and then act all
day long like there is no tomorrow.''
   Iacocca also called for year-round school terms to keep U.S.
students competitive with their peers in other nations.
   Afterward, First Lady Barbara Bush called on the audience to
concentrate on fighting illiteracy.
   She said the inability to read and write can lead to drug abuse
and contributes to the nation's social problems.
</TEXT>
