<FILEID>AP-NR-10-23-89 1825EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Earns-Oil     10-23 0628</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-Oil,0647</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mixed Bag for Oil Companies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Six major oil companies reported mixed quarterly results Monday,
mostly because of lower gasoline prices that hurt their refining
and marketing businesses.
   Earnings were down at Exxon Corp., Phillips Petroleum Co.,
Atlantic Richfield Co., and Ashland Oil Inc. reported a net loss.
Occidental Petroleum Corp. said earnings rose slightly. Amerada
Hess Corp., bucking the trend, said earnings more than doubled.
   Analysts said higher worldwide crude oil prices partly offset
weaker refining margins due to a fall in gasoline prices. Soaring
gasoline prices in the spring led to softer-than-expected demand
for gasoline during the peak summer travel season, hurting refining
and marketing profits for most companies.
   New York-based Exxon, the nation's largest oil company, said it
earned $1.1 billion or 87 cents a share in the third quarter ended
Sept. 30, down 9 percent from $1.2 billion or 93 cents a share a
year earlier. Revenue totaled $23.6 billion vs. $21.8 billion an 8
percent gain.
   For the first nine months, earnings fell 34.5 percent to $2.54
billion, or $1.99 a share, from $3.88 billion, or $2.89 a share.
The lower nine-month earnings reflected the company's provision for
the March 24 Alaska oil spill.
   Los Angeles-based Occidental earned $108 million or 39 cents a
share in the third quarter, up from $105 million or 38 cents a
share a year earlier. Revenue declined 2 percent to $4.8 billion
from $4.9 billion.
   Occidental's nine-month earnings dropped 14 percent to $255
million or 93 cents a share, compared with $295 million, or $1.23 a
share, in the same 1988 period. Revenue rose 6 percent to $15
billion from $14 billion.
   Phillips Petroleum's earnings dropped 60 percent to $87 million,
or 36 cents a share, from $215 million, or 89 cents a share a year
earlier. Revenue for the Bartlesville, Okla., company rose 7
percent to $3.1 billion from $2.9 billion.
   For the nine months, Phillips earned $474 million or $1.95 a
share, down 8 percent from $515 million or $2.17 a share a year
earlier. Revenue dropped 10 percent to $9.5 billion from $8.6
billion a year earlier.
   Los Angeles-based Arco earned $379 million, or $2.19 a share in
the quarter, down 3 percent from $391 million or $2.17 a share a
year earlier. Arco's revenue totaled $3.7 billion, down 20 percent
from $4.6 billion in the 1988 third quarter.
   Arco's nine-month earnings rose 33 percent to $1.6 billion, or
$8.87 share, compared with $1.2 billion, or $6.56 a share, a year
earlier, while revenue declined 13 percent to $12 billion from
$13.8 billion in 1988.
   Ashland Oil, reporting its fourth-quarter results, said it lost
$39.4 million or 71 cents a share due to previously announced
charges of $78 million. Revenue rose to $2.3 billion from $2.2
billion.
   For the fiscal year, Ashland's earnings totaled $86.2 million or
$1.55 a share, down from $224 million or $4.01 a share a year
earlier. Revenue grew about 4 percent to $8.5 billion from $8.2
billion as year ago.
   New York-based Amerada Hess's third-quarter earnings jumped to
$51.8 million, or 64 cents a share, from $15.8 million, or 20 cents
a share, reflecting much stronger refining and marketing segments
that bucked the general trend in the industry. The company also
benefited from unused tax credits of years past.
   The third-quarter results included a charge of $30 million,
associated with expenses from a refinery shutdown in the Virgin
Islands during Hurricane Hugo.
   Amerada Hess's third-quarter revenue rose to $1.2 billion, up 28
percent from $925 million in the same 1988 period.
   Amerada Hess' nine-month earnings jumped to $406 million, or
$4.99 a share, from $57.9 million, or 71 cents a share. Revenue
totaled $4 billion, up 35 percent from $3.1 billion in 1988.
</TEXT>
