<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     10-23 0236</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0247</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Futures Prices Decline</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures prices fell in relatively light
trading Monday led by a sharp fall in heating oil prices.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the November contract for
domestic heating oil finished 2.02 cents lower at 58.42 cents a
gallon and the contract for delivery in December closed at 58.84 a
gallon, down 2 cents.
   Wholesale unleaded gasoline for November delivery ended 1.03
cents lower at 53.48 cents a gallon, while the December contract
declined 1.10 cents to settled at 52.78 cents a gallon.
   The December contract for West Texas Intermediate, the U.S.
benchmark grade of crude oil, lost 39 cents to close at $19.76 a
42-gallon barrel. January crude fell 36 cents to $19.59 a barrel
and February shed 31 cents to close at $19.44 a barrel.
   Analysts said volume remained light to moderate throughout the
session.
   An explosion and fire at Phillips Petroleum Co.'s Houston
chemical complex boosted prices only briefly, traders said.
   ``It lifted gasoline prices about 30 points but they came back
off,'' said Ann Shannon, trader at Elders Futures Inc. ``It was a
petrochemicals plant and shouldn't affect the market.''
   Energy brokers said the drop in heating oil was not unexpected,
given its strength in relation to crude oil and other market
segments.
   ``Heating oil got its just desserts,'' said Greg Dreis, energy
broker with Merrill Lynch Energy Futures.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
