<FIRST>u f AM-UAL 1stLd-Writethru f0126 10-23 0651</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UAL, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0126,0670</SECOND>
<HEAD>UAL Board Meets As Buyout Group Explores New Bid</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with UAL statement; picks up 3rd
graf pvs bg'ng, Spokespersons for ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   UAL Corp. said Monday it will continue exploring
ways to get the best deal for its shareholders and indicated it may
not accept anything less than the $6.75 billion offered by a
labor-management group which failed to get financing for a buyout.
   In a vague statement, the parent of United Airlines said it
considered the failed bid's price of $300 a share to be ``an
attractive offer'' and ``in the best interests of shareholders.''
   ``Consistent with the effort to maximize shareholder value, the
board will continue to explore all strategic and financial
alternatives available to the company,'' UAL said.
   ``However, the board has concluded that, at this time, the
welfare of the company, its shareholders, its employees and the
broader public served by the airline can best be enhanced by
continued development of UAL as a strong, viable, independent
company.''
   The company issued the statement late in the day after a special
board meeting had ended.
   The statement also contained an ambiguous statement from UAL
Chairman Stephen Wolf, who had joined with the company's 7,000
pilots in leading the buyout group.
   Wolf said the cooperative effort had helped management and the
pilots to forge a ``substantially improved working relationship.''
But he made no mention in the statement of the group's recent
efforts to revise its offer.
   Wolf said he ``hopes that all 70,000 United employees can now
turn their full attention to operating the best airline in the
world.''
   Published reports had indicated the battered buyout group would
bring a new proposal to the board Monday while others said the
group wanted to secure financing before putting another offer on
the table.
   Spokespersons for United's parent UAL, the Air Line Pilots
Association and the flight attendants all declined comment on the
status of their efforts to put together another bid.
   A $300-a-share bid valued at $6.75 billion collapsed Oct. 13
when key banks refused to provide financing.
   The Wall Street Journal reported that the labor-managment group
was considering a revised offer that would give employees a
majority stake in UAL and leave some stock in public hands.
   The Journal said the group was seeking reactions to the new
deal, valued at $225 to $240 a share, or about $5.09 billion.
   The newspaper said the group did not plan to formally present
the scheme at the UAL board meeting but would seek binding
commitments from banks covering all the money needed to finance the
buyout before making a formal proposal.
   Meanwhile, the Chicago Sun-Times and Chicago Tribune reported
that the employee-management group intended to submit a revised
proposal to the UAL board Monday.
   The offer for Chicago-based UAL will be in the range of $220 to
$250 a share, the newspapers said, quoting unidentified sources.
   The Association of Flight Attendants told its members in a
recorded phone-in message that any revised proposal ``will
obviously be considerably lower'' than the unsuccessful deal.
   The failure of the earlier bid helped trigger a 190-point plunge
in the Dow Jones industrial average on Oct. 13 and precipitated a
40 percent drop in UAL's stock price. UAL stock closed last Friday
at $168.50 a share.
   But the stock rebounded Monday morning as the board meeting
began and was trading at $182 at midday on the New York Stock
Exchange.
   The flight attendants joined the pilots and United's top
management in the bid on Thursday.
   The original deal would have given management and labor an 85
percent stake in UAL under the largest employee buyout in corporate
history. British Airways PLC, which pulled out of the buyout group
on Friday, would have taken a 15 percent ownership stake in return
for a $750 million investment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
