<FILEID>AP-NR-10-23-89 2112EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-TimeWarner     10-23 0392</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Time Warner,0407</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reports Loss for Third Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Time Warner Inc. said Monday it lost $176
million in the third quarter due to huge expenses associated with
its acquisition of a controlling interest in Warner Communications
Inc.
   The loss amounted to $2.88 per share on revenue of $2.2 billion.
   A year ago, Time alone earned $81 million, or $1.42 a share, on
revenue of $1.13 billion.
   Those figures are not directly comparable, however, with the
latest results reflecting Time's acquisition in late July of 100
million shares of Warner stock, boosting its stake in Warner to
59.3 percent. The latest results also reflect a pro-rated share of
Warner's earnings for August and September.
   For the first nine months of the year, the newly configured
entertainment and media giant known now as Time Warner lost $33
million, or 56 cents per share, on revenue of $4.5 billion.
   Time alone earned $231 million, or $4 a share, on revenue of
$3.3 billion a year ago.
   The Time Warner loss in the latest quarter reflects a jump in
interest expense to $451 million from $25 million for Time alone in
1988, as well as depreciation and amortization charges of $155
million compared with $55 million a year earlier.
   The company said that for purposes of discussion, it computed
earnings before interest, taxes, depreciation and amortization for
the new company.
   Under that method, it said its pro-forma earnings amounted to
$526 million for the quarter, up from $242 million a year earlier,
and to $1.52 billion for the nine months, up from $999 million.
   Magazine division earnings on a pro-forma basis fell to $41
million in the latest quarter from $47 million a year earlier, as
advertising revenues were flat.
   The filmed entertainment division had pro-forma earnings of $103
million in the quarter in contrast to a loss of $123 million last
year, reflecting the success of ``Batman'' and ``Lethal Weapon II.''
   On the same pro-forma basis, Time Warner's recorded music and
music publishing division earned $108 million, up from $92 million
a year earlier, and cable division earnings rocketed to $166
million from $94 million.
   Time Warner expects to complete the acquisition of the remaining
shares of Warner stock later this year, paying for a package that
includes preferred stock and Warner's holdings in a subsidiary of
Chris-Craft Industries Inc.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
