<DOCNO> AP891023-0271 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-23-89 2121EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Boeing     10-23 0540</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Boeing,0561</SECOND>
<HEAD>Boeing Chairman: No Increase in Money to Settle Strike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM KLASS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Boeing Co. will not offer any more money to
settle a three-week strike by production workers despite mounting
and ``irreparable'' losses, Chairman Frank Shrontz told reporters
Monday.
   Earlier Monday, Tom Baker, president of District Lodge 751 of
the International Association of Machinists and Aerospace Workers,
said the strike could not be settled without a bigger money offer.
   The separate news conferences, including the first by Shrontz in
the dispute, appeared to mark a hardening of positions in the 20th
day of a walkout at the world's largest commercial airplane
manufacturer.
   Four hours of talks Wednesday were the first since union members
voted by an 85 percent margin to strike rather than accept the
company's a three-year offer.
   That offer included annual pay increases of 4 percent, 3 percent
and 3 percent; bonuses of 8 percent of gross pay in the first year
and 3 percent in the second; cost-of-living increases to cover
inflation; a 20 percent reduction in mandatory overtime; and higher
benefits.
   No further talks were scheduled. The Machinists represent 57,800
Boeing workers nationwide, including 43,300 in the local district,
12,000 in Wichita, Kan., 1,700 in Portland, Ore., and a few hundred
at scattered sites in other states.
   At Wichita, a non-union Boeing worker and two others were
released on bond after being arrested early Saturday in the firing
of a shotgun at the union's strike headquarters. Pellets hit the
building, parked cars and a sign, but no one was injured. Sedgwick
County sheriff's deputies said charges could be filed within 14
days.
   Picketing has been generally quiet in the Seattle area.
   The last paychecks for work done before the walkout were mailed
by Boeing last week. The first union strike payments of a flat $100
per week per member are set for distribution Thursday.
   Baker said union members were adamant about getting a bigger
financial package, with less than 1 percent crossing picket lines
and fewer total crossing than in the last Boeing strike, in 1977.
   At his news conference, Shrontz maintained the package was the
best in recent U.S. industrial history and said any boost would
jeopardize Boeing's competitive position.
   ``We're not prepared to increase the offer,'' Shrontz said.
   Shrontz said he hoped the dispute would not jeopardize Boeing's
long-term labor relations, generally regarded as among the best in
the aerospace industry.
   ``I don't think I've drawn a line that is unreasonable,'' he
said.
   Contacted by telephone after Shrontz spoke, Baker said he didn't
consider that the company's last word.
   ``They have their own timing on when they want to settle the
strike,'' the union leader said, adding that he did not know what
that timetable might be.
   Shrontz said Boeing already faced unspecified losses, including
sales, on which he gave no figures or other indication of magnitude.
   ``We certainly are not ignoring this strike. We certainly want
to see it settled as soon as possible,'' Shrontz said. ``I think
our losses are irreparable already.''
   Meanwhile, contract talks with Boeing's second-largest union,
the Seattle Professional Engineering Employees Association, were
set to resume Tuesday and continue through the week, said Robbi
Miner of the unaffiliated union.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
